<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Rise Sharply / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices rose sharply Thursday -- marking the  
first gains in four days -- on economic news that lessened fears of 
rising inflation and raised confidence that the Federal Reserve 
Board won't increase interest rates next week. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 1 3/32  
point, or $10.94 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves 
in the opposite direction, fell to 6.04 percent from 6.12 percent 
late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Gross Domestic Product, which tracks domestic economic  
growth and is a key index for gauging inflation, slowed to 1.6 
percent growth in the second quarter, the slowest growth rate since 
1995. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Reserve has increased interest rates twice this year  
in an effort to slow the economy and stave off inflation. An 
overheated economy lowers unemployment and pushes up prices. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, bonds rose on news of a radiation leak at a  
Japanese power plant, which caused some investors to pull funds out 
of Japanese securities and place them in U.S.-backed bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
were up 1/8 to 3/16 point, while intermediate maturities rose 11/32 
to 5/8 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading Thursday, yields on three-month Treasury bills  
rose to 4.84 percent, as the discount rose 0.02 from Wednesday to 
4.71 percent. Six-month yields rose to 4.96 percent as the discount 
rose 0.01 percentage point to 4.77 percent. One-year yields fell to 
5.17 percent as the discount fell 0.04 percentage point to 4.91 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 5.75 percent from 5.25 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds rose 1/4 to 112 15/32. The average yield to 
maturity of the index fell to 5.89 percent from 5.91 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
