<DOCNO> APW19990930.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 09:00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Noon EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Sept. 30, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Full Probe Sought on Korea Killings  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Saying ``the U.S. government can no  
longer deny its responsibility,'' South Koreans who say they 
survived a U.S. Army machine-gunning of hundreds of refugees in the 
Korean War demanded a formal investigation today into what happened 
beneath the No Gun Ri railroad bridge in July 1950. The Pentagon 
said any ``compelling new evidence'' would cause it to look again 
at the allegations. The Associated Press reported yesterday that a 
dozen Army veterans, in AP interviews, corroborated the core of the 
Koreans' account of the killings. 

</P>
<P>
	Leak Hits Japan Uranium Plant  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- A leak at a uranium-processing plant in central  
Japan today sent radiation levels skyrocketing and led to the 
hospitalization of three workers, two in critical condition. Hiromu 
Nonaka, the top government spokesman, called the accident 
``unprecedented,'' and officials said no previous Japanese accident 
had left workers so seriously injured. About 150 people were 
evacuated from the area around the plant in the town of Tokaimura, 
70 miles northeast of Tokyo. 

</P>
<P>
	Bradley Outraises Gore in Quarter  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bill Bradley, his Democratic presidential  
campaign surging, raised more money than Vice President Al Gore 
over the last three months, and has more money in the bank heading 
into the final quarter of the year. Bradley raised an estimated 
$6.7 million from July to September, spokeswoman Anita Dunn said 
today. Gore raised around $6.5 million during the same period, 
according to senior advisers. By spending less than $4.2 million 
during the last three months, Bradley wound up with more than $10 
million in the bank as of today. Gore aides said the vice president 
would have between $9.5 million and $10 million. 

</P>
<P>
	Sky Clears Over North Carolina  
</P>
<P>
	TARBORO, N.C. (AP) -- The sky cleared over eastern North Carolina  
today after a last soaking rainfall rang the curtain down on one of 
the wettest months ever for the region devastated by Hurricane 
Floyd's floodwaters. An inch of rain fell overnight, adding to the 
misery inflicted by 7 inches from Tropical Storm Dennis in early 
September, 20 inches of rain during Floyd two weeks ago, and up to 
8 inches of rain earlier this week. In Virginia, wind gusts up to 
60 mph blew down trees and power lines from remote mountain regions 
to the Washington suburbs. 

</P>
<P>
	Timor Peacekeepers May Cross Border  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, East Timor (AP) -- Amid reports of a militia buildup in  
West Timor, Australia said today that peacekeepers in East Timor 
are authorized to cross the border into the Indonesian territory if 
engaged in a battle with militiamen. Indonesia warned peacekeepers 
against entering West Timor, saying such action could lead to a 
clash between the Australian-led mission and Indonesian soldiers. 
Militiamen went on a rampage following an Aug. 30 independence 
vote, forcing hundreds of thousands of East Timorese to flee to 
West Timor, which remains part of Indonesia. 

</P>
<P>
	Greyhound To Install Bus Lifts  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Greyhound Lines Inc. reached an agreement with  
the Justice Department today under which the bus company will begin 
phasing in lift-equipped buses for disabled passengers two years 
before it is required to have them. The Justice Department said the 
out-of-court agreement resolves a number of complaints that 
Greyhound drivers and employees had violated the Americans with 
Disabilities Act. The complaints involved refusal to aid a disabled 
person in boarding a bus and injuries that occurred when disabled 
riders were carried on or off buses. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Rises 59; Nasdaq Gains 11  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before noon EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 59.52 points at 10,273.00. Advancers on the New York Stock 
Exchange led decliners 1,524-1,129. The Nasdaq composite index was 
up 11.01 at 2,741.28. 

</P>
<P>
	Haas Upsets Agassi in Three Sets  
</P>
<P>
	MUNICH, Germany (AP) -- Andre Agassi, rusty in his first match  
since winning the U.S. Open nearly three weeks ago, was beaten in 
three sets today by Tommy Haas at the $6.7 million Grand Slam Cup. 
Agassi sleep-walked through the first set, picked up his game in 
the second, but appeared to run out of steam in the third as the 
21-year-old German won 6-0, 6-7 (2-7), 6-4. Haas picked up $325,000 
for reaching the semifinals of the richest tournament in the world. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
