<DOCNO> APW19990930.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 15:20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Raises $56M, Banks $37M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Continuing to financially overwhelm both  
Republicans and Democrats, GOP presidential front-runner George W. 
Bush reported raising more than $56 million through the end of 
September, winding up with a campaign bank balance of $37 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bush campaign said Thursday that it had raised $19 million  
between July and September. That was more money than the two 
Democratic contenders, Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill 
Bradley, raised between them. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley, in fact, outraised Gore for the quarter, $6.7 million  
to $6.5 million. Since the beginning of the year, Gore has 
outraised Bradley, $24 million to $18.4 million. But Gore also has 
spent more money. At the end of September, Bradley had more than 
$10 million in the bank while Gore had between $9.5 million and $10 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush continues to outpace his Republican opponents as well. Sen.  
John McCain, R-Ariz., was a distant second, raising $3 million 
during the last three months and bringing his total to $9.3 
million, which includes $2 million transferred from his Senate 
campaign account. Gary Bauer, Patrick Buchanan, Elizabeth Dole, 
Steve Forbes and Orrin Hatch each raised more than $1 million 
between July and September. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain had $2 million in his campaign bank account as of Sept.  
30; Forbes had $1.4 million. 
</P>
<P>
	With $37 million in the bank, Bush not only has enough money to  
wage energetic campaigns in the early caucus and primary states, 
but to set up full-scale operations elsewhere, such as in 
California, New York and the Midwestern states that will be key 
battlegrounds in the general election. 
</P>
<P>
	``Candidates develop full organizations in Iowa, New Hampshire  
and a few other states,'' said Anthony Corrado, a professor of 
government at Colby College in Waterville, Maine. ``The rest of the 
campaign is tarmac to tarmac, where they look for free TV time. The 
difference is he's going to be able to set up organizations in any 
of those key states that are essential to the general election.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush reported receiving more than 135,000 contributions en route  
to his record-setting haul. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am humbled and honored that so many Americans are helping me  
spread my message of improving schools to leave no child behind, 
strengthening our military to keep the peace, and ushering in an 
era of responsibility in America,'' Bush said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bush campaign also released 41 more names of its top  
fund-raisers, known as the Pioneers, each of whom have raised at 
least $100,000. The list included Indianapolis Mayor Stephen 
Goldsmith, a leader of Bush's domestic policy team, and former 
Massachusetts Gov. William Weld. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes, who is largely financing his own campaign, raised $1.4  
million over the last three months, bringing his total to $4.2 
million through Sept. 30. In addition, Forbes spent around $15 
million from his own pocket. 
</P>
<P>
	``Establishment financial support might be tight-fisted, but  
grassroots support is free flowing, as our lists of endorsements 
and escalating poll numbers reflect,'' Forbes spokeswoman Juleanna 
Glover Weiss said. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Bush and Forbes are not accepting federal funds to help  
fund their presidential campaigns. But the other candidates are 
eligible for millions of dollars in financial help from the 
government after Jan. 1. Both McCain and Bauer, for example, expect 
to receive more than $3 million in taxpayer funds apiece based on 
what they have raised so far. The federal government matches the 
first $250 of each individual contribution in exchange for 
candidates agreeing to limit their spending. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are well along in our goal of raising $15-$20 million by  
the end of 1999,'' McCain campaign manager Rick Davis said. ``Our 
success has been fueled by tens of thousands of contributors who 
share John McCain's desire for leadership and independent 
conservative reform.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bauer campaign manager Frank Cannon noted the campaign has  
received contributions from more than 100,000 individuals. ``Beyond 
the front-runner, we have the broadest financial base in the 
Republican field,'' Cannon said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's fund-raising success has some supporters beginning to  
talk about whether the Texas governor should give up federal 
funding for the general election as well, allowing him to raise and 
spend as much as he wants. After the national party conventions, 
the Republican and Democratic presidential nominees will receive 
around $66 million for the fall campaigns in exchange for not 
raising any private funds, except to cover legal and accounting 
costs. 
</P>
<P>
	``That discussion is out there,'' said a Republican close to the  
Bush campaign, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``It is 
something that will be looked at down the road.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just as Bush will have more money to spend for the primaries  
than he would have if he accepted federal funds, the campaign will 
have to decide whether he can raise more than the $66 million he 
would receive from the federal government if he is the GOP nominee. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's certainly raising money at a pace that makes forgoing the  
public money a definite option,'' Corrado said. ``The question is 
whether the public will see this as a defiance of the rules and 
view it poorly. To date, we have no evidence that the public will 
use its votes to penalize a candidate who chooses not to take 
public money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said the campaign has not  
discussed its fund-raising strategy for the general election. 
``Right now, we are focusing on raising money for the primary and 
winning the nomination,'' she said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
