<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 08:50:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bombs Found at N. Hampshire Stores </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- An unexploded bomb was found at a  
home-improvement store that is part of a chain that was hit by two 
bombings last week. 
</P>
<P>
	A bomb at a Lowe's Home Improvement Warehouse in Asheboro  
slightly injured several employees and customers Sept. 22. Minutes 
later, a customer was seriously injured in the bombing of a Lowe's 
50 miles away in Salisbury. 
</P>
<P>
	A third device was found at a Concord store Tuesday afternoon,  
minutes after the arrival of Bob Tillman, chairman and chief 
executive of the national chain. 
</P>
<P>
	Earl Woodham, spokesman for the federal Bureau of Alcohol  
Tobacco and Firearms, said more lab tests are being conducted on 
the bomb, but it was clearly an explosive designed to harm people. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowe's officials and the ATF declined to comment on the  
investigation. But the News &AMP; Record of Greensboro reported today 
that investigators are considering two theories: that the bombings 
were in retaliation for a fatal accident earlier this year at a 
race car track sponsored by Lowe's, or were connected to efforts to 
unionize Lowe's workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper quoted a source as saying that the chain's  
headquarters received a call from a purported relative of one of 
the spectators killed or injured in a May 1 crash at Lowe's Motor 
Speedway in Concord. The caller complained that the chain hadn't 
done enough for the victims. 
</P>
<P>
	Three spectators were killed and eight injured when debris from  
a wrecked Indy Racing League car flew into the stands. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowe's, based in North Wilkesboro, is the corporate sponsor of  
the track, which is owned by Concord-based Speedway Motorsports 
Inc. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 11:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.-Russia Relationship Said Vital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former Russian Prime Minister Viktor  
Chernomyrdin said today concern over alleged Russian corruption and 
money laundering through a U.S. bank must not overshadow the vital 
relationship between the two nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Chernomyrdin, speaking to reporters during a visit to the United  
States, acknowledged that Russia has a corruption problem. However, 
he said, ``It would be premature and unfair to think that all 
Russian business is corrupt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chernomyrdin, speaking through an interpreter, said U.S.-Russian  
relations have been thrown into question by the allegations 
concerning the Bank of New York, a development he called ``very 
dangerous both for the peoples of our two countries and for the 
whole world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The former prime minister, who jointly headed a commission with  
Vice President Al Gore on bilateral ties, expressed anger at 
suggestions that Gore should be held responsible for the alleged 
misdeeds because of his strong support for U.S. aid to Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	Corruption ``is our responsibility,'' he said. ``What does it  
have to do with Gore, what does it have to do with the U.S. 
government?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chernomyrdin said he did not meet with Gore during his visit  
this week to Washington and New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore has come under fire from Republicans for his close  
relationship with Russian leaders and his hands-on role in 
U.S.-Russian diplomacy. Republican leaders have recently criticized 
the administration's support for aid to Russia, as federal 
investigators have widened their inquiry into allegations that 
Russian companies and individuals -- including organized-crime 
figures-- laundered billions of dollars through the Bank of New 
York. 
</P>
<P>
	Chernomyrdin spoke as Russian authorities announced their first  
banking investigation since those allegations surfaced last month. 
The suspected culprit is one of Russia's smallest and most obscure 
banks. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors are examining Moscow's Flamingo Bank, which  
allegedly had $430,000 and the equivalent of another $120,000 in 
rubles without proper documentation, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Those sums are minuscule compared to the allegations that  
Russian businesses and organized crime groups may have laundered 
billions of dollars through the Bank of New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia has agreed to cooperate with U.S. investigators, though  
it seemed reluctant to launch its own probe. But now, the 
Prosecutor General's office says it intends to closely scrutinize 
Russian banks. 
</P>
<P>
	``In connection with the scandal we are investigating all  
suspicious deals,'' the chief investigator with the prosecutor's 
office, Vladimir Minayev, was quoted as saying by the Kommersant 
daily. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Russian prosecutors have given no indication that  
Flamingo Bank had dealings with the Bank of New York or any other 
American bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Flamingo, with only one branch and no private depositors, has  
never previously attracted public notice of any sort. 
</P>
<P>
	Flamingo has a license that allows it to deal with foreign  
currencies, said a Flamingo bank official who declined to give her 
name. The bank refused to discuss details of the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Many legitimate Russian businesses conceal part of their assets  
or try to move them abroad to avoid paying taxes in Russia. The 
practice is widespread, and could account for some of the funds 
that were allegedly funneled through the Bank of New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of New York scandal has been described as potentially  
one of the largest money-laundering cases ever uncovered in the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's inquiry -- focusing on a small bank and a small amount  
of money -- prompted suggestions that the government wants to make a 
scapegoat of Flamingo and give the appearance it is thoroughly 
investigating alleged money laundering. 
</P>
<P>
	``Flamingo Bank will answer for the Bank of New York,''  
Kommersant said. 
</P>
<P>
	Most crime and corruption scandals in Russia over the past few  
years have fizzled out, with hardly anybody taken to court. As a 
result, Russian law enforcement agencies are widely seen as either 
a feeble or corrupt. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russian government played down the money laundering scandal  
for weeks after it broke this summer. But officials have 
acknowledged that the scandal is hurting the country's reputation 
and could hurt Russia's chances for receiving new loans from the 
International Monetary Fund. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF has toughened its conditions for the release of further  
loans following the scandal. The fund is demanding that Russia make 
its finances more transparent, and that the Russian Central Bank 
allow international auditors to examine its management of gold and 
currency reserves, First Deputy Prime Minister Viktor Khristenko 
told the daily Segodnya. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
