<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thais Take Hope From Output Figures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Thailand's strong manufacturing  
performance in August confirms that the economy is on track to 
recovery despite recent softness in the currency, economists said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Manufacturing production jumped 17.7 percent in August compared  
with the same period last year, said Suchada Kirakul, deputy 
director of the Bank of Thailand's economic research department. 
</P>
<P>
	``Thailand's economy in general is showing clear signs of  
recovery,'' she said at a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists were surprised last week by data from Thailand's  
economic planning agency which showed second-quarter gross domestic 
product growth was a lower-than-expected 3.5 percent. GDP is the 
measure of all goods and services produced in a country. 
</P>
<P>
	The data indicated manufacturing production was flat in the  
April-to-June period compared with the previous quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the Bank of Thailand figures released Thursday told a  
different story. 
</P>
<P>
	Output not only increased over the same period the year before --  
when manufacturing had almost ground to a halt -- but also was up on 
July, Sriyan Pieterz, head of research at SG Asia Credit in 
Bangkok, told Dow Jones Newswires. 
</P>
<P>
	Month-on-month growth in output shows manufacturers are meeting  
new demand, and not just restocking inventories which declined 
during Thailand's deep two-year recession, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The output resurgence is mainly to feed export growth,  
economists believe. Thailand's exports grew by 15 percent 
year-on-year in August, compared with a 7.2 percent increase in 
July. 
</P>
<P>
	The central bank expects the economy, as measured by GDP, to  
grow by 3 percent to 4 percent this year, while many economists say 
a higher figure is likely given the strong manufacturing and export 
numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	There also seemed to be a recovery in consumer demand, JP Morgan  
regional economist David Fernandez told Dow Jones Newswires. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of Thailand's composite consumption index for August  
was up 2.4 percent over the previous month to 99.5 points, 
reflecting improvements in sales of motorcycles, liquor and 
value-added tax receipts. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we're seeing is a consumption recovery,'' said SG Asia  
Credit's Pieterz. 
</P>
<P>
	But most economists agree exports are the real engine behind  
Thailand's growth, and any downturn in Japanese or U.S. demand 
could stifle economic recovery. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
