<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 20:00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Greenspan Nixes Free Trade-Job Link </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said  
Thursday there are countless economic arguments in support of free 
trade but job creation is not one of them. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan, returning to a theme he has sounded several times  
this year, mounted a strong defense for the benefits the U.S. 
economy has enjoyed from reducing trade barriers. But he said he 
regretted that supporters have tried to link trade policies with 
job creation. 
</P>
<P>
	``We too often try to promote free trade on the mistaken ground  
that it will create jobs,'' Greenspan said in a speech prepared for 
a meeting of business executives in Minneapolis. Copies of the 
speech were distributed here. 
</P>
<P>
	Trade can influence the type of jobs that an economy can create,  
but not the overall number, Greenspan said. By opening up a country 
to competition, he said, free trade enhances productivity by 
forcing industry into more productive fields to the benefit of 
workers, who see their salaries increase. 
</P>
<P>
	But the overall number of jobs is influenced my other economic  
factors, Greenspan said, putting forth an argument made by a large 
number of economists. They contend that overall employment is 
influenced much more by factors such as interest rate policies, 
that can boost or depress consumer demand. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is difficult to find credible evidence that trade has  
affected the level of employment in this country over the long 
run,'' Greenspan said. ``Indeed, we are currently experiencing the 
widest trade deficit in history with a level of unemployment close 
to record lows.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan's remarks represented the latest in a series of  
speeches he has given this year seeking to counter what he views as 
rising protectionist sentiments as America's trade deficit has 
soared over the past two years. A global financial crisis has cut 
sharply into U.S. export markets and increased the flow of low-cost 
imports into this country. 
</P>
<P>
	``The campaign to expand free trade is never won,'' Greenspan  
said. ``Legislation to further lower trade barriers ... is becoming 
increasingly difficult to pass in Congress.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The United States will serve as hosts this December to a meeting  
in Seattle of the 134-nation World Trade Organization, where a new 
round of global trade liberalization talks will be launched. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the U.S. delegation will attend the session without the  
congressional authorization it needs to complete the negotiations 
because President Clinton has been unable in five years to get the 
measure through Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan said he also was concerned that as formal trade  
barriers were being reduced, more countries were resorting to other 
forms of protectionism such as raising tariffs through findings 
that goods were being ``dumped'' at unfairly low prices. 
</P>
<P>
	``While these forms of protection have often been imposed under  
the label of promoting fair trade, oftentimes they are just simple 
guises for inhibiting competition,'' Greenspan said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration has supported a number of dumping  
cases filed in recent months by the steel industry, which argued 
they were losing millions of dollars in sales because of a flood of 
cheap imports into the country as a result of the Asian financial 
crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan said the U.S. economy has benefited greatly from  
lowering trade barriers, which has increased competition and forced 
American businesses into more innovative fields paying higher wages 
for workers. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said the transition from obsolete technologies to newer  
technologies does represent lost jobs for workers through no fault 
of their own. He urged support for the transition through job 
training programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be a great tragedy were we to stop the wheels of  
progress because of an incapacity to assist the victims of 
progress,'' Greenspan said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
