<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religious Bias Bill Introduced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The devout Christian trucker is forced to  
drive on a Sunday. The Muslim woman is barred from wearing a head 
covering to work. The observant Jew is scheduled for duty on the 
Sabbath. 
</P>
<P>
	Such cases were cited by five senators Wednesday as proof that  
Congress should clarify a federal law protecting workers' religious 
practices. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are liberties upon which our country was founded,'' said  
Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	Joining Kerry in sponsoring the bill were Republican Sens. Sam  
Brownback of Kansas and Tim Hutchinson of Arkansas and Democratic 
Sens. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut and Barbara Mikulski of 
Maryland. 
</P>
<P>
	They said their bill would only clarify a provision in the 1972  
amendments to the 1964 Civil Rights Act that require an employer to 
``reasonably accommodate'' a worker's religious practice or 
observance unless it imposes an ``undue hardship'' on the employer. 
Kerry said courts have interpreted the law so that virtually any 
accommodation can be considered an undue hardship. 
</P>
<P>
	The Equal Employment Opportunity Commission would be charged  
with enforcing the new law. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard T. Foltin, a lawyer for the American Jewish Committee,  
said roughly 200 complaints against businesses for failing to 
accommodate religious practices are filed yearly with the EEOC and 
others are filed with state human rights agencies. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
