<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Execs More Bullish on 4th Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- American executives are bullish about the final  
three months of 1999, according to a Dun &AMP; Bradstreet survey that 
reports the first gain in the outlook for exports since the Asian 
financial crisis arose in mid-1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey of approximately 3,000 executives, conducted in  
August, had especially strong results in its indexes measuring 
sentiment about exports, sales, profits and employment. 
</P>
<P>
	A boost in hiring plans might further tighten labor markets at a  
time when the unemployment rate is at a 29-year low of 4.2 percent, 
possibly leading to significant wage increases, the 
business-information company said. 
</P>
<P>
	But executives surveyed said they did not expect wage pressures  
to significantly increase inflation. Two-thirds of those responding 
said they expected prices in the fourth quarter either to be the 
same as, or lower than, they were a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey reported 66 percent of the executives expect sales to  
rise in the fourth quarter, 58 percent expect higher profits and 38 
percent plan to hire additional workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The export index surged 19 points from its all-time low of 12 in  
the last quarterly survey in June, rising to 31. That also 
represents a gain of 6 points from a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Other optimism indexes also were up substantially from the  
previous quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our survey indicates that during the last quarter of the  
millennium U.S. businesses expect to turn in very strong results,'' 
said David T. Kresge, chief economist for Dun &AMP; Bradstreet. ``For 
the first time in nearly two years, they see foreign demand for 
U.S. goods picking up significantly, adding to the continued 
strength in domestic spending.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Few executives fear Year 2000 computer problems, Kresge said.  
</P>
<P>
	``Only 10 to 15 percent of respondents expect Y2K to have any  
impact at all on sales, investments, or inventories in the fourth 
quarter. And, among those who think that Y2K will have any effect, 
the great majority expect it to have a positive, rather than a 
negative, influence,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey, which was conducted by telephone, has a margin of  
error of less than 2 percentage points. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
