<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Douglas May Return to Eagles Lineup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA, Pa. (AP) -- The Philadelphia Eagles, who could use  
some help, any help, might have defensive end Hugh Douglas when 
they play Sunday against the New York Giants. 
</P>
<P>
	Douglas suffered a sprained ligament in his left knee in Week 2  
and was expected to miss four to six weeks, but has astounded his 
team by returning to practice. Douglas worked out in full pads on 
Thursday and said his status is now ``day-to-day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't say that right now I'm ready to play,'' said Douglas.  
``I've got to be smart about it. I've got the kind of injury that, 
if I try to play on it, I may prolong it and make it worse. I'm 
still day to day. The good thing is I'm a lot further along than 
they thought I'd be on it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I proved that I could get out there and practice,'' Douglas  
said. ``It's a step. I'm doing something that I wasn't even 
supposed to do at this point. I felt pretty good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Douglas suffered a partially torn medial collateral ligament in  
after his left knee collided with the helmet of teammate Mike 
Mamula in the second quarter of the Sept. 19 game against Tampa 
Bay. Douglas, the Eagles' best defensive player, had two sacks in 
two games. 
</P>
<P>
	He missed last week's game against Buffalo, a 26-0 defeat. If he  
plays Sunday, it will probably only be in obvious passing 
situations. 
</P>
<P>
	If nothing else, his return to the practice field gives the  
Eagles some life. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's the heart and soul of this defense,'' said cornerback  
Troy Vincent. 
</P>
<P>
	Douglas is aching to play.  
</P>
<P>
	``More than anything, it's a matter of building that confidence  
back up and going out and playing,'' he said. ``I'm not in any kind 
of pain. I've been trying to simulate playing football, going out 
there in certain game situations, and it's feeling pretty good. I 
can do all of the lateral movements I have to make. 
</P>
<P>
	``That Sunday when I got hurt, it was more disappointment than  
pain,'' he said. ``When it first happened, I was just upset that it 
happened so soon in the season. If I was going to get hurt, why 
couldn't I get hurt in the 16th week of the season and not so early 
in the season?'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
