<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dry Weather for Floyd's Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TARBORO, N.C. (AP) -- The sky cleared over eastern North Carolina  
today after a last soaking rainfall rang the curtain down on one of 
the wettest months ever for the region devastated by Hurricane 
Floyd's floodwaters. 
</P>
<P>
	An inch of rain fell overnight, adding to the misery inflicted  
by 7 inches from Tropical Storm Dennis in early September, 20 
inches of rain during Floyd two weeks ago, and up to 8 inches of 
rain earlier this week. Residents of the soggy region hoped October 
will be drier. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically, after we get through this, we'll be sunny and have  
dry conditions right on through Monday,'' Richard Jones, a National 
Weather Service meteorologist in Raleigh, said today. By 
midmorning, the sun was shining on the flooded region. 
</P>
<P>
	Two solid days of rainfall, however, pushed up the Tar and Neuse  
rivers again. The Tar was expected to crest Sunday in Tarboro 7 
feet above its 19-foot flood stage. Forecasters said the Neuse 
would crest in Goldsboro on Friday at 24 feet, 10 feet above flood 
stage. 
</P>
<P>
	Signs of normalcy flickered in the worst-flooded areas, but not  
at Tarboro High School, serving as a shelter for 300 displaced 
flood victims beset by boredom and frustration. More than 1,500 
made homeless by the storm remain in 18 shelters. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want a home,'' said Annie McDowell of Tarboro while snapping  
a plastic spoon in her hand after another lunch Wednesday at the 
high school shelter. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest rain system spawned tornadoes that downed trees and  
damaged homes Wednesday night in central North Carolina, to the 
west of the worst of Floyd's damage. One person was injured by a 
fallen tree. 
</P>
<P>
	In Virginia, wind gusts up to 60 mph blew down trees and power  
lines from remote mountain regions to the Washington suburbs. A 
tornado also demolished mobile homes several miles from Darlington, 
S.C., but did not seriously injure anyone, emergency officials 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Southeast of Goldsboro in the small town of Seven Springs,  
residents braced for more flooding as authorities said the Neuse 
would crest Friday. Many of the town's side streets were covered 
Wednesday and an overnight curfew remains enforced. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Jesse Jackson toured Princeville, a town of 1,900  
founded by ex-slaves that is still closed to residents. Jackson 
said eastern North Carolina needs not just flood relief but a 
top-to-bottom reconstruction. 
</P>
<P>
	``This area had people who were hurting even before this  
flood,'' he said. ``Not only must we pump water out, but pump 
resources in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Princeville residents today were allowed to enter their town for  
the first time since they fled Floyd's floodwaters two weeks ago. 
However, residents may not be able to move back into their homes 
immediately. On Wednesday, Mayor Delia Perkins said the water 
system will need replacement this winter, suggesting it may be next 
year before residents can return for good. 
</P>
<P>
	Floyd is expected to eclipse the $6 billion in state losses  
caused by Hurricane Fran in 1996. It has claimed at least 47 lives 
in North Carolina, destroyed 1,461 homes and damaged thousands of 
others. 
</P>
<P>
	In Greenville, East Carolina University opened Wednesday for the  
first time in two weeks. School officials said up to 2,500 of the 
university's 18,000 students may need new housing. 
</P>
<P>
	In Edgecombe County, the epicenter of the storm damage, schools  
plan to reopen on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``All of their curriculum materials, all of their supplies were  
lost,'' said county spokeswoman Diane LeFiles. ``They're really 
starting from scratch. They've got to order the pencils, paper and 
paper clips.'' 
</P>
<P>
	State officials announced plans to spend up to $60 million to  
buy 4,000 mobile homes for displaced flood victims to live in for 
up to 18 months. Sixty-five families already are living in camping 
trailers in Rocky Mount. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 42,500 people have registered for state and federal  
assistance, and about $4.8 million in aid already has been 
approved. 
</P>
<P>
	Farmers got more bad news Wednesday when state Agriculture  
Secretary Jim Graham urged them to destroy flood-damaged tobacco 
leaves rather than risk contaminating other harvested tobacco. 
</P>
<P>
	``We recognize this request is severe and costly,'' Graham said.  
</P>
<P>
	Early estimates peg flood losses for the state's tobacco crop at  
nearly $99 million, and all agriculture losses at $1 billion or 
more. North Carolina is the No. 1 tobacco state. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
