<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Robert Brooks To Keep Signing Bonus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Robert Brooks, who retired from the Green  
Bay Packers during training camp, will keep all of his signing 
bonus. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrew Brandt, the team's director of player finance/football  
operations, said that after researching the matter, the Packers 
decided not to file a grievance to recover some of the $3.5 million 
signing bonus Brooks received in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks, who had been with the team since 1992, retired because  
of a knee injury and the resulting problems caused by 
overcompensating for it. 
</P>
<P>
	He had received the signing bonus as part of a five-year deal he  
signed in February 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The Green Bay Press-Gazette said in reporting the move that, if  
a player retires voluntarily, National Football League contracts 
call for a prorated portion of the signing bonus to be returned to 
the club while, if team doctors tell a player he should retire 
because of an injury, the player keeps the signing bonus. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks had passed the Packers' physical but said he was in too  
much pain to play. 
</P>
<P>
	The Press-Gazette said the Packers sent Brooks a letter saying  
they wanted to negotiate a settlement rather than pursue the matter 
through a grievance. It said Brooks countered by saying he would 
come back and play, which would have forced the Packers to cut him. 
</P>
<P>
	If he was cut, he would keep the bonus money anyway, so the  
Packers dropped the matter, the newspaper said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 18:50:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Govt Lawyer in Microsoft Case Quits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- One of the lead lawyers for the government in  
the antitrust trial against the Microsoft Corp. has quit the case 
and resigned from the New York attorney general's office just weeks 
before the judge's initial verdict is expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephen Houck, who resigned Wednesday, led the courtroom fight  
for the 19 states suing Microsoft along with the Justice 
Department. He also delivered part of the government's closing 
arguments to the judge last week. 
</P>
<P>
	His decision was not expected to affect the trial's outcome  
because New York and the other states still are pursuing their 
claims. Iowa's attorney general, Tom Miller, is coordinating the 
states' role in the trial. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to see how this is going to affect the case,'' said  
Robert Litan, a former senior Justice official. ``Turnover is 
normal. I don't think you can really read too much into this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Houck did not return messages left at his office Thursday.  
</P>
<P>
	Houck questioned only one of the 26 trial witnesses, IBM  
executive John Soyring, who also was from New York. Much of the 
attention during 77 days of testimony, has been on Justice 
Department lawyer David Boies, who questioned Microsoft trial 
executives. 
</P>
<P>
	When Houck sought an expanded role early in the trial -- asking a  
question during testimony from the first witness -- the judge 
snapped at him harshly and reminded him that only one government 
lawyer was allowed to question each witness. 
</P>
<P>
	Houck was perhaps best known for his strong views that Microsoft  
should face the severest penalties for its alleged antitrust 
violations. On the final day of testimony, he told reporters the 
company was a ``malignant despot'' and that its behavior ``will 
justify a very significant remedy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Houck also was the only lawyer, besides Boies, to question  
Microsoft's chairman, Bill Gates, during a sworn videotaped 
deposition over three days last year. Shown at trial, excerpts from 
the tape of Gates professing to forget key events and appearing to 
evade questions proved embarrassing for the software giant. 
</P>
<P>
	Houck mentioned the Gates tape again during closing arguments  
last week when he said the judge ``plainly has seen enough of Mr. 
Gates' videotaped deposition to make your own findings'' about his 
truthfulness. 
</P>
<P>
	A Microsoft spokesman, Jim Cullinan, declined to comment on  
Houck's resignation. ``He has not applied for a job in (Microsoft) 
law and corporate affairs,'' Cullinan quipped in response to a 
question. 
</P>
<P>
	Houck was the head of the antitrust office for New York's  
attorney general until last year's election, when Democrat Eliot 
Spitzer defeated the incumbent and replaced Houck with Harry First. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 00:00:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Paper: Radio Station Steals Stories </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOLEDO, Ohio (AP) -- The Blade claims a radio station and its  
morning host have used the daily newspaper's stories on the air 
without crediting the newspaper or obtaining permission. 
</P>
<P>
	In a lawsuit filed Tuesday, the newspaper accused WSPD-AM of  
``pirating'' its stories and using deceptive trade practices. 
</P>
<P>
	The radio station's manager denied the allegations.  
</P>
<P>
	``We would not intentionally pirate any other journalist's  
work,'' Andy Stuart, vice president and market manager for Clear 
Channel Communications Inc.'s five Toledo stations, said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper cited four examples of articles it said were  
published in The Blade during September and then used by morning 
show host Mark Standriff on the air without proper credit. 
</P>
<P>
	``The law and the most fundamental rules of journalism require  
that when they use The Blade, they must give proper attribution 
each and every time,'' said the newspaper's lawyer, Fritz Byers. 
</P>
<P>
	Standriff would discuss issues based on what was reported in the  
newspaper and read direct quotes from The Blade as if he had 
gathered the information himself, the lawsuit said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stuart said Standriff's show is based on opinions and that the  
standards are different. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mark is not a journalist,'' Stuart said. ``Mark is a radio  
talk show host and has a much broader license.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit also claims that Standriff has encouraged listeners  
not to read the newspaper by using the motto ``I Read The Blade So 
You Don't Have To.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Standriff joked about the lawsuit during his show Wednesday.  
``I'm a wanted man,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit seeks unspecified damages and an order that WSPD stop  
broadcasting news or other reports taken from The Blade. The 
lawsuit also asks that the court order WSPD to pay The Blade all 
advertising profits generated during the broadcasts at issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Newspapers often complain about broadcast stations pirating  
stories, said Aly Colon, a member of the ethics faculty at the 
Poynter Institute, a journalism training center in St. Petersburg, 
Fla. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a general perception that news is a public  
commodity,'' he said. ``Once the news comes out, it's often 
considered in the public domain.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 12:50:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blues Claim Reirden From Edmonton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- The St. Louis Blues claimed defenseman Todd  
Reirden off waivers from the Edmonton Oilers Thursday. 
</P>
