<DOCNO> APW19990930.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 10:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Restoring the Satire of Animal Farm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LUGGALA, Ireland (AP) -- The actor-comedian W. C. Fields famously  
advised against working with children or animals, so he clearly 
would have balked at a film set without actors. 
</P>
<P>
	And yet that was the situation one rainswept day last fall on  
the set of ``Animal Farm,'' the $22 million TNT Original movie 
airing Sunday at 8 p.m. EDT on TNT. 
</P>
<P>
	Performers had, of course, previously been present on the rural  
Irish location, from Englishman Pete Postlethwaite (``Among 
Giants,'' ``In the Name of the Father'') to Dublin theater mainstay 
Alan Stanford (``Waiting for Godot''). 
</P>
<P>
	But halfway through the autumn shoot, the animals took over. As  
in the book, so it was on set where the day's stars included the 
donkey portraying Benjamin and the gray mare playing Mollie, not to 
mention a potentially scene-stealing border collie named Spice in 
the pivotal dog's role of Jessie. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are no Winnebagos, no makeup and hair, no costumes, no  
perks, nothing,'' said Robert Halmi Sr., the film's executive 
producer, explaining the differences between this shoot and just 
about any other in the veteran producer's long career. 
</P>
<P>
	For one thing, Halmi had to build the entire location, creating  
a little town -- complete with electricity and phone lines -- on a 
fraction of the 2,000-acre Guinness Estate in a grassy dip amid the 
Wicklow Mountains. 
</P>
<P>
	Then there was the film itself, a Hallmark Entertainment  
adaptation intent on honoring its source, as befits a producer who 
says bluntly of the venture, ``This is it. I'll be happy if I don't 
do anything else in my life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The goal is George Orwell, with satiric sting intact.  
</P>
<P>
	``In America, this is probably over the heads of most people,''  
conceded Halmi, who was 21 and living under Communist rule in his 
native Hungary in 1945 when Orwell's portrait of an animal uprising 
as a parable for Stalinism was first published. 
</P>
<P>
	While a student in Budapest, Halmi was part of the  
anti-communist resistance movement and got hold of a smuggled 
version of the book, which had been banned in Eastern Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 50 years later, he is using his clout as an  
Emmy-winning producer to bring it to the screen. ``For me, the most 
important thing -- almost religiously -- has been to do this book,'' 
Halmi said. 
</P>
<P>
	What he didn't want, he added, ``was a Disney-esque adaptation  
or a cartoon. That would be Hollywood, and I'm antiestablishment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Animal Farm'' did inspire a British cartoon feature in 1954  
that radically softened Orwell's ending, and Halmi admits that even 
his live-action version leaves open an un-Orwellian door to hope. 
(``There are always survivors'' reads a key line at the end of the 
film.) 
</P>
<P>
	Other versions of the same fable include an acclaimed,  
much-traveled stage version, directed by Sir Peter Hall, that began 
at London's National Theater in 1984. A separate youth theater 
production for 24 actors ages 11 to 14 will run in Leicester in the 
English Midlands in late October. 
</P>
<P>
	Wherever it is seen, this is still the story of Napoleon, the  
nostril-flaring pig who participates in an insurrection on Manor 
Farm -- soon renamed the Animal Farm of the title -- only to end up 
grandly sipping whiskey with the same abusive landowners whom the 
animals displaced. 
</P>
<P>
	Napoleon's excesses mirror those of man at his most beastly, as  
Orwell paints a ruthless picture of totalitarianism then and for 
all time. 
</P>
<P>
	The film marries live-action with animatronics -- the latter  
courtesy of Jim Henson's Creature Shop in London -- alongside 
computer-generated effects, all intended to bring the barnyard 
inhabitants to nearly human life. (Think ``Babe'' but more 
bruising, as well as technically advanced.) 
</P>
<P>
	``If it's walking, it's an actual animal; if it's static and  
talking, it's animatronic,'' visual effects supervisor Angus 
Bickerton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Postlethwaite plays the bibulous owner of Manor Farm, with  
Patrick Stewart, Ian Holm and Julia Ormond supplying the voices for 
the opportunistic Napoleon, his sidekick Squealer and the wise 
escapee Jessie, respectively. 
</P>
<P>
	But on a muddy day last October, actors voicing the animals had  
yet to be chosen, while those playing humans had done their jobs 
and left. (Kelsey Grammer and Julia Louis-Dreyfus were among those 
ultimately selected to voice the animals.) 
</P>
<P>
	So the rural location south of Dublin found director John  
Stephenson, a veteran of the Creature Shop, clambering through hay 
in a leaking barn, preparing for a close-up on an animatronic 
red-haired pig in what is Stephenson's first major directing 
assignment. 
</P>
<P>
	``The main thing is to get believable lips in,'' he explained,  
in between overseeing the four puppeteers who control the animals 
alongside a back-up team numbering almost 20. 
</P>
<P>
	``We do try and treat them as actors,'' he said of the animal  
operators. ``The end results are better that way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Have any non-human stars been born? All eyes were on Spice, the  
3 1/2 year-old pooch playing Jessie, who is that rare holdout amid the 
autocratic misrule chronicled in ``Animal Farm.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone's in love with that dog,'' Bickerton said. ``She's  
gorgeous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mary Owens, Spice's Irish owner and trainer, said the dog would  
take it in stride: ``I think Spice thinks she's ready for Hollywood 
anyway.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ...  
</P>
<P>
	`SHASTA McNASTY': Your wait is over. Perhaps the season's  
least-awaited sitcoms will preview tonight at 9:30 p.m. EDT on UPN. 
Three rowdy roommates living in Venice Beach, Calif., make up the 
music group Shasta McNasty in a show that dares to be one of the 
most outrageous sitcoms on network television (this, according to 
the network). Dale Godboldo, Jake Busey and Carmine Giovinazzo 
star. If you want more, ``Shasta'' officially premieres next 
Tuesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
