<DOCNO> APW19990930.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 22:50:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Challengers: We've Got Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Thanks in part to the federal funds being  
rejected by Republican presidential front-runner George W. Bush, 
his GOP challengers maintain they will have enough money to compete 
financially with the Texas governor. 
</P>
<P>
	As Bush reported yet another new fund-raising record Thursday,  
raking in $56 million through the end of September, his rivals 
touted their own fund raising during the period from July 1 to 
Sept. 30. 
</P>
<P>
	Except for Bush and millionaire Steve Forbes, who is paying most  
of his campaign expenses, the remaining six Republican and two 
Democratic candidates are accepting federal help for their 
campaigns. Under the Watergate-era law, taxpayers match the first 
$250 of each individual contribution, while candidates agree to 
limit spending. 
</P>
<P>
	In a year when Bush has captured most of the available  
contributions, the federal aid looms larger as his opponents 
struggle to raise enough to be effective. 
</P>
<P>
	While Bush reported having $37 million in the bank, the others  
noted they had millions of dollars not yet reported because the 
federal funds won't be released until January. 
</P>
<P>
	A case in point: Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a poor second in the  
money race. 
</P>
<P>
	Though McCain reported $2 million in the bank as of Thursday,  
aides noted that he already was eligible to receive another $3 
million in federal matching funds, bringing his real total to $5 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	``John McCain will lead America on a new patriotic challenge and  
the McCain campaign will have sufficient resources to spread that 
message across the nation,'' said McCain's national finance 
chairman, Herb Allison. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Bauer had just $300,000 in the bank at September's end, but  
has $3.6 million in federal matching funds coming next year, 
campaign manager Frank Cannon said. ``Beyond the front-runner, we 
have the broadest financial base in the Republican field,'' Cannon 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bush campaign said Thursday that it had raised $19 million  
between July and September. That was more money than the two 
Democratic contenders, Vice President Al Gore and former Sen. Bill 
Bradley, raised between them. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley, in fact, surpassed Gore for the quarter, $6.7 million  
to $6.5 million. Since the beginning of the year, Gore has raised 
more money than Bradley, $24 million compared to $18.4 million. But 
Gore also has spent more money. As of Thursday, Bradley had more 
than $10 million in the bank while Gore had between $9.5 million 
and $10 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush reported receiving more than 135,000 contributions en route  
to his record-setting haul. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am humbled and honored that so many Americans are helping me  
spread my message of improving schools to leave no child behind, 
strengthening our military to keep the peace, and ushering in an 
era of responsibility in America,'' Bush said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bush campaign also released 41 more names of its top  
fund-raisers, known as the Pioneers, each of whom have raised at 
least $100,000. The list included Indianapolis Mayor Stephen 
Goldsmith, a leader of Bush's domestic policy team, and former 
Massachusetts Gov. William Weld. 
</P>
<P>
	With his sizable bank balance, Bush not only has enough money to  
wage energetic campaigns in the early caucus and primary states, 
but to set up full-scale operations elsewhere, such as in 
California, New York and the Midwestern states that will be key 
battlegrounds in the general election. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is now going to have the money needed to run not just  
robust campaigns in Iowa and New Hampshire, but he will be able to 
run well-organized campaigns in most of the states, which means he 
will be able to use his primary campaign to set a strong foundation 
for a general election organization,'' said Anthony Corrado, a 
professor of government at Colby College in Waterville, Maine. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
