<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McNown Pleads No Contest To Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Cade McNown admits he made a mistake nearly  
three years ago, and now he's going to pay for it. 
</P>
<P>
	Through his attorneys, the rookie Chicago Bears quarterback  
pleaded no contest Thursday to a misdemeanor charge of illegally 
possessing a handicapped parking placard. 
</P>
<P>
	Current UCLA safety Eric Whitfield and former Bruins fullback  
Craig Walendy also entered no-contest pleas in Los Angeles 
Municipal Court, joining 13 other current and former UCLA football 
players who previously agreed to a plea agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	All 16 have been ordered to pay $1,485 in fines and perform 200  
hours of community service, and also must spend a day meeting with 
the disabled and their advocates. 
</P>
<P>
	The final three charged in the matter were scheduled for  
arraignment Thursday before Municipal Judge Sam Ohta, but were 
granted continuances until Oct. 20. 
</P>
<P>
	McNown's lawyers, Ronald Safer and Stanley Greenberg, entered  
the no-contest plea. McNown issued a statement nearly three hours 
later from the Bears' practice site in Lake Forest, Ill. 
</P>
<P>
	It read: ``During offseason workouts at UCLA, I applied for a  
handicapped parking sticker. Although I was injured, the process by 
which I acquired the permit was wrong, and for that I am sorry. I 
had trouble getting around, but applying for the sticker minimized 
the needs of permanently disabled persons. I deeply regret the 
incident occurred, and hope people don't judge me on this 
particular mistake.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McNown refused to comment further, citing the advice of his  
lawyers. He could not be found earlier when the Bears' locker room 
was open following practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Safer emphasized outside court that McNown never used a  
handicapped parking space, and said the state had no such evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	``He feels terrible that his conduct and the conduct of others  
denigrates the seriousness of the obstacles faced by permanently 
handicapped people,'' Safer said. ``He made this mistake in 
judgment when he was 19 years old. Let the first person who made no 
mistakes of judgment when they were teen-agers throw the first 
stone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now 22, McNown was a first-round draft choice of the Bears last  
April. 
</P>
<P>
	``The crime is obtaining and possessing this handicap sticker,''  
Safer said. ``He did not obtain the placard through correct 
channels, and he acknowledges that. He should have followed 
procedures and seen a doctor himself instead of somebody else 
obtaining a doctor's signature.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Safer said McNown, who led the Bruins to the Pac-10 championship  
last season, believed at the time that the doctor's signature was 
valid. The lawyer wouldn't elaborate further. 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy city attorney Brian Williams said he expected the three  
remaining men charged -- Washington Redskins running back Skip 
Hicks, Kansas City Chiefs safety Larry Atkins and former UCLA 
linebacker Brendon Ayanbadejo -- to enter no-contest pleas Oct. 20. 
</P>
<P>
	The city attorney's office brought charges July 8 against 14  
current or former players alleged to be part of the disabled 
parking scam, and five more were charged Sept. 13. Nine entered 
pleas on July 28, four more on Sept. 14. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten, including Whitfield, are members of the current team and  
were suspended for the season's first two games. 
</P>
<P>
	California law allows people with temporary or permanent  
disabilities to obtain permits to park in special handicap spaces, 
to use metered spaces for free and to park in limited-time zones 
indefinitely. 
</P>
<P>
	The football players reportedly used the placards to avoid the  
$132-per-semester fee for parking on campus and to park in the area 
around UCLA where parking problems are chronic. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 12:20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Agents Probe N. Carolina Bombs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) -- Federal investigators are said to be  
looking into a possible link between three bombs found at Lowe's 
stores and a fatal accident at an auto track named for the home 
improvement chain. 
</P>
<P>
	The News &AMP; Record quoted an unidentified source Thursday as  
saying someone had called Lowe's to complain not enough was done 
for victims of the accident. 
</P>
<P>
	Three spectators were killed and eight injured May 1 at Lowe's  
Motor Speedway in Concord when debris from a wrecked car flew into 
the stands. 
</P>
<P>
	The person who called the chain's headquarters in North  
Wilkesboro claimed to be ``an aggrieved relative,'' said the 
source, who spoke on the condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators also are looking into the possibility that the  
bombings are connected to recent efforts to unionize Lowe's 
workers, the source said. 
</P>
<P>
	A bomb that was found at a store in Concord on Tuesday before it  
went off was the third planted at a Lowe's in less than a week. Two 
bombs exploded minutes apart Sept. 22 at stores in Asheboro and 
Salisbury. Three people were injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Earl Woodham, spokesman for the U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco  
and Firearms, said lab analysis showed that all three bombs 
appeared to be the work of the same person or persons. He wouldn't 
confirm the newspaper report. 
</P>
<P>
	Concord store employees found the bomb soon after Bob Tillman,  
the chairman and chief executive of Lowe's, entered the store. 
Tillman regularly visits stores. 
</P>
<P>
	Lowe's spokesman Brian Peace would not comment on the  
investigation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 15:30:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  U.S.-Russia Relationship Said Vital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Concern over alleged Russian corruption and  
money laundering through a U.S. bank must not overshadow the vital 
relationship between the two nations, former Russian Prime Minister 
Viktor Chernomyrdin said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Chernomyrdin, speaking to reporters during a visit to the United  
States, acknowledged there is corruption in Russia. However, he 
said, ``It would be premature and unfair to think that all Russian 
business is corrupt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chernomyrdin noted that U.S.-Russian relations have been thrown  
into question by the allegations about money laundering at the Bank 
of New York, a development he called ``very dangerous both for the 
peoples of our two countries and for the whole world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The former prime minister, who jointly headed a commission with  
Vice President Al Gore on bilateral ties, bristled at suggestions 
that Gore should be held responsible for the alleged misdeeds 
because of his strong support for U.S. aid to Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	Corruption ``is our responsibility,'' he said, speaking through  
an interpreter. ``What does it have to do with Gore, what does it 
have to do with the U.S. government?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chernomyrdin, who had a longer tenure than most Russian prime  
ministers, from 1992 to 1998, said he did not meet with Gore during 
his visit this week to Washington and New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore has come under fire from Republicans for his close  
relationship with Russian leaders and his hands-on role in 
U.S.-Russian diplomacy. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican leaders recently have criticized the administration's  
support for aid to Russia, as federal investigators have widened 
their inquiry into allegations that Russian companies and 
individuals -- including organized-crime figures-- laundered billions 
of dollars through the Bank of New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Chernomyrdin spoke as Russian authorities announced their first  
banking investigation since those allegations surfaced last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors are examining Moscow's Flamingo Bank, which  
allegedly had $430,000 and the equivalent of another $120,000 in 
rubles without proper documentation, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Those sums are tiny when compared with those allegedly involving  
the Bank of New York, the 15th-largest U.S. bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian prosecutors have given no indication that Flamingo Bank  
had dealings with the Bank of New York or any other American bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Flamingo, with only one branch and no private depositors, has  
not attracted public notice in the past. The bank has a license 
that allows it to deal in foreign currencies, said a Flamingo 
official who declined to give her name. The bank declined to 
discuss details of the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's inquiry -- focusing on a small bank and a small amount  
of money -- prompted suggestions that the government wants to make a 
scapegoat of Flamingo and give the appearance it is thoroughly 
investigating alleged money laundering. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 09:00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alitel To Cut 350 Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Communications company Alltel Corp.  
plans to cut 350 jobs during the next year. 
</P>
<P>
	The cutbacks are to come from Alltel's wire-line operations in  
13 states, mostly in the Southeast and Midwest markets, the company 
said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The job cuts will begin next month and continue through next  
summer, Alltel spokesman George Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some jobs are to be eliminated through attrition and others  
through early retirement. Some employees may be offered other jobs 
in the company, Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent years, Alltel has been installing digital and  
fiber-optic equipment that has eliminated the need for some 
engineering, warehousing and switching office jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's unfortunate that dramatic changes in technology can  
result in the elimination of job positions,'' said Scott Ford, 
Alltel's president and chief operating officer. ``This announcement 
is a clear indication that our business needs are changing and our 
company must be proactive in meeting daily challenges.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The job cuts amount to 1.5 percent of Alltel's nearly  
24,000-person work force. 
</P>
<P>
	Alltel, based in Little Rock, Ark., will take a yet-unspecified  
third-quarter charge to cover severance expenses, which will be 
offered based on years of service and company benefit plans. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 15:30:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
