</P>
<P>
	Gore has come under fire from Republicans for his close  
relationship with Russian leaders and his hands-on role in 
U.S.-Russian diplomacy. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican leaders recently have criticized the administration's  
support for aid to Russia, as federal investigators have widened 
their inquiry into allegations that Russian companies and 
individuals -- including organized-crime figures-- laundered billions 
of dollars through the Bank of New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Chernomyrdin spoke as Russian authorities announced their first  
banking investigation since those allegations surfaced last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors are examining Moscow's Flamingo Bank, which  
allegedly had $430,000 and the equivalent of another $120,000 in 
rubles without proper documentation, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Those sums are tiny when compared with those allegedly involving  
the Bank of New York, the 15th-largest U.S. bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian prosecutors have given no indication that Flamingo Bank  
had dealings with the Bank of New York or any other American bank. 
</P>
<P>
	Flamingo, with only one branch and no private depositors, has  
not attracted public notice in the past. The bank has a license 
that allows it to deal in foreign currencies, said a Flamingo 
official who declined to give her name. The bank declined to 
discuss details of the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's inquiry -- focusing on a small bank and a small amount  
of money -- prompted suggestions that the government wants to make a 
scapegoat of Flamingo and give the appearance it is thoroughly 
investigating alleged money laundering. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 14:20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Help Wanted Ads Up in in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The volume of help-wanted advertising in major  
U.S. newspapers edged up in August from the three-year low reached 
in the previous two months, a private research firm reported 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Conference Board said its index of help-wanted ads rose  
slightly to 86 in August, up from 85 in both June and July. 
</P>
<P>
	The index is used as a gauge of changes in job supply. It is  
watched by economists as an indicator of labor market conditions to 
help form estimates of unemployment rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the slow rate of increase in the index in August, the  
Conference Board's chief economist said he remained convinced that 
an expected spurt of economic growth in the second half of this 
year could force the unemployment rate to its lowest level in 
nearly 30 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are very few signs that hiring will slow as companies  
scramble to rebuild inventory,'' Ken Goldstein said in a prepared 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Goldstein predicted that with economic growth of at least 3.5  
percent in the third and fourth quarters driving increased creation 
of jobs, the unemployment rate could fall below 4 percent for the 
first time since 1970. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's unemployment rate rose from a 29-year low of 4.2  
percent in May to 4.3 percent in July, which was still the lowest 
level in three years. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, the Commerce Department reported Thursday that U.S.  
economic growth dipped to a relatively slow annual rate of 1.6 
percent in the spring, but many analysts expect the slowdown to be 
temporary. Some economists are even more bullish than Goldstein, 
expecting growth of at least 4 percent in the July-September 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The seasonally adjusted help-wanted index, which stood at 100 in  
the base year of 1987, is derived from measuring the volume of 
unemployment ads in 51 major newspapers across the country each 
month. 
</P>
<P>
	From June through August, help-wanted advertising fell in seven  
regions and rose in two. The steepest declines took place in the 
West North Central region, which includes Kansas City, Mo., 
Minneapolis, Omaha, Neb., and St. Louis, down 10.1 percent; the 
West South Central region, including Dallas, Houston, San Antonio, 
New Orleans, Oklahoma City, and Tulsa, Okla., down 7 percent; and 
the South Atlantic region region -- Atlanta, Baltimore, Charlotte, 
N.C., Miami and Jacksonville in Fla. , Richmond, Va., and 
Washington, down 4.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Increases took place in the Mountain region, which includes  
Denver, Colo., Phoenix and Salt Lake City, up 4.9 percent; and the 
East South Central region, including Birmingham, Ala.; Knoxville, 
Memphis and Nashville in Tennessee; and Louisville, Ky., up 2.4 
percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
