<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MLS' Revolution Fires Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FOXBORO, Mass. (AP) -- Coach Walter Zenga was fired Thursday by  
the New England Revolution with two games left in the regular 
season. He was replaced by Steve Nicol, who coached the Boston 
Bulldogs of the A League in Framingham. 
</P>
<P>
	Zenga, who took over as player-coach with six games left last  
season, led the Revolution to a 10-20-4 record this year. With two 
games left, New England trails Miami by one point for the last 
playoff spot in the Eastern Conference. Zenga has a 5-13 record as 
a goalkeeper and will not continue as a player with the Revolution. 
</P>
<P>
	General manager Brian O'Donovan said Zenga didn't want to wait  
until the end of the season to discuss a contract extension. 
</P>
<P>
	``He also indicated to us that he had other options in Italy and  
needed to explore them immediately,'' O'Donovan said in a team 
statement. ``We received (Wednesday) a written ultimatum insisting 
that the team reach a decision. We would have preferred to evaluate 
fully the situation during the offseason and make our decision 
then.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zenga, 39, named the world's best goalkeeper after the 1990  
World Cup, played that position for the Revolution in 1997. He then 
retired from the team and returned to Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	On Aug. 23, 1998, he was named to replace Thomas Rongen, who was  
fired by the Revolution. Zenga led the Revolution to a 3-3 record 
last year and its first playoff berth ever. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 15:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mazda Settles Clean Air Act Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Mazda Motor of America Inc. agreed Thursday to  
pay a $900,000 penalty and to modify its reporting of emission 
control defects in order to settle allegations it violated the 
Clean Air Act, the Justice Department said. 
</P>
<P>
	The department and the Environmental Protection Agency filed the  
settlement in U.S. District Court here to resolve civil claims that 
Mazda, based in Irvine, Calif., failed to promptly report defective 
emission control devices in its MPV minivans. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement covers 226,000 MPV minivans in model years 1989  
through 1994. Their emission control devices have a part that can 
crack or break, emitting gasoline vapor into the atmosphere at a 
level substantially above EPA's standard, the government said. 
Passengers may detect a gasoline odor inside the car when the part 
fails. 
</P>
<P>
	The toxic emissions contain hydrocarbons, a component of ozone,  
which can aggravate respiratory problems such as asthma. 
</P>
<P>
	``Prompt disclosure of emissions-related defects by automakers  
is critical to assuring the public that it is driving clean cars,'' 
said Lois J. Schiffer, assistant attorney general for environment 
and natural resources. 
</P>
<P>
	EPA regulations require automakers to file emissions defect  
reports with the agency within 15 days after learning of them in 25 
or more vehicles of the same model year. The government alleged 
Mazda knew of this defect years before it filed a report with the 
EPA in November 1996, preventing the agency from taking prompt 
action to fix the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to paying a penalty and changing its investigation  
and reporting of defects, Mazda also will extend the warranty on 
the defective part on all 1989 through 1994 MPV minivans to a total 
of 11 years, without any mileage limitation. 
</P>
<P>
	The automaker will notify owners that they do not have to wait  
for the part to fail before having it replaced. Earlier, Mazda had 
notified them of a similar warranty extension as part of an 
agreement with the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Mazda also agreed to reimburse minivan owners who repaired a  
defective vapor separator at their own expense. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 00:40:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Final Candlestick Game Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- When the San Francisco Giants move downtown  
next season, leaving wind-swept Candlestick Park to the NFL's 
49ers, they'll take four decades of memories to the new stadium, 
and little else. 
</P>
<P>
	``I won't miss the place,'' Giants senior vice president Pat  
Gallagher said. ``We had a lot of meetings to think about what we 
wanted to take from Candlestick to the new park, and we couldn't 
think of a thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Few pitchers will miss a park in which popups blew over the  
outfield wall for homers. Neither will fans, who came to August 
games in ski jackets and gloves. 
</P>
<P>
	The lousy weather, which became a part of Candlestick lore  
almost from the day it opened in 1960, forced players to come up 
with survival strategies. They tried a variety of tricks to stay 
warm at Candlestick, where a perfectly nice day could suddenly 
become arctic as a cold fog descended on the park. 
</P>
<P>
	Bobby Murcer heated his bat in the Giants' clubhouse sauna  
before plate appearances. The Atlanta Braves hugged hot-water 
bottles in the dugout. Right fielders sometimes skipped into the 
clubhouse between innings for coffee, or whatever else they could 
find to ward off the cold. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never got cold out here. I would make sure I had a lot of  
oil on me, like a swimmer. They could smell me on the bench,'' said 
Willie Mays, who wore heating balm on his back. 
</P>
<P>
	Mays had other ways of adapting to the weird weather. In fact,  
he used a simple formula for coping with the swirling winds. 
</P>
<P>
	``Take two steps in and five steps back, and get the ball,'' he  
explained. 
</P>
<P>
	Candlestick, which had its final major league game today as the  
Giants faced the Los Angeles Dodgers, opened on April 12, 1960 -- 
two seasons after the Giants moved west from New York. Vice 
President Richard Nixon and Hall of Famer Ty Cobb presided over the 
opening ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	Candlestick, now the fifth-oldest park in the majors, was home  
to Willie McCovey, Juan Marichal and Mays, who hit 203 homers there 
and undoubtedly would have hit many more if not for the gusts 
blowing in from left field. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the few opposing players who enjoyed Candlestick was San  
Diego's Tony Gwynn, whose 134 hits tie him for fifth among visitors 
to the park. Pete Rose tops the list with 201 hits. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to miss it because Willie Mays is not going to play  
in the other park. This place has a lot of history,'' Gwynn said. 
``That's just a little disappointing, seeing a place where Willie 
Mays, Willie McCovey and Jim Ray Hart played not being used 
anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Candlestick was the site of the Beatles' final concert, on Aug.  
29, 1966. When the group took the stage behind second base, John 
Lennon's first words to the crowd were not surprising. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a bit chilly,'' he complained.  
</P>
<P>
	The stadium survived the Oct. 17, 1989, earthquake that  
interrupted the World Series for 10 days. But one fan in Section 
51, atop the center-field stands, probably needed years of 
psychotherapy -- the 7.1 quake opened an expansion joint next to his 
seat, leaving him staring down 12 stories to the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	About the only person in the ballpark who didn't immediately  
realize it was an earthquake was elevator operator Bob Goodman, who 
has been working at Candlestick since 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	``The elevator had been shaking all homestand. I was going up  
and it was shaking again that night, and I didn't think twice about 
it,'' he said. ``When I opened the door, it was the weirdest site I 
ever saw. The whole world was going back and forth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marichal was scheduled to throw out the ceremonial first pitch  
today. Mays was to throw the final pitch, after the Dodgers-Giants 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	The stadium was renamed 3Com Park in 1996, but almost no one  
called it that. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the 'Stick. It'll always be the 'Stick,'' Gallagher said.  
``That was the only good thing about the ballpark, the name.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 14:36:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Giuliani Declares War on a Painting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- City officials have fired another round in their  
escalating fight with the Brooklyn Museum of Art, accusing the 
museum of displaying controversial work just to drive up its value. 
</P>
<P>
	The accusations made Wednesday by Deputy Mayor Joseph Lhota and  
the city's top lawyer, Michael Hess, came a day after the museum 
sued to stop Mayor Rudolph Giuliani from freezing its funding over 
the dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	Giuliani has threatened to cut city funding to the museum  
because of its decision to display an exhibit that includes a black 
Madonna decorated with elephant dung and pornographic cutouts. The 
funding amounts to $7 million, or about one-third of the museum's 
budget. 
</P>
<P>
	The pieces are from advertising executive Charles Saatchi's  
collection. Lhota and Hess say the museum's board planned the 
``Sensation'' exhibition so the works would fetch high prices at 
auction once the show closes. 
</P>
<P>
	The museum's board members are ``shilling for a British subject  
who is a multimillionaire and trying to enhance his art 
collection,'' Lhota said. 
</P>
<P>
	He cited a New York Observer article which said that after the  
show closed in London, Saatchi auctioned 128 pieces from his 
collection, many of them by artists in the show. 
</P>
<P>
	Giuliani, on a fund-raising trip in California, said he has been  
in touch with Lhota and Hess about their accusations. He said the 
project raises the question whether a publicly funded museum should 
engage in ``shock commercialization.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Andree Corroon, a spokeswoman for Christie's, which is helping  
sponsor the show, said the auction house had no plans for an 
auction. 
</P>
<P>
	``This bewildering accusation has absolutely no substance, is  
absolutely not true,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, the museum called the accusations ``preposterous  
and misleading.'' The show opens Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a federal judge has been asked to decide whether to  
restore the museum's funding. The museum sued the city on Tuesday, 
saying Giuliani's act violates the First Amendment. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, the Senate agreed unanimously Wednesday to a  
non-binding measure calling for the withholding of federal funds 
from the museum unless it cancels the exhibit. Independent Sen. Bob 
Smith of New Hampshire said the museum has received $500,000 from 
the National Endowment for the Arts in the last three years. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Wednesday, singer David Bowie -- who recorded an audio tour  
for museum visitors -- joined leaders of major New York City museums 
in support of the Brooklyn Museum. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sensation represents some of the best, worst but definitely  
most extreme of the high-profile work to have come out of Britain 
in the last 10 years or so,'' Bowie said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The leaders of two dozen cultural institutions -- including the  
Metropolitan Museum and the Museum of Modern Art -- signed a letter 
protesting the mayor's funding cut. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0053 </DOCNO>
