<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Michigan St. Player Acquitted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- Former Michigan State basketball star  
Antonio Smith was acquitted Thursday of charges he broke a cooler 
door lock and stole a 40-ounce bottle of beer from a convenience 
store. 
</P>
<P>
	An East Lansing District Court jury deliberated for less than  
two hours before finding Smith, 23, innocent of larceny and 
malicious destruction of property less than $200. 
</P>
<P>
	A conviction could have resulted in a jail sentence of up to 90  
days. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said during the three-day trial that Smith and his  
former teammate, Mateen Cleaves, stole the bottle from a 7-Eleven 
cooler about 2 a.m. April 14. 
</P>
<P>
	Police pulled the two players over that morning after Smith's  
Ford Expedition matched the description of one reportedly involved 
in the theft. Jason Klein, another Michigan State player, and two 
women also were in the vehicle. Arrest warrants were issued June 2 
against Smith and Cleaves. 
</P>
<P>
	During closing arguments, Smith's attorney, Frank Reynolds,  
argued the prosecution never proved there was a robbery. Two 
7-Eleven employees testified they had no inventory recorded to 
determine if the bottle was stolen. 
</P>
<P>
	Only the 911 tape, in which an anonymous caller tipped police to  
a robbery, indicated a crime may have been committed, Reynolds 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Assistant Prosecutor Joe Finnerty told the jury his case was  
strong, with testimony from a witness who saw Smith break the lock 
at the convenience store. 
</P>
<P>
	Finnerty had no comment following the verdict. Ingham County  
Prosecutor Stuart Dunnings did not return phone calls seeking 
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquittal was a relief for Smith, who said he was on edge  
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I tried to work out and couldn't concentrate,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Smith, the Spartans third-leading career rebounder, completed  
his college eligibility in March. He said Thursday he is headed to 
New York for a tryout with the Knicks. 
</P>
<P>
	Dunnings III dropped a larceny charge against Cleaves, 22, last  
week because a key witness was out of the country. Charges against 
Cleaves could be refiled if the witness returns. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
