<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 23:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Govt Lawyer in Microsoft Case Quits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- One of the two government lawyers who  
questioned Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates in videotaped testimony 
that proved embarrassing during the company's antitrust trial has 
quit his job. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephen Houck resigned unexpectedly earlier this week from the  
New York attorney general's office. He had led the courtroom fight 
against Microsoft for the 19 states suing the software giant along 
with the Justice Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Houck, whose decision comes just weeks before the judge's  
initial verdict is expected, also delivered part of the 
government's closing arguments to the judge last week. 
</P>
<P>
	His decision was not expected to affect the trial's outcome  
because New York and the other states still are pursuing their 
claims. 
</P>
<P>
	Houck did not return messages left at his office.  
</P>
<P>
	Houck never achieved the prominence during the 77-day trial that  
was afforded the Justice Department's high-profile litigator, David 
Boies. Houck questioned only one of the 26 trial witnesses, IBM 
executive John Soyring, who also was from New York. 
</P>
<P>
	When Houck sought an expanded role early in the case -- asking a  
question during testimony from the first witness -- the judge 
snapped at him harshly, reminding him that only one lawyer from the 
government was allowed to question each witness. 
</P>
<P>
	Houck was perhaps best known for his strong views that Microsoft  
should face the severest penalties for its alleged antitrust 
violations. On the final day of testimony, he told reporters the 
company was a ``malignant despot'' and that its behavior ``will 
justify a very significant remedy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Houck was the only lawyer, besides Boies, to question Gates  
during a sworn videotaped deposition over three days last year. 
Shown at trial, excerpts from the tape of Gates professing to 
forget key events and appearing to evade questions proved highly 
embarrassing. 
</P>
<P>
	Houck mentioned the Gates tape again during closing arguments  
last week when he said the judge ``plainly has seen enough of Mr. 
Gates' videotaped deposition to make your own findings'' about his 
truthfulness. 
</P>
<P>
	A Microsoft spokesman, Jim Cullinan, declined to comment on  
Houck's resignation. ``He has not applied for a job in (Microsoft) 
law and corporate affairs,'' Cullinan quipped in response to a 
question. 
</P>
<P>
	Houck was the head of the antitrust office for New York's  
attorney general until last year's election, when Democrat Eliot 
Spitzer defeated the incumbent and replaced Houck with Harry First. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
