without hitting a home run sometimes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Busch Stadium figures to have at least a semblance of the  
atmosphere during McGwire's record 70-homer season from 1998, with 
the series sold out for months. The scene may more closely resemble 
the lower-key setting for McGwire's 500th career homer last month, 
however, when 50 or 60 outside media requests were filled, instead 
of the 700 or so during the Maris chase at the height of 
McGwire-mania. 
</P>
<P>
	That's what you get with a sequel.  
</P>
<P>
	``Last year was totally different; last year was a record,''  
McGwire said. ``Here, everybody is talking about a home run title, 
which up until this last year nobody ever talked about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire, who had 65 homers with three games to go last year,  
believes fans are disappointed there won't be another challenge to 
the record. 
</P>
<P>
	``People, I think, are spoiled from what we've done last year,''  
McGwire said. ``They constantly want more, more, more. It's hard to 
comprehend that what we've done this year is harder than what we 
did last year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sosa echoed those sentiments.  
</P>
<P>
	``The people expect us to go out there and hit a home run every  
at-bat,'' Sosa said. ``They have to understand that we don't play 
by ourselves, there's a guy out there trying to get me out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	La Russa has said several times that McGwire's encore is perhaps  
more impressive than his record-setting season, because it would be 
natural for most players to relax after such an achievement. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, with me, no,'' McGwire said. ``I'm just speaking for  
myself, but I would never allow that to happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he also said he's been more mentally weary this year than  
last year, mostly because the Cardinals are winding up another 
disappointing season, and can't wait for it all to end. 
</P>
<P>
	He's also been stung by criticism that 50 home runs isn't such a  
notable accomplishment, noting that only he and Sosa have done it 
the last two years. Ken Griffey Jr., who had 48 and could do it 
three straight years, was the only other player in striking 
distance. 
</P>
<P>
	``What I can't understand is people can't accept what's  
happening, they always have to find a reason why it's happening,'' 
McGwire said. ``There's no reason; it's just happening. So accept 
it. Enjoy the moment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire has a combined three homers in 26 at-bats against the  
Cubs' three scheduled starters, Jon Lieber, Andrew Lorraine and 
Steve Trachsel. Trachsel has surrendered two homers in 15 at-bats, 
including McGwire's 62nd last year, Lieber has allowed one homer in 
10 at-bats and Lorraine has walked and struck out McGwire in his 
only two appearances. 
</P>
<P>
