<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 07:40:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani Declares War on a Painting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has gotten high marks for  
clean parks, low crime and clearing X-rated stores out of Times 
Square. But now he's declared war on a painting, and not everyone 
is cheering. 
</P>
<P>
	Giuliani has said he will cut all city funding to the Brooklyn  
Museum of Art over its decision to display a black Madonna 
decorated with elephant dung and pornographic cutouts. 
</P>
<P>
	The Catholic Church is on his side, but the arts community and  
prominent people including his likely opponent in the 2000 Senate 
race, Hillary Rodham Clinton, and First Amendment lawyer Floyd 
Abrams -- who is representing the Brooklyn institution -- think the 
mayor should keep his hands off the city's museums. 
</P>
<P>
	The leaders of two dozen city museums and cultural institutions  
-- including the Metropolitan Museum, the Museum of Modern Art, the 
Whitney Museum and the Guggenheim -- have signed a letter protesting 
the mayor's funding cut. 
</P>
<P>
	Whether the museum gets the money -- $7 million, or about  
one-third of its budget -- restored is now up to a federal judge. On 
Tuesday, the museum sued, saying Giuliani's act violates the First 
Amendment. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year the Supreme Court ruled that government may exercise a  
``decency standard'' for funding the arts. But Abrams said the 
decision also ``made quite clear that a city cannot manipulate the 
funding process in an effort to coerce people into shutting up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate approved a non-binding measure Wednesday saying the  
museum should not get federal funds unless it cancels the exhibit. 
</P>
<P>
	``People can do what they want to do and they can draw what they  
want to draw,'' said New Hampshire Sen. Bob Smith, an independent 
who sponsored the measure. But he added: ``The government doesn't 
have to fund this garbage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his Sunday sermon, Cardinal John O'Connor, who heads the New  
York Archdiocese, deemed the work an ``attack on religion.'' The 
next day, Mrs. Clinton said it was wrong to ``penalize and punish 
an institution such as the Brooklyn Museum.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The British show featuring ``The Holy Virgin Mary'' -- called  
``Sensation'' -- opens Saturday. The ticket agent for the show would 
not comment on sales and the museum did not return calls Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia University art history professor James Beck said the  
controversy over the elephant dung painting ``could be the 
beginning of a public debate about the role of government in art.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the early 1990s, the National Endowment for the Arts was  
nearly shut down by conservatives in Congress outraged that it had 
given grants for works like Robert Mapplethorpe's homoerotic art 
and Andres Serrano's photograph of a crucifix immersed in urine. 
The stir over the NEA led to the Supreme Court ruling on decency. 
</P>
<P>
	Average New Yorkers are divided, and some out-of-towners are  
intrigued. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had a lot of people say, `Why aren't we going to  
Brooklyn?''' said Lisa Hahn, president of Art Horizons, which plans 
cultural tours of New York City for museum staffs from all over the 
world. ``I hadn't put it on everybody's schedule. But I've had 
people call me and say, `Do we have enough free time to get out 
there?''' 
</P>
<P>
	Patrick Fitzgerald sided with Giuliani. ``It's a disgrace,'' he  
said, referring to the Virgin Mary painting. ``I'm a Catholic and I 
think this is an offense against Catholics and all religions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Damien Hirst, whose display of bisected animals pickled in  
formaldehyde is also part of the show, said Wednesday that the 
mayor ``may as well say `I only like Picasso and if you don't show 
it then I'm going to cut your funding.' It's just pure 
censorship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Ofili, a Catholic who created the Virgin Mary painting,  
was more oblique, telling The New York Times: ``The people who are 
attacking this painting are attacking their own interpretation, not 
mine.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 07:40:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former CEO Pleads in Price-Fix Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A former executive of the world's largest  
producer of graphite electrodes agreed Wednesday to plead guilty 
and serve 17 months in jail for fixing prices of a key steel-making 
component. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Krass, former president, chairman and chief executive  
officer of UCAR International Inc., also agreed to pay a $1.25 
million fine, the Justice Department said. He filed his plea in the 
U.S. District Court in Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	Krass is the second executive of UCAR, based in Nashville,  
Tenn., to agree to a fine and time in jail to settle charges of 
conspiring to fix prices in the graphite electrodes market. Last 
week, UCAR's former senior vice president and chief operating 
officer, Robert Hart, pleaded guilty for his part in the conspiracy 
and agreed to pay a $1 million fine and serve a nine-month jail 
term. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation into the industry continues, the Justice  
Department said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 06:00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Broncos' Romanowski Fined $10,000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Denver Broncos linebacker Bill Romanowski has been  
fined 
</P>
<P>
	$10,000 for a late hit to Tampa Bay quarterback Trent Dilfer.  
</P>
<P>
	The third-quarter hit came Sunday after Dilfer released a pass.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm surprised,'' Broncos defensive coordinator Greg Robinson  
said Wednesday when he learned of the fine, the second for 
Romanowski in as many weeks. ``I guess the cameras are on Bill at 
all times.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Romanowski received a $5,000 fine for a hit on Kansas City tight  
end Tony Gonzalez on Sept. 19, an NFL source told the Denver Post. 
</P>
<P>
	He wasn't penalized for either offense during the game. However,  
upon studying the videotapes, the NFL ruled the Broncos linebacker 
struck Dilfer with his helmet and that he used unnecessary 
roughness against Gonzalez, hitting the Chiefs' tight end in the 
neck and head. 
</P>
<P>
	The league is known to treat multiple infractions with increased  
fines, which could help explain the $5,000 hike between fines. 
</P>
<P>
	Romanowski has appealed the first fine and is expected to the do  
same with Wednesday's $10,000 fine. He could not be reached for 
comment, but is expected to comment today on whether he thinks they 
were warranted. 
</P>
<P>
	Fines are nothing new to Romanowski.  
</P>
<P>
	During the 1997 season, he compiled $27,500 worth of fines --  
$20,000 for a helmet-to-helmet hit that broke the jaw of former 
Carolina quarterback Kerry Collins, and a $7,500 fine for spitting 
on San Francisco wide receiver J.J. Stokes. NFL officials also did 
not penalize Romanowski for either of those plays. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 21:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pet Safety in Cars Becomes Focus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WAUSAU, Wis. (AP) -- People are treating their pets more like  
family members these days, taking them on the road for quick jaunts 
to the market or out for joyrides. 
</P>
<P>
	Some automakers and pet supply companies are taking notice --  
offering seat belts and other restraints so animals can go along 
for the ride safely. 
</P>
<P>
	A Wisconsin company sells harnesses for dogs to be strapped to a  
seat belt, while two automakers, Saab Car USA and Ford Motor Co., 
are introducing cars that offer ways to safeguard pets in case of 
an accident and keep drivers focused on the road. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are seeing a lot more of these kinds of devices out in the  
marketplace,'' said Kathy Bausch, director of projects for the 
Humane Society of the United States, the nation's largest animal 
protection organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Abbey White, 39, of Oakland, Calif., routinely takes Poppy, her  
3 1/2-year-old yellow lab, on errands to the gas station, the post 
office or to a park for exercise. 
</P>
<P>
	These days, Poppy sits or lies down in the passenger seat of  
White's station wagon, hooked to a seat belt by a harness. 
</P>
<P>
	White said she decided to buy the harness after she heard that  
the accident that injured best-selling author Stephen King was 
caused by a dog running loose in a minivan. 
</P>
<P>
	``If people have seat belts, why shouldn't animals?'' said  
White, who owns Abbie's Animal Care, a pet-sitting business. ``I 
really feel it is important to have pets tethered in the car and 
this is a great way to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gloria Bergquist, a spokeswoman for the Alliance of Automobile  
Manufacturers, a coalition of 11 car and light-truck manufacturers, 
said the industry's safety focus remains on humans because only 70 
percent of people routinely use seat belts. 
</P>
<P>
	As for pets, ``It had to happen. We have all heard stories of  
dogs distracting drivers in vehicles,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The potential market is enormous. There are an estimated 40  
million to 70 million pet owners in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Saab recently did a survey of its customers and found that more  
than 60 percent of owners had dogs and traveled with them 
frequently, spokesman Steve Janisse said. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, the Norcross, Ga.-based automaker began offering a  
line of supplies designed to make traveling with pets safer. 
</P>
<P>
	A new Saab wagon includes a standard cargo track also designed  
so a dog's leash can be hooked to it, allowing the dog some 
mobility but also restraining the pet, Janisse said. Since April, 
Saab has sold about 1,200 of the new wagons and 60 buyers bought 
the $49.95 VersaLeash for the cargo track, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also sells a $19.95 belt for strapping a dog to a  
seat belt, some 500 of which have been sold, Janisse said. 
</P>
<P>
	Later this year, Ford is making a ``pet package'' available for  
buyers of its new Focus subcompact. The feature includes a pet 
safety belt, insulated tip-resistant water bowl and other products 
designed to make travel for pets more convenient and comfortable. 
</P>
<P>
	``We realized a lot of our customers are pet owners and we  
wanted to address their needs,'' said Julie Roehm, Focus Brand 
manager. 
</P>
<P>
	The pet package is expected to sell for less than $200, she  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Veterinarians have been preaching pet safety belts for years,  
said Martin Smith, a veterinarian and co-owner of Doctors Foster &AMP; 
Smith, a northern Wisconsin mail-order company that publishes a 
160-page catalog with thousands of products for pet owners. 
</P>
<P>
	Foster &AMP; Smith, headquartered in Rhinelander, sells a $9.99  
harness that allows a dog to be strapped to a seat belt in any 
vehicle. The company sells 14,500 of the harnesses annually, 
promoting them as a way to protect pets in case of an accident and 
as a way to make sure drivers stay focused on the road. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith said he has treated hundreds of dogs who where injured  
when they jumped out of open car windows or were hurled about 
inside the cab in an accident. 
</P>
<P>
	He has also has seen first hand the trouble an untethered pet  
can cause. 
</P>
<P>
	Several years ago, at his veterinary clinic in Minocqua, a car  
crashed through a wall and into the waiting room because a golden 
retriever puppy climbed behind the brake pedal as the car arrived 
at the clinic. 
</P>
<P>
	The harnesses aren't just for dogs.  
</P>
<P>
	Barb Wargo, 51, of Southbury, Conn., has a seat-belt harness so  
her black cat Sooty can ride safely in the passenger seat of her 
BMW convertible and not jump out when she takes him for joy rides. 
</P>
<P>
	The charter trip didn't go too well.  
</P>
<P>
	``He meowed a lot. He was unhappy,'' Wargo said. ``He doesn't  
like the harness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Wargo was undeterred. ``I don't think it is silly,'' she  
said. ``I love my cat.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
