<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Infant, Maternal Death Rates Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Touting what they called one of the century's  
most significant advances in public health, federal officials said 
Thursday that infant and maternal mortality rates have dropped by 
more than 90 percent since 1900. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you look at the number of babies that have been saved  
during the 20th century, it's enormous,'' said Dr. Solomon Iyasu of 
the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention's Division of 
Reproductive Health. ``At the beginning of the century, 10 percent 
of all babies were dying. Now it's less than 1 percent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rate of infants who die before age 1 went from 100 per 1,000  
live births in 1915 to less than 7.2 per 1,000 in 1997, marking a 
decline the CDC said was unparalleled by other mortality reductions 
this century. 
</P>
<P>
	At the turn of the 20th century, six to nine out of every 1,000  
women died of pregnancy-related complications. The rate was less 
than .1 per 1,000 in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Early efforts to combat infant mortality focused on improving  
living conditions in urban areas, such as establishing safe 
drinking water and sewage and trash disposal. Rising standards of 
living, educational levels and access to health care also 
contributed to the decline. In addition, women started having fewer 
children and spacing them further apart. 
</P>
<P>
	But there wasn't much decline in maternal mortality rates during  
the first three decades of the century, until health care providers 
shifted their focus from infant health problems to a more holistic 
approach that included the mother, Iyasu said. 
</P>
<P>
	Delivery practices were the main factor in the high deaths among  
pregnant women -- most births were in the home and obstetrics was a 
specialty was shunned by many physicians. 
</P>
<P>
	The death rate began decreasing during the 1930s and 1940s with  
the introduction of penicillin and other antibiotics along with the 
availability of safer blood supplies. 
</P>
<P>
	The declines slowed during the 1950s and early 1960s, primarily  
because of inadequate programs to reduce deaths among children who 
were born premature or with a low birthweight. The CDC said 
Medicaid and other federal programs implemented during the late 
1960s helped reverse that. 
</P>
<P>
	During the 1990s, the downward trend continued as cases of  
sudden infant death syndrome dropped 50 percent after parents were 
urged to place sleeping infants on their backs. 
</P>
<P>
	``The good news is that the infant mortality rate and the  
maternal mortality rate has declined for all groups during the 
century but there is still a gap that we need to concentrate on,'' 
Iyasu said. 
</P>
<P>
	For example: Black infants are more than twice as likely to die  
than whites and black women are more than three times as likely to 
die as a result of pregnancy-related complications than whites. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
