<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senior PGA Player Kiefer Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Jack Kiefer, a two-time winner on  
the Senior PGA Tour who was diagnosed last year with cancer in his 
spinal cord, has died. He was 59. 
</P>
<P>
	A memorial service for Kiefer will be at Tanglewood Park, site  
of the Senior Tour's Vantage Championship in Clemmons, N.C., after 
the first round on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Kiefer, who died Sept. 24 at his home in Stuart, Fla., won the  
1994 Ralphs Senior Classic and the 1997 du Maurier Champions, when 
he finished 16th on the money list. He played 12 events in 1998 
before he was diagnosed with cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	He joined the senior tour in 1990 after finishing second in  
Q-school, and had the reputation as an ironman for playing at least 
30 tournaments a year every season except 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Kiefer, born Jan. 1, 1940 in Columbia, Pa., was a pitcher for  
Millersville State College in 1961, and his knuckleball earned him 
a contract with the Detroit Tigers. But after three days in camp, 
he left baseball and took up golf. 
</P>
<P>
	He turned professional in 1967. He was inducted two years ago  
into the New Jersey PGA Hall of Fame. Kiefer won the New Jersey 
State Open three times. 
</P>
<P>
	Kiefer is survived by his wife, Jan, and a daughter, Jennifer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Contributions can be made to the Martin Memorial Foundation  
Cancer Center, P.O. Box 9010, Stuart, Fla., 34995. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
