<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Steel Group To Be Named Corus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The group formed by the recent merger of British  
Steel PLC and Dutch metals producer Koninklijke Hoogovens NV is to 
be named Corus, the companies said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The newly merged group was initially called BSKH. Corus has no  
specific meaning but is meant to be a name with international 
appeal, British Steel said. 
</P>
<P>
	Corus would have its headquarters in London and 66,000 employees  
worldwide. Its shares are to start trading next Wednesday on stock 
exchanges in London, Amsterdam and New York. 
</P>
<P>
	European Union regulators approved the planned $6.24 billion  
merger in July. The merger, which would create Europe's largest 
steelmaker, has been approved by shareholders and financial 
authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	The last body still to give its nod to the deal, Britain's High  
Court of Justice, is expected to do so on Monday, British Steel 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The British company, which has sales nearly double those of its  
Dutch partner, would have a 62 percent share in the new group. 
Hoogovens would control the remainder. 
</P>
<P>
	The combined company would rank as the world's third-biggest  
steel manufacturer with annual sales worth $14.8 billion. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
