<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reloaded Rangers: Ready To Roll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The New York Rangers, after going on a big free-agent shopping  
spree this year, will get to see if their investment will pay off 
as they open the NHL season tonight in Edmonton. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our expectations have to be higher,'' Adam Graves said ``We  
made some key additions. We put ourselves into position (to be more 
competitive).'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Rangers might not yet be the Dallas Stars, the defending  
Stanley Cup champions who open the season at home against 
Pittsburgh in the only other NHL game tonight. But they have spared 
no expense to put together a team that will at least compete for a 
playoff berth, spending a reported $67 million in contracts to six 
free agents. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rangers have missed the playoffs for two straight seasons  
despite one of the highest payrolls in hockey, including the $5.5 
million paid to Wayne Gretzky. 
</P>
<P>
	With Gretzky retired and four of New York's defensemen gone from  
last year's team, the Rangers will have a dramatic new look for 
1999-00. Included among the new people are Theo Fleury, a 40-goal 
scorer who was the jewel of the free-agent crop. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rangers also landed forwards Valeri Kamensky and Tim Taylor,  
defensemen Stephane Quintal and Sylvain Lefebvre and goalie Kirk 
McLean in the free-agent market. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rangers also re-signed All-Star defenseman Brian Leetch,  
keeping him from going into the free-agent market himself. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, New York shored up its defense further by acquiring  
veteran Kevin Hatcher from Pittsburgh for defenseman Peter 
Popovich. 
</P>
<P>
	``We played some good games (in the exhibition season) and I  
think we got a good feel how we have to play as a team in order to 
be successful,'' Fleury said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rangers had a 6-3-0 record in September.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're all a little unsure, but excited to get the season  
started and find out what's going to happen,'' Leetch said. ``When 
we get this many players coming from outside the organization. ... 
it's a lot of uncertainty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Rangers-Oilers game will include a special tribute to  
Gretzky, who played for both teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're fortunate to be there for a great night for a great  
man,'' Graves said, ``but we have to be ready to play. We have to 
make sure we're focused.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the Oilers will stage a tribute to Gretzky, the Stars will  
be raising their Stanley Cup banner in Dallas. Last season, the 
Stars won their second straight President's Trophy for the top 
record in the NHL in addition to their first Stanley Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's going to be hard to be as good as last year  
during the regular season,'' Guy Carbonneau said. ``The same goal 
is in our mind this year, but we know it'll be much harder because 
everybody wants to try to beat the best.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Saturday's games, it will be Carolina at Boston, Toronto at  
Montreal, Ottawa at Philadelphia, New Jersey at Atlanta, New York 
Islanders at Tampa Bay, Washington at Florida, Buffalo at Detroit, 
Phoenix at St. Louis, Los Angeles at Nashville, Anaheim at Dallas, 
the Rangers at Vancouver and Calgary at San Jose. 
</P>
<P>
	The New Jersey-Atlanta matchup will be the first game for the  
expansion Thrashers, played in their new Philips Arena. The 
Thrashers are the second expansion team in two years in the NHL, 
following the Nashville Predators last season. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you look how Nashville played last year, they were in every  
game, and we want to be there, also,'' Thrashers captain Kelly 
Buchberger said. 
</P>
<P>
	Teams were still trying to fine-tune their rosters on the eve of  
opening night. 
</P>
<P>
	Vancouver signed free agent defenseman Ed Jovanovski; Calgary  
traded defenseman Todd Simpson to Florida for left wing Bill 
Lindsay; Edmonton re-signed defenseman Roman Hamrlik; St. Louis 
claimed defenseman Todd Reirden off waivers from Edmonton, and 
Dallas claimed forward Chris Murray off waivers from Chicago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
