<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Slaying Victim ID'd After 15 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- He was found shot to death in an abandoned house  
an hour's drive south of Atlanta, badly decomposed and without 
identification. Local officials buried him in a cheap casket under 
the name John Doe. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifteen years later, he has a name and a history. He is Carl  
Rowland, an 18-year-old who disappeared in 1984 while trying to 
hitchhike from Atlanta to Florida for the Fourth of July. 
</P>
<P>
	Rowland's mother and sister visited his grave for the first time  
Wednesday, a day after authorities matched X-rays of Rowland's 
teeth with those of the unidentified victim. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought whenever I retired this would still be an unsolved  
mystery,'' said Rene Chamblee, chief investigator for the Lamar 
County sheriff's department. ``I've asked the question 100 times: 
`Whose son are you? Who do you belong to?' ... And now I have the 
answers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Chamblee hoped she would be able to close the case two  
years ago, when a former sheriff's dispatcher confessed to being 
the killer. But he insisted he didn't know the victim's name. 
</P>
<P>
	It took a bit of luck to find out who John Doe really was.  
</P>
<P>
	Rowland's mother, who asked authorities not to release her name,  
was discussing her son with a co-worker several weeks ago. She 
agreed to hire the woman's boyfriend -- private investigator Ed 
Hood, a former policeman in Barnesville, the Lamar County seat. 
</P>
<P>
	Remembering the John Doe case, Hood contacted Mrs. Chamblee to  
see if there was any possible connection. There was. 
</P>
<P>
	John Doe and Rowland were the same height -- 6 feet. They had the  
same shoe size. A composite drawing made from the killer's 
description had a resemblance to Rowland. 
</P>
<P>
	Dental X-rays revealed Rowland, like John Doe, had four impacted  
wisdom teeth. They also each had two fillings in the same teeth. 
</P>
<P>
	``It did not take an expert or a rocket scientist to say, `Oh  
this is Carl Rowland,''' Mrs. Chamblee said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rowland's mother plans to move his body from Lamar County to  
Atlanta, authorities said. Investigators have told her everything 
they know about the case, showing her crime scene photos and 
photographs of her son's confessed killer, who died earlier this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a blessing in that she is getting some closure to  
knowing the fate of Carl,'' said Abe Sharony, the woman's lawyer. 
``The other side is she has received all this information and 
images that have almost created a video in her mind of what 
happened. It's so real it's almost hard for her to cope with it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dennis Cloud, who confessed two years ago to shooting Rowland,  
said he shot the teen-ager in self-defense after Rowland tried to 
rob him with a knife. He was charged with murder and concealing a 
death, but died before he could be tried. 
</P>
<P>
	Police never found a knife. With both the killer and victim  
dead, Mrs. Chamblee said, what really happened in that abandoned 
house will likely remain a mystery. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 22:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> French Locate Seizure Gene </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	French scientists have identified a gene associated with the  
kind of brain seizure that killed Olympic sprinter Florence 
Griffith Joyner, a step that may lead to early testing and better 
treatments. 
</P>
<P>
	Faulty copies of the gene, known as CCM1, are responsible for  
the development of tangled blood vessels in the brain known as 
cavernous angiomas, according to a study by three laboratories in 
Paris. 
</P>
<P>
	The results appear in the October issue of the journal Nature  
Genetics. 
</P>
<P>
	The abnormality is found in one in every 40 Americans, and the  
condition is inherited in half of the cases. 
</P>
<P>
	In most cases, these tangles remain quite small for many years,  
making them hard to find even with sophisticated imaging equipment 
and risky to remove. Eventually, the tangles swell and engulf more 
of the brain. Without surgery, they trigger seizures, paralysis and 
potentially fatal strokes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Often, the first clinical sign of the disease is a stroke or  
death,'' said geneticist Doug Marchuk of Duke University, a member 
of an American research team that has also linked CCM1 with the 
brain lesions and will release its study next month. ``A DNA test 
should be readily available. If you know who is at risk, you can 
aggressively treat them early.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An autopsy showed that Ms. Griffith Joyner died in her sleep a  
year ago from a seizure triggered as a result of cavernous angioma. 
She was 38. 
</P>
<P>
	The Olympic gold medalist had a history of seizures in the  
1990s. But it is unknown whether she had a bad copy of the CCM1 
gene and suffered from the inherited form of the brain lesions 
</P>
<P>
	On June 13, Houston Astros manager Larry Dierker suffered a  
violent seizure during a baseball game. Surgeons removed a 
cavernous angioma, and he returned to the dugout a month later. 
</P>
<P>
	In the French study, researcher Elisabeth Tournier-Lasserve and  
others examined unrelated patients from 20 families with histories 
of cavernous angiomas, including a high frequency of multiple 
lesions. CCM1 mutations were found in 12 of the patients. 
</P>
<P>
	In the U.S. study, 16 of 21 Mexican-American families were found  
to share the mutation. Their report will be published in the 
November issue of Human Molecular Genetics. 
</P>
<P>
	``Until now, little has been known about the molecular  
mechanisms leading to these lesions,'' said geneticist Mikka 
Vikkula of Catholic University in Belgium. ``Identifying the 
causative gene and the kinds of mutations it contains allows us to 
start thinking of completely new ways of treating the disorder.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neither study answered several lingering questions about CCM1,  
including whether the gene is implicated in non-inherited forms of 
the disease. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
