<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tough Week To Be an Artist in NYC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The message on the wall of the Brooklyn Museum  
of Art looked like a traffic sign: ``Danger. ART.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Danger, indeed.  
</P>
<P>
	New York's art world has rarely been more hazardous than it was  
this week. 
</P>
<P>
	A dispute over an exhibit containing a dung-plastered portrait  
of the Virgin Mary threatens to cost the Brooklyn Museum of Art 
millions in city funds. An art dealer was busted for distributing 
live ammunition from an artist's ``bullet bowl'' at her gallery. 
And an artist was arrested after flinging horse manure at the 
Brooklyn museum. 
</P>
<P>
	Artists are discovering the two toughest critics in New York may  
be Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and the Police Department. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest flap in the centuries-old battle over what  
constitutes art started with Giuliani taking on the Brooklyn museum 
over an exhibit that previously played in London and includes the 
picture of the Virgin Mary and dissected pigs floating in 
formaldehyde. 
</P>
<P>
	Giuliani ripped the exhibit as ``sick stuff'' and promised to  
withhold $7 million in annual city funding, touching off a court 
battle that remains unsettled. The exhibit is still scheduled to 
open on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, on Wednesday night, Mary Boone was arrested at her Fifth  
Avenue gallery after visitors to the one-man show by artist Tom 
Sachs were invited to take home a souvenir: a 9 mm bullet. A vase 
filled with 100 live bullets was found by police on the reception 
desk. 
</P>
<P>
	The ammunition was in keeping with Sachs' work -- his signature  
artwork is homemade guns. Police, after determining the guns were 
functional, seized them along with the bullets. 
</P>
<P>
	Boone was charged with illegal distribution of ammunition and  
other misdemeanors. Her lawyer, Jed Poretz, did not return a call. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday afternoon, self-proclaimed artist Scott LoBaido was  
grabbed by police for throwing the horse manure at the Brooklyn 
museum. He said the excrement embodied his First Amendment right to 
protest the upcoming exhibit. 
</P>
<P>
	Police disagreed, taking him away after less than five minutes.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm expressing myself creatively!'' shouted LoBaido, who  
charged that the upcoming exhibit was anti-Catholic, as police led 
him off. ``You can't stop me.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
