<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mortgage Rates Fall to 2-Month Low / National Mortgage Survey  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The average interest rate on 30-year  
fixed-rate mortgages fell to 7.70 percent this week, the lowest 
level in two months and the fourth straight weekly decline. 
</P>
<P>
	The average was down from 7.76 percent last week, according to a  
weekly survey released Thursday by Freddie Mac, the mortgage 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Mortgages rates have been on an upward climb for much of this  
year. The average rates on a 30-year mortgage hit a low for the 
year of 6.74 percent at the end of January and a high of 8.15 
percent in mid-August. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifteen-year mortgages, a popular option for refinancing,  
averaged 7.35 percent this week, also down from the average of 7.40 
percent last week. 
</P>
<P>
	On one-year adjustable-rate mortgages, lenders were asking an  
average initial rate of 6.12 percent this week, down from 6.19 
percent the previous week. 
</P>
<P>
	The rates do not include add-on fees known as points, which  
averaged at or just over 1 percent of the loan amount for all three 
types of mortgages. 
</P>
<P>
	``Amid continuing signs of robust health in the housing  
industry, mortgage rates dropped a little more this week,'' said 
Robert Van Order, Freddie Mac's chief economist. From now until the 
end of the year, rates are expected to fluctuate between 7.75 
percent and 8 percent, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, the Mortgage Bankers Association of America said  
that mortgage loan applications for the week ending Sept. 24 
decreased 2.8 percent from the previous week and were down 56.6 
percent compared to the same week last year. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
