<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Academics, Retailers Honor Bar Code </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Academics from some of the nation's top Ivy  
League schools joined executives from Wal-Mart and other retailers 
Thursday to praise the bar code -- that ubiquitous and unfathomable 
collection of lines and numbers that made its debut 25 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	At a daylong conference at the Smithsonian Institution, the  
executives and researchers recalled the earliest days of the humble 
technology, including sometimes epic arguments among supporters, 
and forecast the next generation of bar codes. 
</P>
<P>
	Though consumers pay them little heed, the retail and grocery  
industries describe universal price codes -- scanned an estimated 5 
billion times each day -- as among the most significant advances 
since, well, sliced bread. 
</P>
<P>
	``In all my years, I've seen nothing that has changed the  
industry like the universal product code,'' said Bob Martin, former 
president and chairman of Wal-Mart Stores Inc.'s international 
division. 
</P>
<P>
	During some of the earliest days' most heated debates over the  
technology's development, ``we had to sit in alphabetical order 
because we fought a lot,'' Martin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Since their debut in 1974, the familiar black-and-white symbols  
have found themselves affixed to items from surgical instruments to 
Alaskan sled dogs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Museum of American History organized the conference to  
coincide with its exhibit about the technology, ``25 Years Behind 
Bars,'' which runs through March. David Allison, who coordinated 
the exhibit, said the museum sought to ``take something that is 
today, everywhere, and help people understand the story behind the 
story.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``People do want to know what drives their lives,'' Allison  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Alan Haberman, who was on the 1970s committee that chose the  
design of today's bar codes, said consumers appreciated the 
benefits that grocery scanners offered even when they didn't 
understand how they worked. 
</P>
<P>
	The first bar-code scanner was used June 26, 1974, to buy a  
10-pack of Wrigley's gum in a Marsh Supermarket in Troy, Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	``From day one, they knew we were going faster,'' Haberman said.  
``They were getting through the lines faster. The customer 
appreciates the fact that the checker has an easier job. They could 
talk to her, watch to see what she was doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	These bar-code experts also described the technology's future:  
Starting in 2005, the codes will be redesigned to use 13 and 14 
digits, up from today's 10 numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	They also announced a new multimillion dollar research center at  
the Massachusetts Institute of Technology to develop the next 
generation of bar codes -- tiny radio transmitters on products that 
can track how they were shipped and when they were sold and can 
even distinguish individual cans of Coke or bottles of milk. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's definitely time to pick up the gauntlet, time for the  
Internet generation to pick up this thing and move it ahead,'' said 
Kevin Ashton, director of the new MIT research center. 
</P>
<P>
	The lack of public attention to the bar code doesn't distress  
Haberman. 
</P>
<P>
	``Isn't that what you hope happens with most standards?'' he  
said. ``The proof that this is successful is that everybody takes 
it for granted.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
