<HEADLINE> AutoNation To Spin Off Rental Unit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- AutoNation Inc., the country's  
largest automobile retailer, said Thursday it will spin off its 
troubled rental-car division by issuing stock in the new company to 
current AutoNation shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	AutoNation, which is controlled by billionaire H. Wayne  
Huizenga, spent about $1.8 billion over the past two years to 
acquire five rental car companies, including National Car Rental 
and Alamo Rent-A-Car. 
</P>
<P>
	But the businesses have suffered from too many cars, problems  
with the reservation system, and undercutting its own published 
rates, according to analysts. 
</P>
<P>
	``The retail business is doing extremely well, both in sales  
revenue and earnings, but the rental business has had a difficult 
business of late,'' said Jim Donahue, a company spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	On Aug. 2, the company announced it would separate the rental  
car business. That news was soon followed by the resignation of 
William Lobeck, president of AutoNation's rental car group. His 
successor has not been named. 
</P>
<P>
	Huizenga tried to sell the rental business to at least one  
competitor, Enterprise Rent-A-Car, but couldn't strike a deal. With 
no takers, he decided to spin off the business to shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	AutoNation shareholders will receive one share in the new  
company for each 6 to 8 shares in AutoNation they hold. The 
distribution will take place in late January to anyone holding 
AutoNation shares in late December. The exact share ratio and 
distribution dates have not been set. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of the Ft. Lauderdale, Fla.-based retailer rose 56 1/4 cents  
to $12.50 in trading on the New York Stock Exchange, well below the 
one-year high of $18.37 set in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, AutoNation tapped the president and chief executive  
of luxury car maker Mercedes-Benz USA Inc. to be its chief 
executive. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael J. Jackson was named to replace Steven Berrard, who left  
earlier this year. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
