<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grain, Soybeans Fall on Supply News / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices fell in trading  
on the Chicago Board of Trade Thursday on higher-than-expected 
supply numbers released by the government. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures fell in reaction to U.S. grain stock estimates of  
1.796 billion bushels, about 100 million bushels higher than 
anticipated, market participants said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was bigger than the trade was looking for, surprisingly  
so,'' said Don Roose, president of Iowa-based U.S. Commodities Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	There was other bearish news in corn: harvest conditions  
improved this week; and there are forecasts for rain in the Midwest 
this weekend and early next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures plummeted on estimates that quarterly stocks were  
much larger than expected. Roose said the corn and wheat stocks 
indicate a serious decline in feed use. 
</P>
<P>
	The stock reports were released today by the U.S. Department of  
Agriculture. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean futures fell in sympathy with corn and wheat, but losses  
were limited by stock estimates that were down slightly. 
</P>
<P>
	In trading Thursday, wheat for December delivery fell 8 1/2 cents  
to $2.75 3/4 a bushel; December corn fell 5 1/2 cents to $2.08 1/4 a bushel; 
December oats fell 2 cents to $1.13 1/4 a bushel; and November 
soybeans fell 1/2 cent to $4.91 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, cattle futures prices were higher in trading on the  
Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while pork futures were mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle futures were up .97 cent to 68.27 cents a  
pound; October feeder cattle rose 1.17 cent to 81.07 cents a pound; 
October lean hogs fell .43 cent to 48.97 cents a pound; and 
February pork bellies fell .42 cent to 63.80 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 13:00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gov't. Launches Y2K Travel Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government started warning airline  
travelers about foreign airport and airline Y2K readiness Thursday, 
but one senator questioned why the information was so sketchy. 
</P>
<P>
	The advisory was made public through a new Transportation  
Department Web site, www.fly2k.dot.gov, which will serve as the 
federal government's clearinghouse for Year 2000 traveler 
information during the next three months. 
</P>
<P>
	For those interested in Australia's readiness, for example, the  
site says: ``Reports indicate steps are under way in the civil 
aviation Y2K programs of this country. However, there is 
insufficient information available to estimate the overall status 
of Y2K preparations at this time. It is difficult to estimate the 
likelihood, length or severity of any disruptions in the civil 
aviation system.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The same description is included for numerous other countries,  
followed by a recommendation that travelers ``be prepared to cope 
with disruptions and delays in services.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Such a lack of detail prompted Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn.,  
to complain during a hearing called to assess the transportation 
industry and its Year 2000 readiness. 
</P>
<P>
	Dodd threatened to file legislation grounding any U.S. aviation  
certificate holder who does not respond to a government 
questionnaire about their readiness by mid-November. 
</P>
<P>
	Kenneth Mead, inspector general of the Transportation  
Department, told the hearing that 1,900 certificate holders have 
yet to respond. The Federal Aviation Administration said none of 
them are major airlines and many are manufacturing companies or one 
plane crop-dusters. 
</P>
<P>
	Dodd also complained groups such as the International Air  
Transport Association, which represents 265 international airlines, 
were not making public all the information they had culled from 
their members. An IATA official said airlines agreed to provide the 
information only if it was not made public, which could lead to 
lawsuits against them. 
</P>
<P>
	``Shouldn't I have a right to that information?'' Dodd said.  
</P>
<P>
	Thomas Windmuller, who testified on behalf of the transport  
association, said passengers should trust the airlines to use the 
information wisely. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't imagine any of our member airlines would ever  
compromise safety,'' Windmuller said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Year 2000 problem can plague older computers, since some  
were designed to recognize years in a two-digit format, such as 
``99'' for 1999. There are questions about whether systems will 
malfunction when the new century starts, since some computers could 
confuse ``00'' for 1900 instead of 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	That is of particular concern in aviation, where computers  
control everything from radars to runway lights. In June, the FAA 
announced that it had repaired and tested all of its computers, and 
U.S. and Canadian airlines recently offered the same assurance. 
</P>
<P>
	There are two lingering questions: the readiness of airports  
both domestically and abroad, and the readiness of international 
airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	In launching the new site, Transportation Secretary Rodney  
Slater said that the top three travel destination from the United 
States -- Canada, Britain and Japan -- report they will be fully Y2K 
ready by the end of the year. All told, the Web site covers almost 
90 countries with direct service to and from the United States. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 07:40:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Highlights of Reagan Biography </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	In ``Dutch: A Memoir of Ronald Reagan,'' biographer Edmund  
Morris writes: 
</P>
<P>
	--George Bush felt unappreciated as Reagan's vice president, a  
claim Bush denies. 
</P>
<P>
	--Reagan came closer to dying after the 1981 assassination  
attempt than was let on at the time. Some former aides say Morris 
overdramatized the aftermath of Reagan's surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	--Reagan tried to forgive his attempted assassin, John Hinckley.  
In his diary, Reagan wrote, ``I realized I couldn't ask for God's 
help while at the same time I felt hatred for the mixed up young 
man who had shot me. Isn't that the meaning of the lost sheep?'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Reagan said of aide Alexander Haig: ``It's amazing how sound he  
can be on international matters, but how utterly paranoid with 
regard to the people he must work with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--French President Francois Mitterrand told Canadian Prime  
Minister Pierre Trudeau that Reagan ``is a man without ideas and 
without culture.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Reagan on President Carter: ``And after he left here, he was  
the only president to become a nobody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Reagan was ``greatly depressed,'' according to his diary, about  
the ABC television movie ``The Day After,'' about a nuclear war. 
</P>
<P>
	--Reagan's role was unclear in the diversion of money to the  
Nicaraguan Contras from illicit missile sales to Iran. ``My 
suspicion, for what it's worth, is that Dutch (Reagan) did 
authorize the transfer, not having the smallest comprehension of 
the laws he was subverting.'' Morris said. 
</P>
<P>
	--Reagan sent a love letter to wife, Nancy, saying her love was  
``like fruit of the month with a lifetime subscription -- a 
perpetual motion happiness machine. It starts off fresh and brand 
new every day shining up my whole world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Reagan began conserving his mental resources after second-term  
cancer surgery, focusing on ``rescue of the hostages in Lebanon, 
Contra aid, strategic defense, abolition of nuclear weapons, moral 
warfare against communism and continued restoration of the national 
spirit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Reagan was at his best dealing with Soviet leader Mikhail  
Gorbachev and said of him: ``You could almost get to like the guy. 
I keep telling myself I mustn't do it, because he could turn.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Reagan was aloof and ``never seemed to need anybody'' except  
his wife. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 13:30:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Conectiv Selling Nuclear Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) -- Conectiv will sell its share in three  
nuclear power plants for $20 million as part of a restructuring 
plan, the company announced Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The utility, based in Wilmington, Del., is selling its minority  
ownership to other utility companies which already operate the 
plants and own the majority of the shares. 
</P>
<P>
	PECO Energy Co. of Philadelphia, and PSEG Power, a subsidiary of  
New Jersey's Public Service Electric &AMP; Gas Co., are splitting 
Conectiv's 15 percent interest in the Peach Bottom Atomic Power 
Station in York County, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
	PSEG Power will also buy Conectiv's 14.8 percent interest in the  
Salem Nuclear Generating Station and its 5 percent interest in the 
Hope Creek Nuclear Generating Station. Both of those plants are 
located in Salem County, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	Although sales of the nuclear power plants must be approved by  
government regulators, officials with Conectiv said they believe 
the deals will close by the middle of next year. 
</P>
<P>
	The selloff is part of Conectiv's efforts to raise $1 billion in  
cash to help make the company more flexible for deregulation of the 
consumer energy market. 
</P>
<P>
	Conectiv, created last year by the merger of Delmarva Power &AMP;  
Light Co. and Atlantic Energy Co., provides electricity, natural 
gas and telecommunications services to about 1 million homes and 
businesses in New Jersey, Delaware, Maryland and Virginia. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
