<DOCNO> APW19990930.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 12:50:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Union sells Raleigh Building </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- First Union Corp. has sold the 29-story  
First Union Capitol Center here to a New York-based pension fund 
for $73.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank will continue to occupy about 30 percent of the  
543,896-square-foot building, and has committed to being the anchor 
tenant for 25 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The center, built in 1991, is the tallest tower in Raleigh, N.C.  
</P>
<P>
	The sale to Capitol Center Acquisition LLD, a unit of DRA  
Advisors, took effect Tuesday. As part of the agreement, the buyer 
intends to build a 750-space parking deck retail space on the 
ground floor. 
</P>
<P>
	First Union had been looking for a buyer since last fall.  
</P>
<P>
	First Union provides financial services to more than 16 million  
customers throughout the East Coast and the nation. At the end of 
June, First Union had assets of $230 billion. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
