<DOCNO> APW19990930.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 23:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Academics, Retailers Honor Bar Code </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Consumers might ignore them but to the grocery  
industry, bar code technology -- which made its debut 25 years ago -- 
is among the most significant advances since sliced bread. 
</P>
<P>
	Academics from some of the nation's top Ivy League schools  
joined executives from Wal-Mart and other retailers Thursday to 
praise the bar code -- that ubiquitous and unfathomable collection 
of lines and numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	At a daylong conference at the Smithsonian Institution,  
executives and researchers recalled the earliest days of the humble 
technology, including sometimes epic arguments among supporters, 
and forecast the next generation of bar codes, which are scanned an 
estimated 5 billion times each day. 
</P>
<P>
	``In all my years, I've seen nothing that has changed the  
industry like the universal product code,'' said Bob Martin, former 
president and chairman of Wal-Mart Stores Inc.'s international 
division. 
</P>
<P>
	During some of the earliest days' most heated debates in  
conference rooms about the technology's development, ``we had to 
sit in alphabetical order because we fought a lot,'' Martin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Since their debut in 1974, the familiar black-and-white symbols  
have found themselves affixed to items from surgical instruments to 
Alaskan sled dogs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Museum of American History organized the conference to  
coincide with its exhibit about the technology, ``25 Years Behind 
Bars,'' which runs through March. David Allison, who coordinated 
the exhibit, said the museum sought to ``take something that is 
today, everywhere, and help people understand the story behind the 
story.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``People do want to know what drives their lives,'' Allison  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Alan Haberman, who was on the 1970s committee that chose the  
design of today's bar codes, said consumers appreciated the 
benefits that grocery scanners offered even when they didn't 
understand how they worked. 
</P>
<P>
	The first bar-code scanner was used June 26, 1974, to buy a  
10-pack of Wrigley's gum in a Marsh Supermarket in Troy, Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	``From day one, they knew we were going faster,'' Haberman said.  
``They were getting through the lines faster. The customer 
appreciates the fact that the checker has an easier job. They could 
talk to her, watch to see what she was doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	These bar-code experts also described the technology's future:  
Starting in 2005, the codes will be redesigned to use 13 and 14 
digits, up from today's 10 numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	They also announced a new multimillion dollar research center at  
the Massachusetts Institute of Technology to develop the next 
generation of bar codes -- tiny radio transmitters on products that 
can track how they were shipped and when they were sold and can 
even distinguish individual cans of soda or bottles of milk. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's definitely time to pick up the gauntlet, time for the  
Internet generation to pick up this thing and move it ahead,'' said 
Kevin Ashton, director of the new MIT research center. 
</P>
<P>
	The lack of public attention to the bar code doesn't distress  
Haberman. 
</P>
<P>
	``Isn't that what you hope happens with most standards?'' he  
said. ``The proof that this is successful is that everybody takes 
it for granted.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 13:36:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Giuliani Declares War on a Painting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- City officials have fired another round in their  
escalating fight with the Brooklyn Museum of Art, accusing the 
museum of displaying controversial work just to drive up its value. 
</P>
<P>
	The accusations made Wednesday by Deputy Mayor Joseph Lhota and  
the city's top lawyer, Michael Hess, came a day after the museum 
sued to stop Mayor Rudolph Giuliani from freezing its funding over 
the dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	Giuliani has threatened to cut city funding to the museum  
because of its decision to display an exhibit that includes a black 
Madonna decorated with elephant dung and pornographic cutouts. The 
funding amounts to $7 million, or about one-third of the museum's 
budget. 
</P>
<P>
	The pieces are from advertising executive Charles Saatchi's  
collection. Lhota and Hess say the museum's board planned the 
``Sensation'' exhibition so the works would fetch high prices at 
auction once the show closes. 
</P>
<P>
	The museum's board members are ``shilling for a British subject  
who is a multimillionaire and trying to enhance his art 
collection,'' Lhota said. 
</P>
<P>
	He cited a New York Observer article which said that after the  
show closed in London, Saatchi auctioned 128 pieces from his 
collection, many of them by artists in the show. 
</P>
<P>
	Giuliani, on a fund-raising trip in California, said he has been  
in touch with Lhota and Hess about their accusations. He said the 
project raises the question whether a publicly funded museum should 
engage in ``shock commercialization.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Andree Corroon, a spokeswoman for Christie's, which is helping  
sponsor the show, said the auction house had no plans for an 
auction. 
</P>
<P>
	``This bewildering accusation has absolutely no substance, is  
absolutely not true,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, the museum called the accusations ``preposterous  
and misleading.'' The show opens Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a federal judge has been asked to decide whether to  
restore the museum's funding. The museum sued the city on Tuesday, 
saying Giuliani's act violates the First Amendment. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, the Senate agreed unanimously Wednesday to a  
non-binding measure calling for the withholding of federal funds 
from the museum unless it cancels the exhibit. Independent Sen. Bob 
Smith of New Hampshire said the museum has received $500,000 from 
the National Endowment for the Arts in the last three years. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Wednesday, singer David Bowie -- who recorded an audio tour  
for museum visitors -- joined leaders of major New York City museums 
in support of the Brooklyn Museum. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sensation represents some of the best, worst but definitely  
most extreme of the high-profile work to have come out of Britain 
in the last 10 years or so,'' Bowie said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The leaders of two dozen cultural institutions -- including the  
Metropolitan Museum and the Museum of Modern Art -- signed a letter 
protesting the mayor's funding cut. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 13:36:01 </DATE_TIME>
