<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Sept. 30, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Pentagon To Look at Korea Killings  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Army Secretary Louis Caldera today promised a  
``complete and thorough review'' of accounts of mass killings of 
South Korean civilians by U.S. soldiers early in the Korean war. 
Caldera said The Associated Press account ``clearly has raised new 
information that demanded that it be looked into.'' President 
Clinton said the Pentagon ``wants to get to the bottom of it.'' 
Accounts of South Korean villagers and of a dozen ex-GIs who either 
witnessed or were involved in the killings were reported by The AP 
yesterday. 

</P>
<P>
	Earthquake Rocks Southern Mexico  
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A strong earthquake rocked southern Mexico  
today, toppling church towers and knocking over old homes in Oaxaca 
and shaking buildings in the capital. At least five people were 
killed and an unknown number injured. The quake had a preliminary 
magnitude of 7.5 and was centered 275 miles southeast of Mexico 
City, the U.S. Geological Survey in Golden, Colo. said. Moderate 
damage was reported in Oaxaca City, the state capital, where church 
steeples and many homes collapsed. Federal officials said water and 
sewage treatment plants were damaged in 95 percent of Oaxaca state. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Uranium Workers Contaminated  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- A major leak at a uranium-processing plant in  
northeastern Japan today sent radiation levels skyrocketing. At 
least three workers were hospitalized -- two in critical condition -- 
and at least 34 others may have been contaminated. The nuclear 
reaction is continuing and workers have begun removing water from 
the cooling equipment around the tank to stop it. Five residents 
were also exposed to radiation, a local official said on customary 
condition of anonymity. More than 310,000 people were ordered not 
to leave their homes and officials shut down schools and train 
service in the region. 

</P>
<P>
	Bradley Outraises Gore in Quarter  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bill Bradley, his Democratic presidential  
campaign surging, raised more money than Vice President Al Gore 
over the last three months, and has more money in the bank heading 
into the final quarter of the year. On the Republican side, Texas 
Gov. George W. Bush continued to shatter fund-raising records, 
reporting raising more than $56 million through the end of 
September. He has about $37 million cash on hand. Bradley raised an 
estimated $6.7 million between July and September, a spokeswoman 
said today. Gore raised around $6.5 million during the same period, 
according to senior advisers. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Signs Spending Resolution  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today signed a resolution to  
keep federal agencies financed for the next three weeks, ``not 
because I wanted to but because it was the only way to avoid 
another government shutdown.'' He accused the Republican Congress 
of resorting to ``gimmicks and gamesmanship'' instead of meeting 
the Oct. 1 deadline for passage of the appropriations bills that 
finance the government. The resolution extends funding until Oct. 
21. 

</P>
<P>
	Mixup May Have Doomed Mars Orbiter  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A mixup over metric and English measurements  
likely caused the loss of the $125 million Mars Climate Orbiter as 
it started to circle the planet last week, officials said today. 
The error caused the probe to fly too close to the red planet, 
causing the spacecraft to break up or burn up in the Martian 
atmosphere that it had been designed to study, mission controllers 
at NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory said. 

</P>
<P>
	German Wins Nobel in Literature  
</P>
<P>
	STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) -- Novelist Guenter Grass, whose  
explorations of Germany's troubled century made him one of the 
best-known German writers of the post-World War II generation, won 
the 1999 Nobel Prize in literature today. The Swedish Academy cited 
Grass' first novel, ``The Tin Drum,'' published in 1959, for 
ushering in a new era for German literature ``after decades of 
linguistic and moral destruction.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Rises 151; Nasdaq Gains 25  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 151.65 points at 10,365.13. Advancers on the New York Stock 
Exchange led decliners 1,768-1,178. The Nasdaq composite index was 
up 25.78 at 2,756.05. 

</P>
<P>
	Penguins Deal Hatcher to Rangers  
</P>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The Pittsburgh Penguins traded their  
highest-paid defenseman, Kevin Hatcher, to the New York Rangers 
today for defenseman Peter Popovic, barely 24 hours before the 
Penguins open the season tomorrow night in Dallas. The Penguins 
were eager to trim their payroll after signing defenseman Darius 
Kasparaitis to a $3 million, two-year contract yesterday. Hatcher 
was the Penguins' highest-paid defenseman at $3.1 million per 
season and was the second-high paid player on the team to Jaromir 
Jagr's $10.4 million. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
</P>
