<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jimenez: U.S. Didn't Deserve Win  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLOGNE, Germany (AP) -- Miguel Angel Jimenez still is seething  
about the Ryder Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	The Spaniard shot a 6-under 66 to share the lead in the  
rain-shortened first round of the German Masters Thursday, but even 
that didn't cool him down. 
</P>
<P>
	``The American players are not the winners,'' Jimenez said. ``I  
don't feel like we lost the match. I feel they didn't deserve it 
after what happened the last day. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think all the world is pointing at them because of what  
happened on the golf course. It was not professional.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Justin Leonard holed a 45-foot putt at the 17th hole, the  
American players and wives poured onto the green in a spontaneous 
celebration. That held up Jose Maria Olazabal's putt, which the 
Spaniard missed to clinch the victory for the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	That kicked off a feud, with the Europeans calling the behavior  
of Americans fans and players boorish, and European captain Mark 
James saying his wife was spit at. 
</P>
<P>
	The Americans have apologized, but that has not satisfied  
Jimenez. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the Ryder Cup has to be like this in the future, then I  
don't want to play any more Ryder Cups,'' Jimenez said. ``The 
tradition of the Ryder Cup is very important and it was nice to be 
there and to be involved, but what happened in Brookline (Mass.) is 
not what it is about. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very disappointed about what happened with the players. I  
can't understand them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Spanish teen-ager Sergio Garcia was positive about his first cup  
experience. Then again, the popular teen had the impression the 
crowds were cheering for him to beat the Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the Ryder Cup is a great tournament,'' the 19-year-old  
said. ``What happened last week was bad for the Ryder Cup, but 
nobody wants it to go away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garcia's biggest problem was the way his American caddy, Jerry  
Higginbotham, was attacked at a hotel bar Sunday by a zealous fan. 
The man apparently took exception to the fact he carried the bags 
for a European Ryder Cup player, sending the caddy to the hospital 
with a head wound, two black eyes and a swollen cheek. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very disappointed about that,'' Garcia said. ``But Jerry's  
taking it pretty well.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
