<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Body Found in Steel Drum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) -- Detectives have identified the remains of a  
pregnant woman found stuffed in a steel drum, painting the picture 
of a worker killed three decades ago by her boss after their affair 
spiraled out of control. 
</P>
<P>
	Reyna Angelica Marroquin, a Salvadoran immigrant, is thought to  
have been about 28 when several blows to the head killed her in 
1969. 
</P>
<P>
	The tentative identification was made public Wednesday. The body  
was found Sept. 3 under the former Jericho home of Howard Elkin, 
Ms. Marroquin's former employer. 
</P>
<P>
	Elkin and his wife moved from Long Island to Florida in 1972. A  
little more than two weeks ago, on Sept. 10 and the day after 
Nassau County detectives interviewed him in Boca Raton, Fla., Elkin 
shot himself to death. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said Ms. Marroquin was a factory worker at a flower  
business owned by Elkin. An address book found with the body 
contained his name, along with the address and phone number of a 
confidant of Ms. Marroquin's. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities tracked down the confidant, a former volunteer at a  
Manhattan home for women operated by nuns. It was where Ms. 
Marroquin lived shortly after coming to the United States in 1966. 
</P>
<P>
	The woman told police she had received a frantic phone call from  
Ms. Marroquin in early 1969, saying she had made a ``big mistake'' 
by calling Elkin's wife to tell her she was pregnant with his 
child, Nassau County Police Detective Sgt. Robert Edwards said. 
</P>
<P>
	``She told her confidant either that she was afraid he was now  
going to kill her, or that he had actually threatened to kill 
her,'' Edwards said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Marroquin had asked the confidant, whose name was not  
released, to come to a New Jersey residence where Elkin had put her 
up. 
</P>
<P>
	When the woman arrived, the front door was wide open and a warm  
meal was still on the table, but Ms. Marroquin was not there. She 
went to police, but left after she was told that only family 
members could file missing persons reports. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirty years later, Ms. Marroquin's mummified body was found in  
a drum by the present owners of Elkin's former home, prompting 
authorities to track him down in Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Detectives are awaiting DNA tests results on Ms. Marroquin's  
nine-month old fetus to determine if Elkin was the father. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators said their initial key to Ms. Marroquin's identity  
came when her Social Security number was found in the barely 
legible and decaying address book. 
</P>
<P>
	``The pages were like pulp, stuck together and saturated,'' said  
Edwards. ``Detectives in our documents unit brought the book back 
to life.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
