<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AMC Plans Job Cuts, Office Closings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- The movie theater company AMC  
Entertainment expects to cut $20 million in costs by closing three 
regional offices and eliminating 100 jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	The offices set to close are in Los Angeles, Philadelphia and  
Clearwater, Fla., AMC chairman Peter Brown said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the remaining 300 jobs in those offices will be  
transferred to Kansas City, Brown said, estimating that the changes 
will reduce AMC's general and administrative costs by 40 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	No theaters are to be closed as part of AMC's cost-cutting  
drive. 
</P>
<P>
	When Brown took the helm of AMC in July, after the death of  
founder Stan Durwood, he said he would look for ways to trim fat 
and strengthen AMC's core business. 
</P>
<P>
	``The timing of these moves is a reflection of the new  
management's philosophy of centralization,'' said AMC spokeswoman 
Brenda Nolte. ``As to why this specific time, we're between two 
major peak times in our business -- summer and holiday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Analyst Daniel O'Neill of Credit Suisse First Boston said he was  
pleasantly surprised by AMC's savings estimate. 
</P>
<P>
	``The last time I talked to them about this, the number was more  
like $10 million,'' O'Neill said. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 15:10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Still Feels Like Underdog </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Democratic presidential candidate Bill  
Bradley said Thursday, ``I feel like the underdog,'' but the signs 
contradicted him: he signed autographs and joked with youngsters, 
clearly upbeat as new campaign finance reports showed that he had 
more money in the bank than Vice President Al Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	Buoyed by the shakeup in Gore's campaign and the fresh spending  
figures but as cautious as ever, Bradley said at a news conference, 
``I don't think we have momentum, I think we have a little 
traction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley raised an estimated $6.7 million between July and  
September, spokeswoman Anita Dunn said. Gore raised around $6.5 
million during the same period. 
</P>
<P>
	By spending less than $4.2 million during the last three months,  
Bradley wound up with more than $10 million in the bank. Gore aides 
said the vice president would have between $9.5 million and $10 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's only a snapshot at a particular moment,'' Bradley said.  
``Life's volatile, campaigns are volatile, and I think ultimately 
we have to get known by more people.'' Bradley said he believed at 
least 40 percent of Americans have no idea who he is. 
</P>
<P>
	The former New Jersey senator has repeatedly painted himself as  
an underdog to Gore, and said Thursday that he faced an uphill 
fight against ``entrenched power'' and the ``symbolism'' Gore 
wields by arriving at campaign stops in Air Force Two. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel like an underdog. I always feel like an underdog, and  
here there are some numbers to confirm it,'' he said, referring to 
polls that show him trailing Gore in California. 
</P>
<P>
	Coincidentally, the vice president used that same term to  
describe the state of his campaign. ``I now am, in effect, the 
underdog,'' he said Thursday, a day after announcing he would move 
his headquarters to Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., said he thought that Bradley has  
``clearly grown'' as a campaigner since his days running for the 
Senate. ``He's more engaging, more focused. His campaign is better 
managed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Torricelli, who said he was staying neutral in the Democratic  
presidential race, said Bradley ``was notorious for quickly the 
spending the money he raised'' as a Senate campaigner But, he said, 
``he's now running a very tight organization.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley was upbeat as he campaigned Thursday, signing  
autographs, telling jokes to more than 200 supporters at a rally, 
then bringing them to rapt silence with a story about a 
fourth-grader who told her teacher it was her sibling's turn, not 
hers, to eat breakfast one recent morning. 
</P>
<P>
	He drew repeated applause with pledges to ``bring not just some,  
but all of us to higher ground'' amid the booming economy, and to 
improve race relations. 
</P>
<P>
	Several supporters said it was Bradley's emphasis on racial  
harmony that appealed to them. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a candidate, he's one of the few that's thought carefully  
about issues of race in this country and has actually come up with 
ideas on how to address it,'' said Dr. Lisa Benton, a trauma 
physician at Children's Hospital Medical Center in Oakland. 
</P>
<P>
	At the hospital, Bradley spent his third consecutive day in  
California pitching his health care proposal, designed to enroll 95 
percent of Americans in health plans. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley led a round-table discussion on health care at the  
hospital, where he faced questions about the plan's specifics, but 
widespread support for its goal of near-universal coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	``No American, or no human being inside America's borders,  
should be without health care,'' said Rebecca Denison, who said she 
had been infected with the virus that causes AIDS. 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference afterward, Bradley faced far more questions  
about his surging candidacy than about his health-care proposals. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've made a concerted effort to reach out to new people who  
have never been a part of the process, let them know I'm serious 
about such things as campaign finance reform,'' Bradley said. 
</P>
<P>
	He insisted the financial numbers had not given him or his staff  
any emotional boost. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't get an adrenaline boost in the second quarter,'' he  
said. ``You get an adrenaline boost when you're in the final 
minutes of the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Gore likened the Democratic presidential contest  
to a choice between Coke and Pepsi. 
</P>
<P>
	Told of that comment Thursday, the famously dry Bradley said:  
``Really? I always thought I was 'diet wild cherry.''' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
