<DOCNO> APW19990930.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 07:40:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Donor Gives $60M to Air&AMP;Space Museum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Hungarian American businessman has bestowed  
the Smithsonian's National Air &AMP; Space Museum with $60 million, the 
largest gift in the Smithsonian's 153 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Steven F. Udvar-Hazy, 53, made the donation for the new Air &AMP;  
Space Museum's annex at Dulles International Airport in Virginia, 
about 35 miles from the nation's capital. 
</P>
<P>
	``This wonderful gift is a great beginning for the campaign to  
build the new Dulles Center. It is yet another indication of the 
support of the American people for the Smithsonian Institution,'' 
I. Michael Heyman, the outgoing secretary of the Smithsonian, told 
The Washington Post. 
</P>
<P>
	Udvar-Hazy, a jet pilot, is head of the world's largest aircraft  
leasing company, International Lease Financial Corp., based in 
Beverly Hills, Calif. Forbes magazine named him the 120th richest 
person in the country. 
</P>
<P>
	His donation will go toward a $130 million capital campaign to  
build the annex, which will be four times the size of the museum on 
the National Mall. 
</P>
<P>
	To be completed in 2003, the annex will hold the newest and  
largest crafts in the museum's collection. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
