<DOCNO> APW19990930.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 21:10:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religion in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In December 1995, American Catholic scholar  
George Weigel found himself in Rome listening to a lecture when a 
seminarian slipped into the hall and tapped him on the shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	The pope's secretary is on the phone for you, he whispered.  
</P>
<P>
	Monsignor Stanislaw Dziwisz, Pope John Paul II's longtime aide,  
was calling to ask, ``Can you come over for dinner tonight? Off I 
went.'' The pope had met Weigel several times before, but this was 
far from a routine occasion. 
</P>
<P>
	John Paul wanted Weigel to write his biography.  
</P>
<P>
	Last week Weigel was in Rome to give the pope his first look at  
the resulting 992-page doorstopper: ``Witness to Hope: The 
Biography of Pope John Paul II'' (Cliff Street Books, $35). By 
coincidence, this respectful account of John Paul reaches stores 
alongside ``Hitler's Pope,'' John Cornwell's biographical assault 
on the World War II-era pope, Pius XII, and his record of not 
confronting the Nazis. 
</P>
<P>
	A onetime seminarian and daily communicant at St. Jane Frances  
de Chantal parish in Bethesda, Md., Weigel, 48, was president of a 
conservative think tank, the Ethics and Public Policy Center in 
Washington, D.C., when the pope made his request. He will return 
there as a researcher after a world tour to promote his book's 
English, French, Italian, Spanish, German, Polish and Slovenian 
editions. (Other translations are under negotiation.) 
</P>
<P>
	More than other biographies of John Paul II, Weigel's work was  
shaped by Catholic insiders -- most notably the pope himself, who 
gave Weigel 10 interviews spanning 20 hours, invariably over a 
meal. John Paul granted Weigel not just unusual access to himself 
but remarkable freedom to write whatever he wanted without Vatican 
clearance. 
</P>
<P>
	Not that Rome had reason to worry -- John Paul II made a shrewder  
choice than Ronald Reagan, subject of an authorized biography in 
which the author has stirred controversy by appearing as a 
semi-fictional character. Weigel is a straightforward researcher 
and he's a fan of this pope and his traditionalist policies. In an 
interview, Weigel proudly called himself ``very much a John Paul II 
Catholic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he does give a bit of attention to such papal critics as the  
``We Are the Church'' movement, which roused 1.5 million Germans to 
sign a petition demanding women's ordination and protesting other 
issues. 
</P>
<P>
	The biographer set to work in 1996, equipped with an endorsement  
letter from John Paul, ample access to documents, and assurances 
that the pope and Dziwisz would urge cooperation upon anyone who 
checked with them. Weigel wangled interviews with 43 Vatican 
officials (only two refused) and a vast array of Catholics 
elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	Most important were the 54 Poles, since Weigel thinks John  
Paul's work as an archbishop and cardinal in Cracow was ``a preview 
of his pontificate. He, the supposed outsider, didn't need a lot of 
instruction from the people who run popes. He came in with a 
formulated idea of how to be a pope.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Weigel wrote a 1992 book depicting John Paul's influence as a  
key reason European Communism collapsed when it did and with little 
bloodshed. Hostility to the Kremlin was fermenting prior to John 
Paul, but ``it was not connected with popular piety and a mass 
movement,'' Weigel explains. 
</P>
<P>
	The biographer says that 20th century people think the affairs  
of the world are mostly matters of politics and economics. But John 
Paul believes ``culture is what counts over the long haul,'' 
religion included, and also that ``culture is a powerful 
non-violent weapon against tyranny.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This was a natural viewpoint for a son of Poland, which vanished  
as a nation-state from 1795 till 1918 but survived as a culture, 
thanks largely to the Catholic church. The pope has been proven 
right, Weigel thinks. 
</P>
<P>
	The momentous 1978 choice of a Polish pope, Weigel believes,  
resulted from shock over the sudden death of the newly elected 
Italian, John Paul I. Once the 118 cardinals ``began to think the 
unthinkable,'' namely that non-Italians should be considered, ``the 
question became, who is the most effective public leader in the 
church today?'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Karol Wojtyla was not known to most of us, but to the 118 men  
who counted he was one of the best known figures in the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Weigel thinks ``nationality will mean very little in choosing  
the next pope.'' Future candidates will, like John Paul II, have 
successful pastoral records running local dioceses and be well 
prepared to be public personalities and world travelers, he says. 
</P>
<P>
	He believes that John Paul, unrestrained by tradition, has  
permanently changed the nature of his ancient office. 
</P>
<P>
	Weigel says that two decades into the Wojtyla papacy, ``I was  
surprised the degree to which some parts of the Roman establishment 
are still not accustomed to a non-Italian pontificate.'' To John 
Paul, the pope is no longer the leader of a bureaucracy. 
</P>
<P>
	``The pope of the 21st century is not the C.E.O. of Roman  
Catholic Church Inc. It will be the pope as evangelist, pastor, the 
first witness to the faith, and the world's leading defender of 
basic human rights. There's no reversing this. The church expects 
it. Just as intriguingly, the world expects it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What has been the key to all of John Paul's accomplishments?  
Smarts? Stubbornness? Stamina? ``The sheer intensity of his prayer 
life. He walks down the hall to a meeting and he's praying. He 
prays all the time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Weigel's biography bogs down somewhat when it moves from Poland  
into John Paul's pontificate, due to an unfortunate decision to 
follow rigid chronology rather than organizing the information into 
themes. And the prose, while clear, is not especially engaging. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, this ranks as the definitive biography of the first  
pope from beyond the Danube, due to its rich detail and confident 
grasp of the religious dynamics. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 20:11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Giants, Fans Bid Adieu to the Stick </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Hall of Famer Juan Marichal took the mound  
in a business suit, signaling the beginning of the end, and fellow 
Hall of Famer Willie Mays followed hours later for a last goodbye. 
</P>
<P>
	And finally, after the last baseball game at Candlestick Park  
was in the books and Giants greats past and present took the field 
for a salute, workers dug out home plate and took the old park's 
heart away, flying it by helicopter to be transplanted at the 
team's new stadium near downtown. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess all you can say is, `Tell it goodbye,' '' longtime  
Giants broadcaster Lon Simmons said during postgame ceremonies that 
ended with the blowing out of a candle. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of good memories, a lot of bad memories here,''  
Mays said. ``I'm happy. I don't understand why when you leave a 
good thing and you go to another thing that's going to be good for 
the fans that you've got to be sad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The last day for baseball was unlike any other at Candlestick in  
so many ways. 
</P>
<P>
	The park's famous winds were quiet, the familiar shroud of cold  
and fog nowhere to be seen or felt. 
</P>
<P>
	Defying 40 years of history, the park that was home to Mays,  
Marichal, and Willie McCovey, brought down the curtain on a 
brilliant day for baseball even though the Giants lost to the rival 
Los Angeles Dodgers 9-4. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was very special,'' Dodgers manager Dave Johnson said.  
``Fans were really into it today, but they weren't too bad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Managing general partner Peter Magowan thanked the crowd for  
braving the elements and supporting the team during the last 40 
seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``No fans were prepared to endure as much as you have,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Magowan added, ``This is not a sad day for the Giants. Yes, we  
are leaving our home, but we are going to new one and I promise you 
it will be the best ballpark in this country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The day was special from the start. Marichal, 61, displayed his  
leg kick once again in throwing out the first pitch. Mays, 67, 
returned to throw out the last pitch and his godson, Giants star 
Barry Bonds, caught it. It will be the first ball thrown out next 
season at Pacific Bell Park, about a 25-minute walk from Union 
Square. 
</P>
<P>
	A crowd of 61,389, the most ever to see a regular season  
baseball game at Candlestick, was on hand. Many wore old jerseys 
and hats and some made their feelings known in signs dotting the 
stands. 
</P>
<P>
	``Adios Candlestick,'' one sign read. ``We'll miss the thrills  
and chills,'' read another. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mothers and fathers, sons and daughters, watched some of the  
greatest players in the game on a day-to-day basis in this 
ballpark,'' Giants executive vice president Larry Baer said. ``This 
is closure for them, but it's also a happy sendoff because we're 
going to a new ballpark.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Maligned for its bitter weather and isolation, it was also  
remembered for some of baseball's great moments and its strength in 
withstanding the October 1989 earthquake that ravaged the Bay area 
and interrupted the World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	The All-Star game was played at the 'Stick in 1961, when the  
winds blew pitcher Stu Miller off the mound. 
</P>
<P>
	Dedicated the year before by Vice President Richard Nixon as  
``the finest ballpark in America,'' Candlestick also was the scene 
of the 16-inning scoreless duel between Marichal and the Braves' 
Warren Spahn (Mays won it with a homer); McCovey's 500-foot 
upper-deck homer in a 1966 loss to the Mets and lefty Dave 
Dravecky's August 1989 miracle comeback from cancer, in which he 
beat the Reds. 
</P>
<P>
	``Juan Marichal's no-hitter, the World Series games ...,'' Hall  
of Famer Orlando Cepeda said. ``And that 16-inning game that Juan 
pitched and Willie won, I'll never forget that. This was a tough 
playing field but I spent so many days here and there are so many 
great memories.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A 1964 game was delayed after a visiting Dodgers outfielder lost  
a fly ball in the fog, though the final game was played under a 
broiling sun. The temperature at game time was 82 degrees. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's unbelievable,'' said Richard Scimeca, 43, of San Jose,  
who took the day off from work to be at the final game. ``Maybe 
it's because it's the last game and the baseball gods decided after 
all these years we're going to give you some good weather. It seems 
like every other time I was here, it was windy and freezing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Ivie was among some 60 former Giants players on hand to  
take a final bow. 
</P>
<P>
	``The wind and the cold made it miserable. Night games were  
terrible,'' Ivie recalled. ``It took a little bit to put on the 
insulated underwear and go play nine innings, but just being here 
and seeing all the old coaches players and made it enjoyable for 
me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And with the sun out and the stands and dugout warmed by  
nostalgia, even the bad, cold days didn't seem so windy or so cold. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never really minded it,'' said San Francisco manager Dusty  
Baker, a native of Sacramento who got his first hit here in 1968 as 
a rookie with the Atlanta Braves. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whenever I'm here, I've had all my friends and family here, so  
it was always like a homecoming for me. I had to have my best games 
here in front of my home boys.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 20:11:01 </DATE_TIME>
