<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Next Year Last for Tech's Williams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LUBBOCK, Texas (AP) -- Texas Tech running back Ricky Williams,  
out for the season with a knee injury, said Thursday he probably 
won't ask the NCAA for another year of eligibility. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really don't know, but in my mind I really don't want to,''  
Williams, a junior, said during a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really would like next year to be my last year here playing  
football at Texas Tech. I love Texas Tech a lot and it has done a 
lot for me, but I think next year I'll be able to graduate with the 
classmates I came here with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA allows players to apply for a medical redshirt, which  
gives a player an extra year of eligibility if he misses a season 
because of an injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams, who ran for 1,582 yards and 13 touchdowns last year,  
hurt his knee in the opener against Arizona State and sat out the 
next two games before aggravating the injury during practice this 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	``I fully expect to get back to 100 percent,'' Williams said.  
``Everyone will see that happen. The Heisman was one of my main 
goals so it's very disappointing. Now I just have to work to get 
back.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
