<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                           *Eva Israelsen    	
</P>
<P>
	LOGAN, Utah (AP) -- Eva Israelsen, who lived long enough to have  
271 great-grandchildren, died Thursday, five days before her 105th 
birthday. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Israelsen appeared in Life magazine in October 1993 in an  
article noting the birth of her 200th and 201st 
great-grandchildren. Since then, her progeny has grown to 271 
great-grandchildren and 40 great-great-grandchildren. She had 11 
original children, and they had 67 kids. 
</P>
<P>
	She was born Eva May Butler on Oct. 5, 1894, at the mouth of Big  
Cottonwood Canyon in Salt Lake County. She met Victor E. Israelsen 
while attending Utah Agricultural College, now Utah State 
University, in the 1920s and later married him. 
</P>
<P>
	They spent their lives on a dairy farm. Mrs. Israelsen remained  
active well past her 100th birthday, walking at least a mile a day. 

</P>
<P>
                           *James M. Kelso    	
</P>
<P>
	PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- James M. Kelso, a popular state  
representative and restaurateur, died Wednesday from cancer. He was 
55. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelso was a political novice in 1996 when he ran for the state  
House as a Democrat. He became a deputy majority leader. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelso was also a partner in the Coast Guard House restaurant in  
Narragansett for 20 years. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Jack Kiefer    	
</P>
<P>
	PONTE VEDRA BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Jack Kiefer, a two-time winner on  
the Senior PGA Tour who was diagnosed last year with cancer in his 
spinal cord, died Sept. 24. He was 59. 
</P>
<P>
	Kiefer won the 1994 Ralphs Senior Classic and the du Maurier  
Champions in 1997, when he finished 16th on the money list. He 
played 12 events in 1998 before he was diagnosed with cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Kiefer was a pitcher for Millersville State College in 1961, and  
his knuckleball earned him a contract with the Detroit Tigers. But 
after three days in camp, he left baseball and took up golf. 
</P>
<P>
	He turned professional in 1967 and joined the senior tour in  
1990. He had a reputation as an iron man for playing at least 30 
tournaments a year every season except 1992. 

</P>
<P>
                      *Cotesworth Pickney Lewis    	
</P>
<P>
	WILLIAMSBURG, Va. (AP) -- The Rev. Cotesworth Pinckney Lewis, who  
once told President Lyndon Johnson that Americans needed a 
``straightforward explanation'' about the Vietnam war, died 
Wednesday. He was 86. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis' 1967 sermon to the visiting Johnson at Bruton Parish  
Episcopal Church prompted the church's vestry and the governor of 
Virginia to apologize to the president. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis was rector of the church from 1956 to 1985. The  
congregation more than doubled during his tenure. 
</P>
<P>
	A native of Birmingham, Ala., Lewis earned two divinity degrees  
and spent nearly 50 years in the ministry. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Dmitry Likhachyov    	
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Dmitry Likhachyov, a literary historian who was  
one of Russia's most respected cultural figures, died Thursday. He 
was 92. 
</P>
<P>
	Likhachyov, sometimes described as ``the conscience of Russia,''  
spent four years, from 1928-32, in one of the Soviet Union's most 
dreaded prison camps, Solovki, located in a former monastery on a 
northern Russian island. 
</P>
<P>
	Afterward, he became prominent as an impassioned defender of the  
country's cultural heritage. He fought to protect the purity of 
texts written by Russia's most famous poet, Alexander Pushkin, to 
whom counterfeiters have long attributed fake diaries. 
</P>
<P>
	``In our pragmatic century, he embodied the best qualities of  
Russian intelligentsia -- selfless service to the fatherland, 
nobility, sense of duty,'' President Boris Yeltsin said in a letter 
addressed to Likhachyov's widow and daughter. 
</P>
<P>
	A year ago, Yeltsin awarded Likhachyov one of the country's  
highest honors, the Order of St. Andrew, for contributions to the 
development of national culture. 
</P>
<P>
	Likhachyov, an expert in Russian literature of the 11th-17th  
centuries, held honorary doctorates from Oxford and several other 
foreign universities. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Jules Rind    	
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Jules Rind, a veteran of radio news and  
sports, died Sept. 23 of acute leukemia. He was 82. 
</P>
<P>
	His career of about 60 years included stints with the Mutual  
Broadcasting System, NBC radio, the U.S. Information Agency, and 
local stations WPEN, WFLN and WWDB. At various times, he also 
broadcast games of the Phillies, the Eagles, and University of 
Pennsylvania football. 
</P>
<P>
	``He covered the Three Mile Island nuclear accident for NBC and  
served as the sole radio announcer for many radio networks when 
Pope John Paul II went from Veterans Stadium to Logan Circle in 
1979,'' said his son, Bruce. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to his son, he is survived by his wife of 50 years,  
Helen High Rind; a daughter; and two grandchildren. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
