<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mob Hit Man Admits to Killings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A hit man who admitted to federal prosecutors he  
killed 20 people pleaded guilty Thursday to 10 murders in a plea 
bargain that calls for a sentence of as little as 12 1/2 years in 
prison. 
</P>
<P>
	John Martorano, 58, agreed to the deal that would have him  
testify against his cohorts in a trial of major New England mob 
figures. He has already served five years in prison while awaiting 
trial, so he could be free in eight years. 
</P>
<P>
	As U.S. District Judge Mark Wolf read the 78 charges against  
him, including racketeering, loan sharking and extortion, and asked 
if he understood them, Martorano repeatedly replied, ``Yes, your 
honor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some relatives of Martorano's victims sat in the courtroom as  
the powerfully built mobster impassively admitted to the killings. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was hard to look him up in the eye,'' said Denise Castucci,  
whose father, Richard Castucci, was murdered in 1976 by Martorano. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been ripped off of a father and my children of their  
grandfather,'' she said. ``He's sitting there, waiting for a lesser 
sentence. How dare he?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The plea bargain must be approved by Wolf, who said he is  
uncertain about accepting the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	In a recent ruling, Wolf noted that Martorano turned informant  
only after learning that co-defendants in a racketeering case, 
Stephen ``The Rifleman'' Flemmi and fugitive James ``Whitey'' 
Bulger, were themselves FBI informants for decades. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge was concerned that the information used to indict  
Flemmi and Bulger was gathered while they were helping the 
government put mobsters behind bars under promises of immunity. 
Wolf was further worried that the information was used to gain 
Martorano's cooperation. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolf also said he was not sure a 12 1/2-year sentence was  
appropriate, considering Martorano's record. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
