<HEADLINE> JonBenet's Siblings Appear at Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOULDER, Colo. (AP) -- The grand jury investigating the death of  
6-year-old JonBenet Ramsey returned to work today, possibly to 
learn more about the inner workings of the Ramsey family. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel of 12 jurors arrived at the Boulder County Courthouse  
before 9 a.m. and convened in a closed-door session. It marked the 
second meeting of the jury this month. 
</P>
<P>
	Melinda Ramsey Long of Virginia and John Andrew Ramsey of  
Atlanta arrived in Denver on Wednesday, apparently to testify 
before the grand jury. 
</P>
<P>
	They are children of John Ramsey and his first wife. JonBenet  
and her brother, Burke, are children of Ramsey and his second wife, 
Patsy. Police have said the parents are under suspicion in the 
girl's death; they deny any wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Ms. Long, 27, and John Andrew Ramsey, 23, were with their  
mother in Atlanta when their half sister was found dead in the 
family's Boulder home the day after Christmas in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors and law enforcement officers in Boulder declined to  
comment on the grand jury's plans. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Long and John Andrew Ramsey have repeatedly been questioned  
by police but have rarely talked about the case in public. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Long did say in a British television documentary that her  
father ``has never, ever raised a hand to any of his children. He 
has never ever abused us in any way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The grand jury that has been investigating JonBenet's death met  
a week ago today for the first time in four months. It faces an 
Oct. 20 deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	By that date they must decide whether to indict a suspect, issue  
a ``no true bill'' indicating they didn't find enough evidence to 
indict a named suspect, issue a report, or take no action. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
