<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Down Against Yen, Others </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell slightly against the yen  
Thursday as traders anticipated that a report from Japan's central 
bank would show an improvement in business sentiment. The dollar 
also lost ground to most other major currencies. 
</P>
<P>
	The yen has been on a tear against the dollar this summer, but  
eased up a bit in the last week or so amid signs that Japan may 
take steps to slow the yen's ascent, which has been worrying 
Japanese industrialists. 
</P>
<P>
	A rising yen makes Japanese exports more expensive in world  
markets, something that could threaten an economic recovery from a 
decade-long economic slump. 
</P>
<P>
	The yen began to come back in favor Thursday as investors  
expected a report due out Monday from Japan's central bank to show 
an improvement in business sentiment. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tankan survey is a widely watched indicator of Japan's  
economy. Hopes for a recovery have been a major factor behind the 
yen's rally since May. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 106.77  
Japanese yen, down from 106.98 Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0684, up from  
$1.0641 late Wednesday. The euro has been gaining ground in recent 
days on hopes that the European Central Bank may move to raise 
interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4969 Swiss francs, down from  
1.5036, and 1.4674 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4641. The British 
pound rose to $1.6464 from $1.6442. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Thursday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8308 German 
marks, down from 1.8380; 6.1403 French francs, down from 6.1644; 
and 1,812.39 Italian lire, down from 1,819.63. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
