<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Female Finches Like Handsome Dads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Birds have at least one thing in common with  
humans: The ladies prefer a well-dressed guy. 
</P>
<P>
	A team of researchers in France and Scotland has discovered that  
female zebra finches give an added jolt of hormones to eggs sired 
by males wearing red leg bands. When the father was wearing a green 
leg band the mothers didn't bother with the extra boost. 
</P>
<P>
	The report raises questions about the long-standing assumption  
that female birds pick better-looking males merely to get good 
genes for their offspring. In this case, at least, the mother also 
has a hand in improving the chick's prospects. 
</P>
<P>
	Separate studies have indicated that chicks from eggs that got  
the extra testosterone were more active and grew faster than 
others. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, in the field, male finches do not wear rings, lead  
researcher Diego Gil of the University of Paris pointed out. 
</P>
<P>
	``What they do have is red beaks, which are used by females to  
choose mates. What seems to happen is that by using rings in the 
lab we have tapped into a female perceptive mechanism, and the 
female sees the red-banded male as a super-male,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The new findings are being reported in a paper in Friday's  
edition of the journal Science. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not something the female thinks about, though.  
</P>
<P>
	``To assume consciousness on the part of the female would be a  
big leap,'' Gil cautioned. ``We consider the differential 
investment as a physiological reaction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Professor Hubert Schwabl of Washington State University, who  
first discovered that some female birds can vary the hormones in 
their eggs, termed the findings ``exciting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The surprising result is the influence of male attractiveness  
on these hormone levels,'' said Schwabl, who was not part of the 
research team. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet to be determined, he said, is whether the stimulation by the  
more attractive male raises the female's hormone levels and that is 
reflected in her eggs, or whether females somehow control the 
hormone levels. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
