<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Wants Long-Distance Competition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Asked about a rumored alliance between the  
nation's second- and third-largest long-distance companies, the 
government's top telephone regulator said Thursday that generally 
no merger should be permitted that might raise prices due to less 
competition. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Communications Commission Chairman Bill Kennard said he  
would not discuss published reports of a possible deal between 
Sprint and MCI WorldCom. But Kennard did credit competition in the 
long-distance market for lowering rates for consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today in America consumers are enjoying the lowest  
long-distance rates in history,'' he told business leaders gathered 
at The Wall Street Journal technology conference. ``We cannot allow 
any merger to happen in this industry that turns back the clock on 
that competition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	MCI WorldCom is the nation's second-largest long-distance  
company, followed by Sprint, parent of Sprint PCS, a mobile phone 
business with 4 million wireless customers. Together, Sprint and 
MCI WorldCom control about 30 percent of the U.S. long-distance 
market, still far behind AT&AMP;T Corp.'s 60 percent share. 
</P>
<P>
	Kennard emphasized that all mergers brought before the  
commission must be evaluated on their own terms. But he did 
indicate that such a deal -- if sought by the companies -- would not 
be a sure thing. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't hear me saying it's going to be fine,'' Kennard  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, following WorldCom's $37 billion takeover of MCI  
Communications Corp., Kennard indicated that the industry might be 
at its limit in terms of such colossal deals. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once this merger is consummated, the industry will again be  
poised just a merger away from undue concentration,'' Kennard said 
in September 1998. ``I dare say that any subsequent merger of this 
or similar magnitude between long-distance firms in the near future 
should be judged quite differently than the merger before us 
today.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
