<HEADLINE> Tape Contains Evidence of Sex Abuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- A stolen camcorder contained evidence of a more  
serious crime, which is why police say its owner never reported the 
camera missing in the first place. 
</P>
<P>
	William Hampton, 44, has been charged with four counts of  
first-degree statutory sodomy and one count of using a child for a 
sexual performance. 
</P>
<P>
	Police say the camcorder contained all the proof they needed,  
including a 15-minute segment of Hampton committing lewd acts with 
a 4 1/2-year-old girl. 
</P>
<P>
	``The tape is truly disgusting,'' said Lt. Mary Warnecke,  
commander of the Police Department's sex crimes-child abuse units. 
</P>
<P>
	Police say the discovery would never have been made had the  
camera not been stolen. 
</P>
<P>
	After a burglar broke into Hampton's St. Louis home earlier this  
month, the thief gave the camcorder to his mother and she sold it 
for $150. The buyer examined the camcorder, found a tape inside and 
played it. 
</P>
<P>
	After viewing the contents, the buyer notified police.  
Authorities eventually found the thief, who agreed to help police 
by leading them to Hampton's home. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to facing the state charges, federal prosecutors  
charged Hampton with producing child pornography. 
</P>
<P>
	The thief had been arrested Sept. 22 on unrelated burglary  
charges and was awaiting trial. He told police he stole the 
camcorder about a week before his arrest. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
