<DOCNO> APW19990930.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 15:50:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Many Seniors Face High Drug Costs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Half of elderly Americans who have private  
health insurance covering drugs still spend $500 to $999 a year 
out-of-pocket on prescriptions, according to a new report from the 
AARP. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's largest organization for older adults released the  
study Thursday to back up its support for adding drug coverage to 
Medicare, the national health insurance program for the elderly and 
disabled. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many argue that because roughly two-thirds of Medicare  
beneficiaries have some type of drug coverage, a Medicare drug 
benefit for everybody is not necessary,'' said John Rother, AARP's 
public policy director. ``But this study provides evidence that the 
current system is not working for beneficiaries.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although Medicare now does not cover prescriptions, a majority  
of the elderly has some type of insurance covering drugs -- mainly 
through retirement benefits from jobs, HMOs or private policies 
known as Medigap. 
</P>
<P>
	The AARP study concluded that is no guarantee they will be  
spared high out-of-pocket costs. Deductibles, copayments and caps 
on benefits can leave even those with insurance financially 
exposed. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the elderly who had out-of-pocket drug costs of $500 to  
$999, 50 percent faced those high bills in spite of having some 
insurance coverage, the study found. Among those with $1,000 or 
more in drug costs annually, 42 percent had insurance coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	The AARP study estimates that among all non-institutionalized  
Medicare beneficiaries, average per-person out-of-pocket costs for 
drugs will be $410 this year. About 13 percent will have drug costs 
between $500 and $999, and 12 percent over $1,000. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton has proposed adding drug coverage to Medicare  
as option for all elderly Americans. Republican leaders in Congress 
have questioned whether any but the poorest truly need it. 
</P>
<P>
	AARP based its study on Medicare's 1995 survey of beneficiaries,  
the most recent data available. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
