<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ramsey Siblings Expected To Testify </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOULDER, Colo. (AP) -- John Ramsey's two adult children were  
expected to testify before the grand jury that returned to work 
Thursday to investigate the death of his 6-year-old daughter, 
JonBenet. 
</P>
<P>
	Melinda Ramsey Long and John Andrew Ramsey were in Boulder, but  
prosecutors refused to say whether they testified. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Long, 27, who lives in Virginia, and John Andrew Ramsey, 23,  
who lives in Atlanta, are the children of John Ramsey and his first 
wife. JonBenet and her brother, Burke, are Ramsey's children with 
his second wife, Patsy. 
</P>
<P>
	Police have said John and Patsy Ramsey are under suspicion in  
the girl's death. They have denied any wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Long and John Andrew Ramsey were with their mother in  
Atlanta when JonBenet was found dead in the family's Boulder home 
the day after Christmas in 1996. They repeatedly have been 
questioned by police but have rarely talked about the case in 
public. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Long did say in a British TV documentary that her father  
``has never, ever raised a hand to any of his children. He has 
never ever abused us in any way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The grand jury that has been investigating JonBenet's death met  
a week ago for the first time in four months. 
</P>
<P>
	By its Oct. 20 deadline, the jury must decide whether to indict  
one or more people, indicate they did not find enough evidence to 
hand down an indictment, issue a report or take no action. 
</P>
<P>
	Craig Silverman, a former Denver prosecutor who has followed the  
Ramsey investigation, believes it is important for the grand jury 
to hear from the adult children. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there is going to be a trial of John and Patsy Ramsey, it's  
reasonable to assume the children would be witnesses. It would be 
smart to hear what they have to say now rather than later,'' 
Silverman said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
