<DOCNO> APW19990930.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 16:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.C. Residents Survey Ruined Homes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRINCEVILLE, N.C. (AP) -- Residents of this town founded by  
ex-slaves glumly surveyed their wrecked homes Thursday for the 
first time in the two weeks since Hurricane Floyd's floodwaters 
swallowed the town. Some found the damage too great to bear. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert and Callie Suggs said good-bye to the concrete,  
green-and-white home they built 34 years ago and where they raised 
their six children. An inch-wide crack girdled the foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	``All my life this was a gathering place for the family,'' Mrs.  
Suggs said. ``I would cook something every Sunday, and we would 
come here after church and pray together and eat together. I'm 
really going to miss that. I guess someday it'll be the same, but I 
don't know where.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After 8 inches of rain this week made the misery worse in  
flood-stunned eastern North Carolina, Thursday was dry and weather 
forecasters predicted more of the same for several days. 
</P>
<P>
	``Slowly but surely it's drying out,'' said National Guard  
Master Sgt. Larry Jones in Goldsboro, where this week's rain 
ruptured a dam and flooded the downtown. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tar and Neuse rivers remained well above flood stage and  
were due to crest over the next two days. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's still going to be a dangerous place out there for the  
next couple of weeks,'' warned Jonathan Blaes, a National Weather 
Service forecaster in Raleigh. 
</P>
<P>
	Floyd, which brought 20 inches of rain to eastern North  
Carolina, is expected to surpass Hurricane Fran, which did $6 
billion in damage in 1996, as the state's costliest natural 
disaster. Blamed for at least 47 deaths, Floyd's floodwaters 
destroyed or heavily damaged at least 3,000 homes. About 1,500 
people remain in 18 American Red Cross shelters. 
</P>
<P>
	Government relief funds began flowing toward North Carolina on  
Thursday. Vice President Al Gore announced $20.3 million in federal 
emergency funds would help families in low-income areas rebuild. 
</P>
<P>
	James Lee Witt, director of the Federal Emergency Management  
Agency, and EPA administrator Carol M. Browner toured flooded 
Kinston and surveyed environmental damage near the Neuse River 
community. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked to name the most important environmental lesson  
learned from Floyd, Browner said, ``Stay out of floodplains.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Health officials announced that starting Monday up to 3 million  
acres will be sprayed with mosquito-killing chemicals to curb a 
growing infestation blamed on the heavy rains. 
</P>
<P>
	In Princeville, a community of 1,900, Mayor Delia Perkins has  
said it may be next year before residents can move back. 
</P>
<P>
	The town was engulfed by the Tar River on Sept. 17. At one  
point, brown, swirling water stood 20 feet deep near the town hall. 
The water destroyed homes and cars and wiped out the town water 
system and other infrastructure. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, as bright sunshine filtered through the trees onto  
the damp streets and yards, residents for the first time saw what 
was left. 
</P>
<P>
	Maxie Harrison, 37, had to break a bathroom window to get into  
his home; floodwaters had pushed furniture and appliances up 
against the doors. White mold sprouted from door frames, a TV was 
upside down in a bedroom, and slippery, brown mud covered the 
floor. In the yard, two roosters lay dead in a cage. 
</P>
<P>
	Oscar, a green parrot that belonged to Harrison's 18-year-old  
son, Charlie, gave out a screech. Amazingly, he was still alive 
after two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, at least we got something,'' Maxie Harrison said. ``I  
got Oscar; he's one bad bird.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There was at least some good news created by Floyd on Thursday --  
Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge said the storm's heavy rain helped 
relieve yearlong drought conditions. Ridge lifted mandatory 
restrictions on water use in 54 of the 55 counties that had been 
under such an order since July. 
</P>
<P>
	New Jersey, Delaware and Maryland also have ended drought  
emergencies in recent weeks, thanks in part to Floyd. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
