<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Activists Mobilize for WTO Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Wash. (AP) -- Sweat streamed down longtime activist  
Jennifer Zurick's face as she climbed, foot by arduous foot, a 
nylon line hung from scaffolding four stories tall. 
</P>
<P>
	A half-dozen other veterans of teach-ins, sit-ins and street  
blockades were making similar efforts to reach the top of the metal 
structure, which rose from a grassy clearing among the evergreens 
at a farm. 
</P>
<P>
	The activists are getting ready for the ``Protest of the  
Century'' against global capitalism. 
</P>
<P>
	The showdown comes Nov. 30, when the 160 activist ``boot camp''  
graduates join tens of thousands of others from around the world in 
Seattle for the World Trade Organization's four-day Ministerial 
Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Protest plans include giant puppets in the streets, linking  
hands around the conference site and scaling or rappelling down 
skyscrapers to hang anti-WTO banners. 
</P>
<P>
	What are they upset about?  
</P>
<P>
	Complaints about the Geneva-based WTO include criticism of its  
sweeping powers to enforce international trade agreements. The 
organization is also under fire for overturning a U.S. ban on 
imports of shrimp caught with nets that also snare endangered sea 
turtles, and for opposing state bans on doing business with 
companies in countries with poor human-rights records. 
</P>
<P>
	``The WTO undermines environmental regulations throughout the  
world, as well as supporting regimes that jeopardize or abuse human 
rights,'' said Zurick, a member of the Monterey Action Resource 
Center. 
</P>
<P>
	As many as 50,000 environmentalists, Japanese and Indian small  
farmers, union rank and file, ``fair trade'' activists and possibly 
even Zapatista guerrillas are expected to fill Seattle's streets. 
</P>
<P>
	The conference itself will draw as many as 3,000 delegates from  
the WTO's 134 member countries. It also will bring 2,000 sideline 
participants from WTO-accredited non-governmental organizations as 
well as up to 3,000 journalists, said Ray Waldmann, WTO Seattle 
Host Organization chairman and vice president of international 
relations for The Boeing Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Waldmann and other conference proponents defend the WTO, saying  
free trade improves lives. Peter Werner, a WTO spokesman in Geneva, 
dismissed activist claims his organization is anti-democratic. 
</P>
<P>
	The WTO's member governments ``are represented by trade  
diplomats in WTO meetings,'' he said. ``The governments are, of 
course, elected by their citizens. Hence, anti-democratic criticism 
is a complete exaggeration.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other groups preparing for the protest include the  
100,000-member Council of Canadians, which is holding a series of 
anti-WTO teach-ins and is expected to bring several hundred to the 
conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee activists are putting together a bus convoy, a plane  
has been chartered by others in Minnesota and Wisconsin and groups 
from Malaysia to Brazil to England are sending members, according 
to the Seattle Host Committee of People for Fair Trade. 
</P>
<P>
	The WTO's actions have united many different groups, animal  
rights activist Ben White told a Seattle organizers meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't matter if you're for worker rights, human rights,  
children's rights,'' he said. ``It's one big package, and they have 
opened the door for us.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 07:50:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Libel Judgment Against ABC Tossed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- A federal court has thrown out a $10 million  
libel judgment against ABC, ruling the network's ``20/20'' news 
program didn't intentionally slant a story to make a bank executive 
look like a thief. 
</P>
<P>
	A lawyer for Alan Levan, chairman and chief executive of  
BankAtlantic, said he plans to appeal the ruling to the U.S. 
Supreme Court. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm clearly disappointed, although the court has decided the  
issue on a very narrow ground that will be worthy of Supreme Court 
review,'' Alan Fein said after Wednesday's ruling from a 
three-judge panel of the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals. 
</P>
<P>
	Levan sued ABC over a 1991 broadcast that he said used false  
statements and misleading editing to attack his character. A jury 
ruled in his favor in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The appeals court said ABC and producer William Willson had no  
reason to believe the overall crux of the story was false, which 
Levan's lawyers needed to prove to show the network acted with 
malice. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're delighted with the court's ruling,'' said Eileen Murphy,  
spokeswoman for ABC News. She said the network would not comment 
further until executives had time to study the decision. 
</P>
<P>
	The report focused on real estate partners who accused Levan of  
bilking them in deals known as ``roll-ups,'' in which real estate 
was swapped for BankAtlantic bonds at the height of the 
savings-and-loan crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Fein contended the report accused Levan of knowingly misleading  
his partners into accepting a bad deal. The judges decided that, 
while the story implies Levan must have known the deal was unfair, 
``ABC does not expressly say so.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides claimed high stakes in the case. Fein said the report  
caused BankAtlantic customers to close their accounts because they 
believed Levan was a crook. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC said the $10 million judgment threatened to make news  
organizations think twice before pursuing important, hard-hitting 
stories. 
</P>
<P>
	Levan's partners eventually won an $8 million settlement in  
class-action suits over the roll-ups, but congressional and 
regulatory investigations produced no charges. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC ended up broadcasting a correction stating that the editing  
of the story may have misled some viewers about Levan's role in the 
real-estate deal. The report also said Levan refused to speak with 
ABC, whereas he declined to be interviewed on camera but had 
contacted the show several times. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 09:40:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge May Stop 'Eagles Court' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- A judge says he may soon call off having an  
``Eagles Court'' in Veterans Stadium for unruly football fans 
because of fewer arrests this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The court allows unlawful fans to be arrested, tried and  
convicted in the stadium, and supporters say it has helped dampen 
rowdyism at games. 
</P>
<P>
	Municipal Court Judge Seamus McCaffery says judges have been  
sitting idle this season because police are kicking fans out of the 
stadium instead of collaring them. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there's nothing going on, there's no sense in having a  
court,'' McCaffery said. ``Why they are not making arrests, I don't 
know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCaffery says he is committed to having judges available for  
the historically rowdy Eagles-Dallas Cowboys matchup in two weeks. 
But he won't make any promises for future games. 
</P>
<P>
	Police Commissioner John Timoney said he would like to see the  
court continue because it helps deter serious offenses, such as 
carrying open containers and violence. But he said officers should 
not overreact and arrest fans just because they yell too loud. 
</P>
<P>
	``Being an obnoxious jerk is not against the law,'' he said.  
``It's not healthy if a fan is yelling and ... a cop is locking him 
up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A meeting with top police commanders this week could decide how  
stadium arrests and the court will be run. Timoney would not 
comment on whether he believed officers were making enough arrests. 
</P>
<P>
	McCaffery says that when Eagles Court first began two years ago,  
police and security worked hand-in-hand. But at the first two home 
games this year, dozens of fans were ejected without facing 
penalties, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	WIP sports radio talk-show host Glen Macnow said he expects fans  
to become more rowdy if they know there isn't a court waiting for 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	``The shame of it is that there are many people afraid to go to  
games, to bring their children to games, their wives to games,'' he 
said. ``If they stop the court, it's as if they are giving in to 
rowdyism.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
