<DOCNO> APW19990930.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 22:30:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Racer Craven Signs Extension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HARRISBURG, N.C. (AP) -- Ricky Craven has signed a one-year  
contract extension with the MidWest Transit team that will carry 
through the 2000 NASCAR Winston Cup season. 
</P>
<P>
	``We see Ricky as a smart, talented driver who represents  
MidWest Transit with class, both on and off the track,'' Hal Hicks, 
president of the company, said Thursday. ``We believe the talent 
and marketability he possesses will only enhance our ability to 
sign a primary sponsor in the very near future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Craven, 33, was the Winston Cup series rookie of the year in  
1995, and finished third in the 1997 Daytona 500 after moving to 
the third car fielded by Hendrick Motorsports. 
</P>
<P>
	He missed two races due to injuries in 1997, and early in the  
1998 season took himself out of the car after experiencing problems 
later diagnosed as post-concussion syndrome. 
</P>
<P>
	He returned to racing after missing three months, but was later  
let go by Hendrick Motorsports. 
</P>
<P>
	This summer, he signed with MidWest Transit. In seven races with  
the team, his best finish has been 13th but has more often 
struggled near the back of the field. 
</P>
<P>
	Craven and the MidWest Transit team plan to run a full schedule  
of Winston Cup races next year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've fully enjoyed the races we've run and I'm excited about  
our future together,'' Craven said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 15:20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Met Performs Original 'Lucia' Opera </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                     *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- ``Lucia di Lammermoor'' in its original version  
simply isn't as exciting as the production modern audiences are 
used to. 
</P>
<P>
	The Metropolitan Opera, with Charles Mackerras conducting,  
performed ``Lucia'' in the original version for the first time on 
Wednesday. As far as Mackerras knows, it's a first for New York. 
This version lacked most of the ringing, aria-ending high notes, 
including the high E flat that ends Lucia's famous mad scene. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrea Rost sang the title role in a pure, clear voice that was  
reminiscent of recordings by Lily Pons, whose 1931 Met debut was as 
Lucia. Rost still has plenty of coloratura singing to do and she 
sang with skill and grace. But the famous part of the mad scene in 
which soprano voice alternates with flute was gone. 
</P>
<P>
	An even more important problem with the mad scene is the  
staging. When this Nicolas Joel production was new last year, Lucia 
was outdoors and alone for her mad scene. This year, guests from 
her wedding stand on the sides of the stage. But the drama is 
greater in a traditional staging when, splattered with her 
bridegroom's blood, Lucia descends a staircase from an upstairs 
bedroom. 
</P>
<P>
	Roberto Frontali sang Enrico, Lucia's brother. He has a light,  
flexible baritone. Tenor Frank Lopardo sang Edgardo. He sang loud, 
sounding like he was forcing volume, through Act 1. Later, using 
more variety, he was more effective. 
</P>
<P>
	The Act 1 love duet between Edgardo and Lucia was not a high  
point on this occasion. Paul Plishka, who made his Met debut in 
1967, wasn't at his best as Lucia's tutor. 
</P>
<P>
	Singers caused original high keys of ``Lucia'' to be transposed  
down, so their high notes would be more sparkling in contrast. On 
Wednesday, the mad scene was sung in its original key of F and a 
glass harmonica, representing mental instability, was played. 
</P>
<P>
	Five more performances of the 1835 ``Lucia'' will be sung in  
October. In December, Ruth Ann Swenson will sing four performances 
of the traditional version, conducted by Edoardo Muller. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 13:00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mazda To Pay $5 Million Fine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Mazda will pay $5.25 million to settle charges  
it violated government agreements requiring that the automaker 
clearly disclose important car leasing terms in its advertising, 
federal regulators said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The civil penalties include a $4.05 million fine, the largest  
obtained by the Federal Trade Commission's bureau of consumer 
protection, for what the FTC said was a failure to abide by a 
February 1997 agency order about Mazda's advertising. 
</P>
<P>
	Mazda also agreed to pay a total of $1.2 million in fines and  
costs to 24 states. 
</P>
<P>
	The complaint and consent decree were filed Thursday in U.S.  
District Court in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Mazda, based in Irvine, Calif., said it has sought to comply  
with lease disclosure requirements and has put into practice new 
procedures to ensure full compliance. 
</P>
<P>
	The earlier FTC order prohibited Mazda's television ads from  
misrepresenting the total due at lease inception and from 
highlighting only the most attractive terms of the lease -- such as 
low monthly payments. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement also required Mazda to make a number of  
disclosures before it could state the amount of any payment. They 
included a clear and conspicuous disclosure that the transaction 
advertised is a lease, the total amount due at lease inception and 
whether a security deposit is required. 
</P>
<P>
	The FTC said Mazda continued to run ads in violation of the  
order until early 1998. For example, the disclosures were in small 
and unreadable print, offset by distracting images or sounds, or 
appeared on the screen for too short a time, the agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This substantial penalty should not only deter future  
violations of the commission's order by Mazda, but send a strong 
signal to everyone in the automobile industry -- manufacturers, 
dealers and advertising agencies -- that important leasing 
information cannot be buried in fine print,'' said Jodie Bernstein, 
director of the bureau of consumer protection. 
</P>
<P>
	Mazda said in a statement that consumers who leased cars between  
February 1997 and early 1998 were informed of the complete terms 
and conditions before signing any deal. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the settlement, the Mazda will distribute a consumer  
education brochure on vehicle leasing through its 750 U.S. dealers. 
</P>
<P>
	Mazda Motor of America Inc., doing business as Mazda North  
American Operations, is a subsidiary of Mazda Motor Corp. of 
Hiroshima, Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 20:05:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  MLS' Revolution Fires Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FOXBORO, Mass. (AP) -- Coach Walter Zenga was fired Thursday by  
the New England Revolution with two games left in the regular 
season. He was replaced by Steve Nicol, who coached the Boston 
Bulldogs of the A League in Framingham. 
</P>
<P>
	Zenga, who took over as player-coach with six games left last  
season, led the Revolution to a 10-20-4 record this year. With two 
games left, New England trails Miami by one point for the last 
playoff spot in the Eastern Conference. Zenga has a 5-13 record as 
a goalkeeper and will not continue as a player with the Revolution. 
</P>
<P>
	General manager Brian O'Donovan said Zenga didn't want to wait  
until the end of the season to discuss a contract extension. 
</P>
<P>
	``He also indicated to us that he had other options in Italy and  
needed to explore them immediately,'' O'Donovan said in a team 
statement. ``We received (Wednesday) a written ultimatum insisting 
that the team reach a decision. We would have preferred to evaluate 
fully the situation during the offseason and make our decision 
then.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zenga, 39, named the world's best goalkeeper after the 1990  
World Cup, played that position for the Revolution in 1997. He then 
retired from the team and returned to Italy. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0176 </DOCNO>
