<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Banks Agree To Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- Malaysia's central bank said  
Thursday that all the country's domestic financial institutions 
have signed agreements to merge into six big banking groups. 
</P>
<P>
	The 58 banks and finance companies signed memorandums of  
understanding as of Wednesday for the restructuring, according to a 
statement from Bank Negara, the central bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The central bank surprised bankers in July by announcing a  
drastic reorganization of the battered financial industry. It said 
it would force the merger of all the country's banks -- 21 
commercial banks, 25 finance companies and 12 merchant banks -- into 
six groups. 
</P>
<P>
	The authorities say the mergers were necessary to make the  
industry strong enough to compete with big foreign banks. The 
mergers are to be completed by next April. 
</P>
<P>
	Malaysia's biggest bank employees union has warned that the bank  
mergers could leave some 15,000 workers jobless. 
</P>
<P>
	The banking industry has often been criticized for Malaysia's  
economic fragility. Many banks during the boom years issued loans 
on insufficient collateral, leaving them saddled with bad debts 
when the economy sank in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	But some analysts say many of the banks were strong-armed into  
accepting the mergers. They say that the restructuring is driven by 
politics, with the government attempting to weaken bankers who are 
allies of Anwar Ibrahim, the ousted deputy prime minister and 
former finance minister. 
</P>
<P>
	Anwar is serving a six-year prison sentence for his conviction  
in April of corruption charges. He also faces sodomy charges, but 
denies any wrongdoing, saying they were crafted to end his 
challenge to Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
