<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Opens Education Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PALISADES, N.Y. (AP) -- Saying that Americans are ``hot to do the  
right thing to improve education,'' President Clinton urged the 
Republican-led Congress Thursday to approve his budget to hire new 
teachers, modernize schools and set standards in failing 
classrooms. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to give the schools the tools they need to do the  
job,'' the president said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton spoke before governors and business executives gathered  
for the National Education Summit, the third in a series of 
high-level meetings going back to 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	As Congress struggles to enact spending bills, education remains  
a divisive issue between Republicans and Democrats. ``We're having 
a big argument in Washington on the budget,'' Clinton said, adding, 
``I don't want to get into a partisan rerun of that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The House Appropriations Committee and the Senate moved toward  
approving similar $320 billion packages financing labor, health and 
education programs. But both faced veto threats because of cuts in 
Clinton's proposal to hire 100,000 new teachers and other programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said Americans still retain ``a passionate sense of  
national urgency about school reform'' 16 years after a landmark 
report called ``A Nation at Risk'' deplored the ``mediocre 
educational performance'' of the nation's schools. 
</P>
<P>
	``The country is as hot to do the right thing to improve the  
education of our children today as it was the day after the 'Nation 
at Risk' report was issued,'' the president said. 
</P>
<P>
	When Clinton spoke to the same gathering three years ago, 14  
states had standards defining what students should know at various 
grade levels. By the close of this school year, 49 states will have 
such standards in place. 
</P>
<P>
	The president urged governors to accelerate the pace of fixing  
low-performing schools. 
</P>
<P>
	The education summit is a continuation of an idea inaugurated by  
then-President Bush in 1989, when he gathered educators, governors 
and business leaders in Charlottesville, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	An ambitious education plan set at that gathering has fallen far  
short of its goal to make American schoolchildren first in the 
world in math and science. 
</P>
<P>
	Only in fourth-grade science did the United States lead the  
world, according to the Third International Mathematics and Science 
Study. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1989 gathering also set other broad education goals for 2000  
-- from ensuring children are properly immunized and eating the 
right foods so they are ready to learn, to raising the high school 
graduation rate to at least 90 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics said the goals were vague. Governors thought otherwise  
and adopted them. 
</P>
<P>
	While Bush launched the education reform package, Clinton, who  
headed the governor's association at the time, has popularized the 
goals with more than $1.7 billion in grants to help states set 
standards and find ways to chart progress. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton signed the Goals 2000: Educate America Act in 1994,  
writing the original education goals into law and adding new ones 
on teacher quality and parent involvement. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
