<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore, With Cuomo, Stumps in NY </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMSTERDAM, N.Y. (AP) -- A day after vowing to take his campaign  
directly to the people, Vice President Al Gore hits the streets of 
this once thriving factory town Thursday with the son of a famous 
New York Democrat as his escort. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo, son of former New York  
Gov. Mario Cuomo, accompanied Gore down a residential street toward 
a closed toy factory. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore chatted with bystanders and bounded up porch steps to shake  
the hands of potential voters and admire their babies. Homemade 
banners outside a nearby apartment building proclaimed ``Gore Pres. 
2000'' and ``Cuomo Gov. 2002.'' The younger Cuomo is considered a 
candidate for governor in 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	``Did you see Secretary Cuomo's advance work here?,'' Gore  
called to reporters, pointing to the banners. A sparse crowd of 
about 100 greeted the pair. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's visit to this area west of Albany came one day after the  
vice president, feeling a surge from rival Bill Bradley, announced 
he was moving his campaign headquarters from Washington to 
Tennessee and challenged Bradley to a series of debates. 
</P>
<P>
	Fresh evidence of Bradley's strength also was evident Thursday  
as campaign reports showed he was nearly even with Gore in fund 
raising between July and September. 
</P>
<P>
	New York, with its March 7 primary, is considered a crucial  
state for Gore. Recent polls have shown that his once hefty lead in 
the state over Bradley, a former New York Knicks star, has 
evaporated with the two now in a dead heat among Democratic voters. 
Those same polls also show Bradley, a former U.S. senator from New 
Jersey, running better than Gore against the Republican 
front-runner, Texas Gov. George W. Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	A larger crowd of about 450 people later greeted Gore and Cuomo  
at a forum on ``Tapping America's Potential.'' Democratic mayors, 
business executives, workers and public officials joined Gore in a 
discussion of how to survive tough economic times. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore also staged a fund-raising reception at a Manhattan hotel  
that aides said was expected to raise about $500,000. While some of 
Gore's own supporters have grumbled about the state of his 
campaign, he drew cheers by saying, ``The Republicans are in 
disarray. The far-right hand doesn't know what the right hand is 
doing.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
