<DOCNO> APW19990930.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 11:10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate GOP To Vote on Test Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After months of delay, Senate Republican  
leaders today did a turnabout and agreed to vote next week on a 
treaty to ban all nuclear testing worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Senate's Democratic leader, Tom Daschle of South Dakota,  
called the gesture hollow because it allowed only a single day's 
debate, and rejected the overture. 
</P>
<P>
	Democratic officials, speaking on the condition of anonymity,  
said an informal Democratic count showed they were at least 15 
votes short of the 67 needed to pass the treaty. The tally 
suggested all 45 Democrats and seven Republicans would vote for the 
treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	Lack of support for the pact clearly figured into the GOP change  
of strategy, said a senior Republican official, who also spoke on 
the condition of anonymity. Both sides have vote counts showing the 
treaty would be easily defeated, the GOP official said. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said he would  
schedule 10 hours of debate on the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, 
which has been signed by 152 nations, for Oct 6. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, Lott called the treaty ``bad for the country  
and dangerous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration and congressional Democrats have been  
leaning on the GOP leadership to bring up the measure, increasing 
the pressure in recent weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The pact has been bottled up in the Senate Foreign Relations  
Committee by chairman Jesse Helms, R-N.C., for two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott's offer would have required the unanimous consent of the  
Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Daschle immediately objected, saying, ``Ten hours of debate is  
totally insufficient amount of time for a treaty as important as 
this is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He called for hearings by the committee.  
</P>
<P>
	But Helms stood to assert that his panel had held at least nine  
hearings touching on the subject. He likened Democrats turning 
their back on a vote after pressing for it so long as ``rodents 
running to the hills.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If it were not so pitiful, this behavior would have been  
amusing,'' Helms said as the Senate erupted in a heated, 
unscheduled, debate on the subject. 
</P>
<P>
	The switch in strategy by the Republican leadership appeared to  
catch Democrats off guard. Those on both sides of the issue 
suggested that if a vote were held now, it was unlikely that 
supporters could muster the 67 votes -- or two thirds of the Senate 
-- needed to ratify the treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	However, not all Democrats agreed with Daschle.  
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., a leading Senate sponsor of the pact,  
said the approach outlined by Lott and Helms was ``all right with 
me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Bring it up next week,'' and let the votes fall where they  
may, asserted Dorgan. 
</P>
<P>
	Until now, Helms had refused to bring the treaty to a vote in  
his panel in a separate dispute with the administration on other 
matters. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1996 pact includes a pledge against all testing of nuclear  
devices and sets up a global system of sensors to monitor 
compliance. 
</P>
<P>
	It was signed by 152 nations, but ratification is moving slowly.  
So far, only 18 of the 44 nations with nuclear capabilities that 
must ratify the wide-ranging treaty have taken action. 
</P>
<P>
	The third anniversary of the treaty's opening for signature was  
Sept. 23. A conference will be held Oct. 6-8 in Vienna on the panel 
to consider what measures might be taken to get non-ratifying 
members to join. 
</P>
<P>
	Only nations that ratified the treaty could participate in the  
conference -- leaving the United States without direct influence. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the treaty, all 44 states with some nuclear capacity must  
sign for it to take effect. Even one holdout -- by, say, North Korea 
-- could keep the treaty from taking effect. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
