<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religion Today  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- When Congress passed the International  
Religious Freedom Act last October, it wanted to make fighting 
religious persecution worldwide a national priority. 
</P>
<P>
	Easier said than done.  
</P>
<P>
	The law's implementation was the subject of a conference this  
week at Trinity College, and participants at times disagreed 
sharply on whether government actions -- and the law itself -- will 
be an incentive or a barrier to broader religious freedom. 
</P>
<P>
	Steven McFarland, the new executive director of the Commission  
on International Religious Freedom, a body the law established to 
make policy recommendations, fears that the U.S. government could 
become its own obstacle. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department, he charges, has not complied with the  
act's requirement to name by Sept. 1 those countries deemed 
responsible for ``particularly severe violations of religious 
freedom.'' When a country is so designated, the president has 90 
days to report to Congress on action to be taken. 
</P>
<P>
	Whether the State Department is willing to name Cuba, Sudan and  
particularly China will be the litmus test of its commitment to 
ending religious persecution, McFarland says. Those countries were 
cited for religious rights violations in the State Department's 
first report on religious freedom, an 1,100-page document mandated 
by the bill and released this month. 
</P>
<P>
	In China, the report said, government intolerance of religious  
activity outside officially sponsored churches had led to 
harassment, prolonged detention, imprisonment in labor camps and 
police closure of places of worship. 
</P>
<P>
	``China is going to be the proof of the pudding,'' McFarland  
said during a break between conference sessions. ``No question in 
my mind they're a serious violator.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is considering all  
available evidence as she decides what action to take, said Thomas 
Farr, director of the State Department's Office of International 
Religious Freedom. ``The secretary is aware of the IRF Commission's 
strong recommendation on China and is weighing it carefully,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some human rights activists and scholars, on the other hand,  
worry about potential repercussions from singling out and 
sanctioning countries such as China. Even suspending cultural 
exchanges could discourage the kind of engagement that leads 
governments to make changes, says Mickey Spiegel, a China expert at 
Human Rights Watch. 
</P>
<P>
	But Laura Bryant, an aide to Rep. Bob Clement (D-Tenn.) and a  
co-drafter of the bill, says that naming violators is necessary to 
ensure that the State Department exerts pressure, whether through 
behind-the-scenes negotiations or tougher measures. 
</P>
<P>
	The law gives the president a range of options to punish a  
country that violates religious rights, including private or public 
condemnation, cancellation of scientific and cultural exchanges, 
suspension of some U.S. aid, cancellation of state visits, and the 
banning of new U.S. credits. The president may waive sanctions if 
he decides that it is in the national interest to do so or that the 
offending country has improved. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also set up the independent, 10-member bipartisan  
commission that McFarland heads, which will release its own report 
offering policy recommendations on religious freedom. 
</P>
<P>
	McFarland formerly directed the Center for Law and Religious  
Freedom, part of the Christian Legal Society, an organization of 
evangelical Protestant lawyers. As chairman of the watchdog 
commission, he has said he will encourage religious Americans to 
take up the fight for religious freedom. 
</P>
<P>
	Several participants at the Trinity conference expressed concern  
about whether the U.S. government can counter perceptions abroad 
that it cares most about protecting Christians. 
</P>
<P>
	Bryant says such fears are unfounded. While Christian  
conservatives were influential in the enactment of the statute, and 
an earlier proposed statute that focused more heavily on 
Christians, the new law doesn't target any one religion, she says. 
</P>
<P>
	State Department officials have said repeatedly that they will  
fight persecution of all religious groups, and will apply the law 
uniformly to countries. The department's annual report looks at the 
treatment of Buddhists, Muslims and Hindus, among others. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Emory University law professor Abdullahi Ahmed An-Na'im  
says many remember the early pro-Christian rhetoric and believe the 
United States is only interested in aiding American missionaries 
abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	J. Paul Martin, executive director of Columbia University's  
Center for the Study of Human Rights, goes further. In such 
countries as Russia, France, Belgium, and Germany, he says, many 
see Congress' action as ``part of a larger American imperialism.'' 
That could be lessened, he says, if U.S. activity was part of a 
more coordinated international human rights effort. 
</P>
<P>
	But T. Jeremy Gunn, an executive fellow at the U.S. Institute of  
Peace who worked at the State Department's religious freedom 
office, says that members of minority religions, such as Baptists 
and Pentecostals in Russia, appreciate U.S. involvement. 
</P>
<P>
	``What I hear from them is: `We are so pleased a country such as  
the U.S. is concerned about this issue,''' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	An-Na'im says that many foreign observers anticipate that the  
United States will go easy on its allies. Skeptics are going to 
watch, he says, to see if Sudan is punished while Saudi Arabia and 
Israel go free. All three countries were criticized for violating 
religious rights in the State Department report. 
</P>
<P>
	McFarland, meanwhile, is waiting to see if the State Department  
designates China as a violator. The commission has already drafted 
a press release objecting to a failure to single out China, he 
notes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully,'' he says, ``it will never have to be used.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
