<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rockies' Walker Has Knee Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Colorado Rockies right fielder Larry Walker was  
recovering at home Thursday after an operation to repair cartilage 
in his left knee. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker, who leads the majors with a .379 average, is expected to  
make a full recovery by spring training. 
</P>
<P>
	Bothered by injuries ranging from a broken collarbone to a torn  
rotator cuff, Walker has played 150 or more games just once in his 
11 seasons with Montreal and Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker's durability was a major factor last spring as he  
negotiated a $75 million, six-year contract extension that starts 
next season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Pretty much cursed,'' Walker said last week. ``There's a  
cloud, I guess. They say that people who get hurt aren't flexible. 
Well, I'm flexible, but I get hurt.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite starting only 111 games this year and playing in 127  
Walker hit 37 home runs, scored 108 runs and had 115 RBIs. He also 
had 11 stolen bases and hit .461 at Coors Field -- the highest home 
average since the Elias Sports Bureau began tracking such records 
25 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker is the first player to hit .360 or better in three  
consecutive seasons since Hall of Fame outfielder Al Simmons did it 
for the Philadelphia A's from 1929-31. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
