<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Sept. 30, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Close Higher; Dow Up 123.47  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rallied sharply today for the first time  
in nearly two weeks as a government report of slower economic 
growth raised hopes that the Federal Reserve won't raise interest 
rates next week. The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 123.47 
at 10,336.95, the index's second gain in eight sessions. It was 
also the Dow's biggest point gain since Sept. 3. Broader stock 
indicators were higher as well. The Nasdaq composite index rose 
16.26 to 2,746.53. A growing sense that the Fed may leave rates 
unchanged next week helped bond prices rise, pushing yields lower. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:  
Dow Industrials:        10,336.95  + 123.47
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1,899  Declines 1,177  Unchgd  474
NYSE Volume:         927,198,570
Most Active NYSE issue:         Safeway Inc38 1/16  - 4 3/16
S&AMP;P 500:         1281.43 + 13.06
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          788.23  +  8.19
Nasdaq Composite Index        2,746.53  + 16.26
Gold(final) -    $297.90    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Thu.
Silver(final) -   $5.530  troy oz., NY Comex spot month Thu.

</P>
<P>
	Economic Growth Slows in 2nd Qtr.  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. economy grew at an annual rate of 1.6  
percent, its slowest in four years, in the second quarter, the 
Commerce Department said today. However, many private economists 
believe the slowdown is only a brief pause. They are looking for 
growth in the current quarter to be at a rate of 4 percent or 
higher. On other subjjects, the government said corporate profits 
decreased at an annual rate of $9.5 billion in the second quarter, 
the worst performance in five years. And the Labor Department said 
the number of U.S. workers filing for unemployment benefits last 
week rose by 25,000 to 299,000, reflecting the impact of Hurricane 
Floyd. 

</P>
<P>
	Consumer Spending Outpaces Earnings  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Consumer spending outpaced earnings in the  
second quarter, the government said today. Spending rose at an 
annual rate of 4.8 percent and sent the personal savings rate -- 
savings as a percentage of disposable income - to a record low of 
negative 1.3 percent in the second quarter. 

</P>
<P>
	New Single-Home Sales Rise 2.9 Pct.  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sales of new single-family homes unexpectedly  
surged 2.9 percent in August to a seasonally adjusted annual rate 
of 983,000 units, the second-highest level on record, the Commerce 
Department said. The increase occurred despite rising mortgage 
rates and surprised analysts expecting a decline. In July, 955,000 
units were sold, reflecting a sharp downward revision from the 
government's previous estimate. Sales were up in all parts of the 
country except the South. 

</P>
<P>
	Kaiser Labor Dispute Reaches a Year  
</P>
<P>
	SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) -- The labor dispute at Kaiser Aluminum &AMP;  
Chemical Corp. turned a year old today. Members of the United 
Steelworkers of America scheduled rallies at the gates of two 
Kaiser plants in the Spokane area of Washington. They also 
announced they would escalate their public relations war against 
the company. Kaiser President Raymond J. Milchovich, in a full-page 
ad in The Spokesman-Review newspaper, blamed the union for 
prolonging the dispute. More than 2,900 Steelworkers at five Kaiser 
plants went on strike last Sept. 30 in a dispute over wages, 
benefits and, especially, job security. The workers later offered 
to return to work while negotiations continued. But the company 
locked them out. 

</P>
<P>
	Marriott To Buy Back 10.6M Shares  
</P>
<P>
	BETHESDA, Md. (AP) -- Marriott International Inc. today announced  
it was buying back 10.6 million shares worth more than $320 
million. It also reported that third-quarter earnings were up 12 
percent. The hotel and real estate firm credited cost control for 
the increased earnings. Marriott said net income was $96 million 
for the quarter ending Sept. 10, compared to $86 million in the 
same period a year ago. Per share earnings were 36 cents, compared 
to 32 cents in the corresponding quarter a year ago, the company 
said. Sales were $2 billion, up 11 percent from $1.8 billion in 
same period last year. 

</P>
<P>
	Judge OKs Boeing Settlement  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- A federal judge today approved a $15 million  
settlement of a racial discrimination lawsuit brought against The 
Boeing Co., saying it was the best way to encourage racial 
cooperation at the company. A group of black employees at the 
world's leading maker of commercial airplanes had argued before 
U.S. District Judge John Coughenour last week that the settlement 
was inadequate. But in his opinion, he said the settlement has a 
greater chance of fostering a cooperative relationship between 
Boeing and its African-American employees than would a series of 
protracted individual disputes.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Greyhound To Install Bus Lifts  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- To resolve allegations of discrimination,  
Greyhound Lines Inc. agreed today to phase in lift-equipped buses 
for disabled riders two years before it is required to have them. 
The Justice Department reached the out-of-court agreement with the 
nation's largest intercity bus company after receiving a number of 
complaints that Greyhound drivers and employees had violated the 
Americans With Disabilities Act by discriminating against the 
disabled. Most of the complaints involved refusal to aid a disabled 
person in boarding a bus, injuries that occurred when disabled 
riders were carried on or off buses or other alleged mistreatment, 
the department said. 

</P>
<P>
	Mazda To Pay $5 Million Fine  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Mazda will pay $5.25 million to settle charges  
it violated government agreements requiring that the automaker 
clearly disclose important car leasing terms in its advertising, 
federal regulators said today. The civil penalties include a $4.05 
million fine, the largest obtained by the Federal Trade 
Commission's bureau of consumer protection, for what the FTC said 
was a failure to abide by a February 1997 agency order about 
Mazda's advertising. Mazda also agreed to pay a total of $1.2 
million in fines and costs to 24 states. The complaint and consent 
decree were filed today in U.S. District Court in Los Angeles. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Reconsiders Encryption Ruling  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A federal appeals court agreed to  
reconsider its ruling against the Clinton administration's claim of 
veto power over the export or Internet posting of data-scrambling 
encryption codes for computer messages. A panel of the 9th U.S. 
Circuit Court of Appeals ruled 2-1 in May that encryption codes, 
which make computer files unreadable without a key, contain 
expressions of ideas and cannot be suppressed indefinitely by 
government officials. 

</P>
<P>
	Global Ban on Internet Taxes Sought  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration and Congress are  
urging that the World Trade Organization impose a permanent global 
ban on taxes and tariffs aimed specifically at Internet commerce. 
Of particular concern is the ``bit tax'' on transmission of digital 
data proposed by a recent United Nations report as a way for 
developing countries to gain revenue. The tax would increase based 
on the size of a computer file being transferred. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic reports:  
</P>
