<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> States Want To Duck Smoking Penalty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senators from several states are working to  
derail penalties in an anti-smoking law that could cost their 
states $37 million in drug treatment money. 
</P>
<P>
	Missouri stands to lose the most -- $9.6 million -- among seven  
states and the District of Columbia that missed their targets for 
curtailing underage smoking. Violations are determined by 
investigations into how many retailers are selling tobacco to 
minors. 
</P>
<P>
	For those that miss the mark, the law slashes 40 percent of this  
year's block grants for substance abuse and treatment programs. 
States may appeal the penalties. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican Sen. Christopher Bond of Missouri and Democratic Sen.  
Tom Harkin of Iowa said Thursday they worked out a deal to help 
states dodge the penalty with an amendment to spending legislation 
under full Senate consideration. 
</P>
<P>
	``This amendment allows Missouri to avoid the huge penalty by  
devoting a modest amount of money to solving the problem and making 
sure that kids can't buy cigarettes,'' Bond said. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure would allow states to avoid penalties by committing  
new funds toward initiatives to keep minors from buying tobacco 
products. Missouri would have to commit $1.2 million and might have 
to pass legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan sent Bond a letter dated Wednesday  
asking for help from Congress. State officials have said the 
resulting cuts could limit services ranging from treatment for 
pregnant crack addicts to housing for addicted kids 
</P>
<P>
	``A loss of this magnitude,'' Carnahan wrote, ``would not only  
completely undermine our ability to reach the goals of the Synar 
law in the future, but would decimate our efforts to combat 
substance abuse overall.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Carnahan's spokesman, Jerry Nachtigal, said Thursday the  
governor is open to ideas. 
</P>
<P>
	``We would certainly consider this as an option if we don't  
prevail on our appeal,'' Nachtigal said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1992 law was named for the late Rep. Mike Synar, D-Okla.,  
and requires states to pass laws banning tobacco sales to anyone 
under age 18 with aggressive enforcement measures that include 
random, unannounced inspections using decoy buyers at groceries and 
other retailers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration supports an easing of the penalties.  
</P>
<P>
	In addition to Missouri, states that would be penalized are  
Delaware, $2.2 million; Iowa, $5 million; Minnesota, $8.4 million; 
Oregon, $6 million; Rhode Island, $2.4 million; and Wyoming, 
$980,950. The District of Columbia would lose nearly $2 million. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
