<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Reconsiders Encryption Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A federal appeals court agreed Thursday to  
reconsider its ruling against the Clinton administration's claim of 
veto power over the export or Internet posting of data-scrambling 
encryption codes for computer messages. 
</P>
<P>
	A panel of the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled 2-1 in  
May that encryption codes, which make computer files unreadable 
without a key, contain expressions of ideas and cannot be 
suppressed indefinitely by government officials. 
</P>
<P>
	But on Thursday, the full court announced that a majority of its  
active judges had voted to grant a government request to refer the 
case to an 11-judge panel for a new hearing. No date has been set. 
</P>
<P>
	Two weeks ago, however, the administration announced it would  
allow high-tech companies to sell the most powerful data-scrambling 
technology overseas with almost no restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	That decision, issued over law enforcement objections, was  
designed to help U.S. companies compete against foreign rivals. It 
also helps consumers protect the privacy of their e-mail and online 
credit-card purchases. 
</P>
<P>
	The case before the appeals court involved a mathematician's  
challenge to Commerce Department regulations that treat 
high-powered encryption codes like military weapons, forbidding 
their export without a license. The rules also apply to the posting 
of encryption codes on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	In a May 6 ruling, the appellate panel said the lack of  
timetables or standards for such licensing allowed the government 
to restrain free expression indefinitely, with no clear criteria 
for review. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department asked for a rehearing, saying the ruling  
would diminish the government's ability to keep encryption 
technology from falling into the hands of ``potentially hostile 
foreign parties.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
