<DOCNO> APW19990930.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 23:30:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Buckeye's Look To Stop Badger's Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- At some point in the Wisconsin-Ohio State  
game Saturday, Ron Dayne will be running with the ball at full 
speed when he confronts a lone Buckeyes defender. 
</P>
<P>
	Then it'll be time for the potential tackler to decide how best  
to leash the Great Dayne. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody has to grab a piece of something, and he'll come  
down,'' Buckeyes defensive end Rodney Bailey said. 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe. Maybe not. The thing is, the 250-plus pound running back  
loves inflicting embarrassment -- if not pain -- on those confident 
enough to tackle him by themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like to have some contact because I miss playing defense,''  
Dayne said. ``I used to play defense in high school. Once I run 
over somebody, you know I feel a little bit better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before a team studies game films of Dayne, it must first study  
physics. Such as, what happens when a large, speeding object runs 
into a smaller, stationary one? 
</P>
<P>
	``I honestly think it could happen. I think a man can get hurt  
from trying to tackle another man,'' Bailey said. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the Buckeyes are exactly looking forward to it.  
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't say that's exciting because it's not going to be  
too easy, not going to be easy at all,'' linebacker Na'il Diggs 
said of a possible Diggs-Dayne introduction. ``But I'm always up 
for a challenge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dayne is a load, to say the least. And he has been for a lot of  
defenses that have more experience and perhaps more talent than 
Ohio State's, which surrendered 525 yards a week ago to Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	Dayne has 5,175 yards and needs just 3 to pass Ohio State's  
Archie Griffin and move into fifth place on the NCAA career rushing 
list. With 82 more yards, he'll pass Georgia's Herschel Walker for 
fourth place. 
</P>
<P>
	``The key to stopping him is to not let him get full momentum  
going forward,'' defensive end James Cotton said. 
</P>
<P>
	But what if it's just one defender and Dayne?  
</P>
<P>
	``He's human. It's not impossible. It can be done,'' linebacker  
Courtland Bullard said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dayne is listed at 5-foot-10, 248 pounds, but Ohio State coach  
John Cooper said he appears to be a lot heavier. 
</P>
<P>
	The Buckeyes rely on their safeties for run support, meaning  
195-pound Gary Berry and 203-pound freshman Donnie Nickey likely 
will be called on to abandon deep responsibilities to plug gaps up 
front. On sweeps, Dayne will more than likely make the acquaintance 
of cornerbacks Nate Clements (190 pounds) and Ahmed Plummer (193). 
</P>
<P>
	``If he gets through the linebackers and gets to a safety, and  
the safety gets run over, I think it's up to the safety to get up 
the next play and hit him just as hard,'' Diggs said. ``I don't see 
any of our safeties backpedaling trying to soften up on him because 
he ran them over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Plummer said stopping Dayne is the responsibility of the  
Buckeyes' front seven. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our job is not to stop the run; our job every game is to stop  
the pass,'' Plummer said. ``Hopefully Na'il and James Cotton and 
all of these other great linebackers and defensive linemen can stop 
the run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan limited Dayne to 88 yards on 22 carries and one  
touchdown in a 21-16 win last week. But Dayne still left 
black-and-blue marks on several potential tacklers on his rumble 
through the record book. 
</P>
<P>
	``For a guy who's 250-plus pounds, he's got good speed,'' Cooper  
said. ``You put him in the open and he will flat run over you. 
Very, very seldom do you see one guy knock him down.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
