<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Thomas of White Sox Begins Rehab </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Frank Thomas dismissed rumors he was feuding with  
Chicago White Sox manager Jerry Manuel, saying Thursday he was 
happy with the 1999 season. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas visited his teammates for the first time since a Sept. 13  
operation to remove a bone spur in his right ankle. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a very serious injury,'' Thomas said.  
</P>
<P>
	If Thomas had ruptured tendons, he could have been sidelined for  
more than one year. Instead, he will begin weight-bearing exercises 
next week and predicted he will be 100 percent by spring training. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas still needs to repair what was perceived to be a bad  
relationship with Manuel. The two reportedly argued after a 
doubleheader on Sept. 6, when Thomas told Manuel he was unavailable 
to pinch hit because of the pain in his ankle. 
</P>
<P>
	Manuel reportedly sent Thomas home for disciplinary reasons.  
Thomas said Thursday he was sent home to see doctors. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no problem with Jerry Manuel and I,'' Thomas said.  
``Jerry Manuel was upset that I couldn't play. Of course, he wanted 
me to play the rest of the season and I couldn't. That's the way it 
is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas said he was getting treatment during the entire  
doubleheader in Texas for his sore ankle, which he said started 
bothering him Aug. 23. 
</P>
<P>
	He also sparred with Manuel over playing first base. Manuel  
wanted him on the field, while Thomas wanted to be the designated 
hitter. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's humbling to hear all the bad things about me this year,''  
Thomas said. ``I was having a great season. I'm happy with the 
season. We're playing well. We're winning as a team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas finished with a .305 average, 15 homers, 77 RBIs, 87  
walks and 74 runs. It was the first time he did not drive in 100 
runs, draw 100 walks, score 100 runs or hit at least 20 homers 
since 1990, his first full season in the majors. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas ignored hitting coach Von Joshua until Sept. 1 when the  
two had their first session together -- at Manuel's insistence. 
</P>
<P>
	At that time, Manuel said, ``Our biggest goal as a staff is to  
get Frank back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas said he expects to hit more in the off season and do more  
agility drills, predicting he will return to form in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``I stuck out like a sore thumb on this team all year,'' he  
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
