<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Dips, Japanese Stocks Higher / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The U.S. dollar fell against the yen today, while  
Japanese share prices gained amid increased buying interest from 
both domestic and U.S. pension funds on the last day of the 
quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 105.66 yen, down 1.24 yen from late Wednesday  
in Tokyo and also below its late New York level of 106.98 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average climbed 323.18  
points, or 1.87 percent, to close at 17,605.46. On Wednesday, the 
average closed down 43.42 points, or 0.25 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the currency market, the dollar traded between 105.55 yen and  
107.35 yen, as speculation continued on whether the Bank of Japan 
might ease credit. 
</P>
<P>
	Monetary easing could weaken the yen against the U.S. currency,  
while a strong yen could derail Japan's recovery from recession by 
making Japanese exports more expensive abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of Japan usually increases money supply at the midpoint  
of Japan's fiscal year. The first half ended today. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said some overseas investors mistook today's action for  
an easing in monetary policy, pushing the dollar to an intraday 
high of 107.35 yen. But the move was later interpreted as a routine 
adjustment in the money supply, leading investors to sell dollars 
again and pushing the currency lower, dealers said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The dollar is likely to be supported by the specter of BOJ's  
easing for the near term,'' said Minoru Shioiri, assistant manager 
of foreign exchange at Nippon Credit Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	In the stock market, local and U.S. pension funds bought a broad  
range of international blue chips to enhance their portfolios at 
the end of the month, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Several investment trusts were also active buyers, targeting  
small- and mid-sized issues in particular, as well as other 
high-growth stocks, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hiroichi Nishi, deputy general manager at Nikko Securities Co.,  
said the stock market was boosted by some bullish factors, 
including the dollar's brief rise above 107 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the first section of the Tokyo stock exchange was  
estimated at 526.27 million shares, up from 373 million shares 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancers outnumbered retreaters 1,084 to 195, while 68 issues  
were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 34.91 points, or 2.39 percent, to 1,493.02. 
The index closed down 11.18 points, or 0.76 percent, the day 
before. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 112.24 yen, down  
slightly from 112.52 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.7100 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.6750 percent. Its 
price fell 0.21 points to 99.91. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
