<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marks &AMP; Spenceer Overhauls Board </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Ailing British retailer Marks &AMP; Spencer PLC is  
overhauling its management board structure to respond more quickly 
to customer needs, the company said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of the company's most senior directors will retire early as  
a result. 
</P>
<P>
	The moves are the latest step in chief executive Peter  
Salsbury's effort to reverse the plunging fortunes of one of 
Britain's most venerable department store chains. 
</P>
<P>
	Marks &AMP; Spencer's pretax profits for the year ending March 31  
fell 41 percent from the previous year. 
</P>
<P>
	The company has warned that profits for the first half of this  
fiscal year would be almost half last year's level, due largely to 
unseasonably warm weather that hurt initial sales of its autumn 
line of clothing. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the past year, Marks &AMP; Spencer has trimmed the size of its  
board to 14 from 21 members, and it has halved the number of its 
management layers. Company directors will now report directly to 
Salsbury rather than through divisional managing directors. 
</P>
<P>
	``This structure supports the key strategic steps ahead, such as  
the better procurement of merchandise, further development of the 
relationship with our customer, new selling channels and the 
cultural transformation of the business'', Salsbury said. 
</P>
<P>
	Directors Andrew Stone and James Benfield will both take early  
retirement. Stone, 57, has managed the company's clothing business 
in Britain. Benfield, 50, was replaced last week as marketing 
director. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, the chain announced it was closing its 38 Canadian  
stores after mounting losses. It also began laying off hundreds of 
managers. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, Marks &AMP; Spencer said it will sell its 25  
Kings Super Market stores in New Jersey. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
