<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Canadian Airlines' Future Weighed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Canada has two major airlines: Canadian Airlines,  
which is going broke, and Air Canada, whose disappointing 
performance has left its stock price languishing. A takeover 
specialist called Onex Corp. says it wants to buy both and turn 
them into a single, profitable company. 
</P>
<P>
	Canadian Airlines, which says it has only enough cash to keep  
going until next spring, has little choice in the matter. But Air 
Canada, the former national carrier that is now private, believes 
Onex's $4 billion bid is really an American plot -- led by rival 
American Airlines -- to take over the Canadian airline industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Amid the accusations, the Canadian government worries about  
foreign domination of its skies and consumer advocates wonder if 
anyone cares about how air passengers will be affected. 
</P>
<P>
	The acrimony began in late August after Toronto-based Onex  
offered $1.2 billion in cash and stock and $2.7 billion in debt 
assumption to take over the Canadian carriers. Air Canada charged 
that the bid was merely a front for an American Airlines, whose 
parent, AMR Corp., is backing Onex. AMR owns 25 percent of Canadian 
and would own 15 percent of the new airline. 
</P>
<P>
	Air Canada chief executive officer Robert Milton told Maclean's  
magazine that American Airlines ``is playing a brutal game of 
chicken with Canada.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But AMR chairman Donald Carty said American has no interest in  
running a Canadian airline. What it wants is routes to Asia from 
Vancouver and to Europe from Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	Prior to the Onex bid, it appeared that Air Canada was sitting  
back and waiting for Canadian to go bust. After its smaller 
competitor failed, Air Canada could pick up the pieces for little 
or nothing. Less than two weeks before Onex made its bid, Air 
Canada offered to buy Canadian's international routes, its most 
profitable. 
</P>
<P>
	Canadian called the offer ``just not acceptable.'' Now, pushed  
by the Onex offer, Air Canada is expected to come up with a 
counterproposal soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Air Canada has had problems of its own. Its stock, which traded  
at $5.50 a share after going public in 1988, now hovers in the 
$3.50 to $4 range. The Onex offer has a value of about $5.85 a 
share, although Onex says it really would be $8.25 if stockholders 
accept shares in the new merged airline as partial payment. 
</P>
<P>
	Douglas Reid, a professor of business strategy at Queens  
University, says the real issue in the takeover fight is whether 
there should be an airline monopoly in Canada. Travelers want 
convenient departure times and reasonable prices, and for that, 
there must be competition, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Monopoly is not good for the traveler,'' he says. ``The  
nationality of ownership isn't important ... it's a question of 
whether there will be competition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jennifer Hillard, vice president of the Consumers Association of  
Canada, agreed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to see Canadians having to fly from Vancouver to  
Toronto via Chicago just to get a decent fare,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Canadian government has joined in, concerned about who will  
own the country's airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	``The government remains absolutely committed to a  
Canadian-controlled airline industry,'' Transport Minister David 
Collenette said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Harry Gow, president of the lobby group Transport 2000, said  
of the takeover fight, ``this is a case of the chickens jumping 
into the pot and cooking themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``AMR is not something we want to have dominating the Canadian  
market, but they can hardly be blamed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some say that in the larger scheme of things, Canada is a  
battleground for two competing integrated airline networks -- 
American's Oneworld, with partners like Canadian Airlines, Quantas 
of Australia and British Airways and Star Alliance, with United 
Airlines, Air Canada and Germany's Lufthansa. 
</P>
<P>
	These networks allow travelers to accumulate and redeem  
frequent-flyer points on any of the allied airlines. Travelers can 
also buy a ticket through one carrier to the destinations of any of 
its partners, allowing each airline to offer hundreds of 
international destinations. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the Onex merger plan, American and Oneworld would come out  
on top, shutting out United and Star Alliance. 
</P>
<P>
	The main question, however, is whether Canada can support two  
major airlines. Evidence seems to indicate no, but some say 
Canadian Airlines' problems have always been poor management, not 
lack of market. 
</P>
<P>
	No matter what solution emerges, it seems certain Canada is  
headed toward an airline monopoly. That, says business professor 
Reid, is going to put heavy pressure on the government. 
</P>
<P>
	``A better way forward, whichever airline becomes the  
monopolist, is to open our skies to competition from any carrier, 
domestic or foreign, that meets Canada's standards for 
airworthiness and safety,'' he said. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
