<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 1,400 Blind Workers May Lose Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- When a government agency made a decision that  
would furlough six blind workers, Bob Berrang was caught off-guard. 
</P>
<P>
	The general manager for the Virginia Industries for the Blind  
thought he had landed good jobs for the workers in Franconia, Va., 
as customer service representatives for the General Services 
Administration, the government's purchasing agent and landlord. 
</P>
<P>
	``Six is a lot,'' Berrang said. ``We've been looking for other  
opportunities for those folks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A GSA decision to close eight government supply facilities,  
including the one in Franconia, means more than 1,400 blind workers 
face the same plight, say people who run associations for the 
blind. 
</P>
<P>
	The facilities, which employ the blind and sell products they  
make to federal agencies, will begin to shut down in mid-October as 
the GSA tries to streamline operations. 
</P>
<P>
	GSA Administrator David Barram said Wednesday the impact on the  
blind workers was inadvertent and he promised to implement a plan 
to help organizations that employ blind workers market their 
products to the government through other avenues. 
</P>
<P>
	In line with a 1938 law, the government has long given special  
consideration to organizations that sell products -- of competitive 
price and quality -- made by the blind. The unemployment rate for 
this group is more than 70 percent, say advocates for the blind. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Industries for the Blind -- the umbrella group for  
88 organizations that provide services and jobs to the blind -- has 
been scrambling to find customers for more than $135 million of 
goods normally bought by GSA. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our agencies produce everything from (computer) mouse pads to  
mops for staffers in the city to soldiers in Kosovo,'' said the 
group's president, Jim Gibbons. ``We are looking for a plan we can 
wrap our arms around.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barram said the GSA had no choice but to change its purchasing  
practices. 
</P>
<P>
	``The commercial and federal market place is changing,'' he said  
in a statement. ``Super stores, e-commerce, Internet buying and the 
government purchase card have revolutionized the way everyone 
buys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Local organizations for the blind are struggling with the  
planned shutdown of the eight GSA facilities. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Rhinesmith, president of York Industries for the Blind in  
Pennsylvania, said he ``saw the writing on the wall'' and began 
looking for other customers four years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	In contrast, at the San Antonio Lighthouse, which employs 120  
blind workers, president Bob Plunkett last week introduced a 
three-day work week and laid off 23 part-time employees. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our concern in San Antonio is not what is being done, but how  
it is being done ... without any real consideration to the impact 
of a small but very important program,'' Plunkett said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
