<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kaiser Labor Dispute Reaches a Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) -- The labor dispute at Kaiser Aluminum &AMP;  
Chemical Corp. turned a year old on Thursday, with both sides doing 
plenty of talking, but not to each other. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of the United Steelworkers of America scheduled rallies  
at the gates of two Kaiser plants in the Spokane area of 
Washington. They also announced they would escalate their public 
relations war against the nation's fifth largest aluminum maker. 
</P>
<P>
	Kaiser President Raymond J. Milchovich, in a full-page ad in The  
Spokesman-Review newspaper, blamed the union for prolonging the 
dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 2,900 Steelworkers at five Kaiser plants went on  
strike last Sept. 30 in a dispute over wages, benefits and, 
especially, job security. 
</P>
<P>
	The workers later offered to return to work while negotiations  
continued. But on Jan. 14 the company locked them out, saying it 
would be in a weaker negotiating position with disgruntled workers 
in the plants. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an anniversary that none of us wanted to see,''  
Milchovich wrote. ``Kaiser has offered the Steelworkers Union a 
contract that provides for wage and benefit increases in exchange 
for productivity improvements.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, the leaders of most major religious groups in  
Eastern Washington released a letter urging the company and union 
to end the dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	``The human suffering and pain that this situation has caused  
needs to be acknowledged,'' the letter said. 
</P>
<P>
	It called on the company to end the lockout and both sides to  
commit to negotiating a settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	About 2,000 of the workers operate the two Spokane-area plants.  
The rest work at much smaller operations in Tacoma, Wash., 
Gramercy, La., and Newark, Ohio. 
</P>
<P>
	The five plants have been operating with managers and  
replacement workers since the strike began. There have been 
occasional talks, but no new negotiations are scheduled. Kaiser has 
lost almost $93 million in the three quarters since the dispute 
began. 
</P>
<P>
	In its latest offer, Kaiser proposed pay increases of $3.13 per  
hour over the length of a 5-year contract, plus some benefits 
improvements. The company said base wages for its workers are more 
than $40,000 a year. 
</P>
<P>
	But Kaiser is also demanding that 700 jobs be eliminated at the  
five plants, which it contends can be accomplished mostly by 
attrition. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also wants 239 jobs currently covered by the  
Steelworkers' contract to be given to nonunion workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Steelworkers plan to escalate their campaign against Kaiser.  
That will include expanded efforts to end The Boeing Co.'s use of 
Kaiser aluminum produced by replacement workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Steelworkers have repeatedly implied that the aluminum produced  
by the replacements is of lower quality, but the company and some 
of its customers have denied that. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
