<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former First Lady on Campaign Trail </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Barbara Bush isn't satisfied that ``one  
out of every eight Americans is governed by a Bush.'' She wants to 
make that all Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	The former first lady said Thursday that she was delighted to be  
back on the campaign trail, this time on behalf of her oldest son, 
George W. Bush, the Republican presidential front-runner. ``I love 
the candidate,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Bush spoke at a $100-a-plate lunch that aides said was her  
first public appearance on behalf of her son's presidential 
campaign. Coupled with a $1,000 per person reception, she raised 
$100,000 for the Bush campaign, which reported Thursday that it had 
collected more than $56 million thus far this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The matron of a political dynasty, Mrs. Bush noted that her sons  
govern the second- and fourth-largest states in the nation and are 
striving to move higher as Bush, the Texas governor, seeks the 
Republican presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	``One out of every eight Americans is governed by a Bush,'' Mrs.  
Bush said. ``With your help, we'll make that all Americans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's brother Jeb Bush is governor of Florida.  
</P>
<P>
	Former President Bush will be in Iowa next week campaigning for  
his son, but Eric Woolson, a campaign spokesman, said there are no 
plans to have mom and dad campaign extensively. 
</P>
<P>
	``We expect we'll probably see them back in the state before the  
caucuses, but we don't anticipate they'll be doing very much,'' 
Woolson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meeting briefly with reporters, Mrs. Bush dismissed suggestions  
of improper behavior in her son's personal life. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't bother me, because there's nothing wrong with his  
personal life at all, so it doesn't bother me,'' Mrs. Bush said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush has admitted to irresponsible behavior as a young man, but  
has not detailed that action. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush has campaigned less extensively in the state than some of  
his rivals, but he has a host of big-name backers to fill in for 
him and Mrs. Bush drew a crowd of several hundred to the luncheon. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has other things to do and I was out in this part of the  
world,'' Mrs. Bush said when a reporter asked why she was 
campaigning instead of her son. 
</P>
<P>
	During her speech, Mrs. Bush recounted her history of  
campaigning in Iowa dating back to 1979, when her husband 
unsuccessfully sought the Republican presidential nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	``If his father and I had had crowds like this, our life would  
have been considerably easier,'' Mrs. Bush said. The former 
president was ousted by Bill Clinton in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	While her campaign time will be limited, Mrs. Bush said she'll  
do her part to help her son become the next president. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's overwhelming to a mother to even say those words,'' Mrs.  
Bush said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
