<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuador Defaults on $6B Brady Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Creditors faced a decision on whether to press  
Ecuador for full payment of its $6 billion debt after the South 
American country became the first ever to default on its 
U.S.-guaranteed ``Brady bonds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brady bonds, named after former U.S. Treasury Secretary Nicholas  
Brady, were created to resolve the Latin American debt crisis of 
the 1980s. They are partly backed by U.S. Treasury securities. 
Though other nations have restructured their payments, no country 
before Ecuador has ever defaulted. 
</P>
<P>
	The failure to make a $98 million interest payment on Thursday  
had been expected for weeks and should have little short-term 
impact, said Ramon Aracena, an economist with the Institute of 
International Finance in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, however, it could make borrowing harder for other  
developing countries as investors perceive them as being on riskier 
financial ground. Ecuador's prospects for long-term growth could be 
damaged as well, because having assets seized overseas to pay the 
debt would leave the government fewer resources to create jobs, 
Aracena said. 
</P>
<P>
	New York-based Chase Manhattan Corp., which has acted as an  
agent for creditors, counted votes Thursday on whether investors 
should press for full repayment or allow a financial restructuring. 
Chase said the voting was to continue Friday because neither camp 
had the required votes needed to decide a course of action. 
</P>
<P>
	But there were some hopeful developments.  
</P>
<P>
	At the country's capital of Quito, President Jamil Mahuad said  
Thursday that his government had signed a letter of intent with the 
International Monetary Fund for a $400 million loan that could lead 
to $1.3 billion in overall international aid. 
</P>
<P>
	Ecuador is laboring under its worst economic crisis in 70 years,  
and the South American nation of 12 million people has so far been 
unable to come up with the $98 million interest payment that was 
due Aug. 31. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, Mahuad said Ecuador would take advantage of a grace  
period, deferring the interest payment until Thursday and buying 
time to build consensus for restructuring. The deadline passed 
Thursday without the payment. 
</P>
<P>
	IMF officials urged Ecuador to develop a new economic strategy  
and reach a comprehensive accord with creditors before collecting 
the 18-month $400 million credit. The deal hinges on Ecuador 
passing austerity measures and tax increases that most lawmakers 
there oppose. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking at United Nations headquarters in New York, Ecuador's  
foreign affairs minister said repairing damage from last year's 
widespread flooding, coupled with the economic hardship of 
declining oil prices -- the nation's primary export -- made it 
difficult for Ecuador to meet its loan payments. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign Minister Benjamin Ortiz Brennan told the assembly  
Ecuador ``is preparing to commence a process of restructuring these 
obligations that will enable it to share, in a more equal way, the 
debt load among all the actors of this financial relationship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He did not provide details, and no one from the Ecuador Mission  
immediately returned phone calls seeking explanation. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem of restructuring is complicated because no  
individual or institutional investor holds a majority of Ecuador's 
Brady bonds, and there appeared to be no coordinated group for 
Ecuadorian officials to negotiate with. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not like the old days when the banks made the loans,''  
said Andrew Tuck, of Chase, the acting fiscal agent between Ecuador 
and its Brady investors. ``We live in a different world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tuck said investors began faxing instructions to Chase weeks  
ago, indicating whether they favored accelerating Ecuador's debt 
payments -- in effect calling in the loan for full or partial 
payment immediately -- or seizing a portion of the country's 
collateral to make payments. 
</P>
<P>
	Though Ecuador's total public debt is $13 billion -- expected to  
top 117 percent of the country's gross domestic product by Dec. 31 
-- President Mahuad has said he would limit the debt restructuring 
to Brady bonds. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
