<HEADLINE> Protest Outside Clinton's New Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHAPPAQUA, N.Y. (AP) -- As some neighbors cringed, two dozen  
candle-carrying protesters marched at the house President Clinton 
wants to buy in a protest seeking stronger U.S. action in East 
Timor. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides the protesters, who sang quietly, the demonstration  
Wednesday night drew reporters, photographers and TV trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's going to be 30 times worse when they move here,''  
said Ken Kosyk, an investment counselor who lives on the next 
block. ``It's aggravating to the town as a whole. But what can you 
do?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president and first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton have agreed  
to buy a $1.7 million house in the town, which would satisfy New 
York's residency requirement should Mrs. Clinton decide, as 
expected, to run for the U.S. Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	The Westchester People's Action Coalition figured a protest at  
Clinton's future home would attract his attention, demonstrators 
said. The group wants Clinton to take stronger action to prevent 
killings of independence-minded East Timorese. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're hoping to get him interested,'' said Vincent Romano, who  
was holding up one corner of a mock coffin. Police kept the 
protesters behind a barricade. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House had no comment.  
  	   	
</P>
