<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rite Aid Might Sale PCS Health Unit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In a bid to stem rising debt, Rite Aid Corp. is  
considering the sale of part of its PCS Health Systems division, 
just eight months after buying the pharmacy benefits manager for 
$1.5 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The company has received unsolicited offers for PCS that value  
the division at more than $1.5 billion and may be willing to sell 
part of the operation, Rite Aid spokeswoman Karen Rugen said 
Thursday, confirming a report in The Wall Street Journal. 
</P>
<P>
	But, she added, ``we are not actively looking for a buyer for  
PCS,'' and the company would be careful not to sell any part of the 
division that benefits Rite Aid's core, retail drug business. 
</P>
<P>
	Rite Aid chief executive Martin Grass disclosed the plans in an  
impromptu conference call with securities analysts Wednesday, the 
Journal reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The call, held after the close of the markets, was meant to  
reassure investors about the Camp Hill, Pa.-based company's 
prospects amid rising debt and mixed sales results released earlier 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``My goal in the near future is to de-leverage the company and  
focus on cash generation going forward,'' he said. ``We have the 
ability to meet all our scheduled obligations going forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rite Aid's debt has risen to $5.1 billion from $3.6 billion a  
year ago, mostly because of the PCS purchase from Eli Lilly &AMP; Co., 
the Journal said. 
</P>
<P>
	Grass said Rite Aid has received ``unsolicited offers'' for PCS  
that value the company at more than $1.5 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Rite Aid, the nation's No. 3 drugstore chain, reported that  
sales at stores open a year or longer, rose 8.3 percent in 
September, and prescription sales growth was up 16.7 percent. But 
other merchandise, so-called front-end sales, fell 2 percent in the 
four weeks ended Sept. 25. 
</P>
<P>
	Rite Aid's stock rose 56 1/4 cents per share to $13.18 3/4, or 3.3  
percent, in trading on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Grass also said the company plans to sell 250 of its  
poorer-performing Western stores. It recently agreed to sell 38 of 
those stores in California for $186 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The company is talking to six potential buyers, which he didn't  
identify. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
