<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 16:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bills and Marino Butt Heads Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORCHARD PARK, N.Y. (AP) -- There's one thing the Buffalo Bills  
can always count on when they play Miami: Dan Marino will be there 
to make their lives miserable. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bills have handled Marino better than any AFC East rival  
over the years, but Miami has won five straight at home against the 
Bills, including in last season's playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every time you play Miami, you think of Dan Marino,'' Bills  
cornerback Ken Irvin said. ``A lot of teams prepare their game plan 
around him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Part of Buffalo's plan for Monday night's game in Miami  
apparently involves a pre-emptive strike of kindness. That's 
because Pat Bowlen lit a fire under Marino before the season when 
the Broncos owner said, ``Dan Marino, if he isn't on his last legs, 
he's very close to being on his last legs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Big mistake. The Bills won't go there, but they won't back off.  
``He's the greatest still playing,'' defensive end Marcellus Wiley 
said. ``But we're coming. We have something to prove -- that we're 
also one of the elite teams.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Dolphins quarterback, 38, occupies 46 pages of the team  
media guide and a prominent place in the minds of Buffalo 
defenders. 
</P>
<P>
	``Quick release, hasn't been sacked,'' Wiley said. ``I heard  
he's chasing a ring this year. Looks good on film. His presence 
alone is enough to inspire a team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marino is especially tough at home, but he proved he can win  
anywhere when he steered the Dolphins to a stunning 38-21 victory 
over the defending Super Bowl champion Broncos at Mile High Stadium 
in the opener. 
</P>
<P>
	Marino is 13-16 against Buffalo without the luxury of a  
consistent running game. Marino has completed 62 percent of his 
career passes against the Bills for 7,302 yards and 49 touchdowns 
with 33 interceptions. 
</P>
<P>
	In his 17th season, Marino has thrown for more yards -- 59,349,  
including this season's 436 -- than anyone in NFL history. He's 
thrown more passes (8,047) for more completions (4,799) and more 
touchdowns (411) with more interceptions (237) than anyone, and is 
the fifth-ranked passer in the AFC this season. He's thrown to Mark 
Clayton, Mark Duper and Nat Moore; he's still throwing to O.J. 
McDuffie, who led the league in receptions with 90 last year and 
now leads Miami with eight. 
</P>
<P>
	``He throws the ball as well as anybody ever has in this game,''  
said Bills quarterback Doug Flutie, who is 3-1 in NFL starts 
against Marino and whose Boston College Eagles narrowly lost to 
Marino's No. 2 Pittsburgh Panthers in 1981. 
</P>
<P>
	Marino's best deep threat is Tony Martin, averaging 22 yards per  
catch. ``Tony and Dan are just now getting on the same page, 
because (Martin) missed a lot of training camp,'' Miami coach Jimmy 
Johnson said. ``Tony made some big plays for us in the opening game 
against Denver. He's extremely smooth, he catches the ball 
extremely well, and we've got to get the ball in his hands more 
than we have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mmiami's offense is improved over last season. It's deeper,  
faster, better-balanced. Marino still makes it go. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anytime you have Dan Marino, you have a ready-made offense,''  
Bills coach Wade Phillips said. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson has done everything he can to wean his Dolphins off an  
over-reliance on Marino. The Dolphins averaged 3.4 yards per carry 
last year, worst in the NFL, and sputtered in short-yardage 
situations. 
</P>
<P>
	They know they have to pick up the running game to complement  
the pass, but injuries have made things tough. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were making some progress last year,'' said Johnson, who  
lost left tackle Richmond Webb, LG Mark Dixon and RG Kevin 
Donnalley. ``Once those three got banged up from about midseason 
on, we went back to our security blanket of Dan throwing the 
football. 
</P>
<P>
	``When that happens, you don't have the consistency, you start  
to turn the ball over more and you have some problems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Guard Kevin Gogan and tight end Hunter Goodwin have provided  
depth, and the Dolphins have run the ball six more times than they 
have thrown it, but with little success: Miami is averaging 3 yards 
per carry. 
</P>
<P>
	Believe it or not, that could be bad news for the Bills.  
</P>
<P>
	``Problem is, if you stop the running game you force Dan Marino  
to throw,'' Phillips said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
