<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Some Unhappy With Anthrax Vaccine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Top military commanders told Congress today  
that the mandatory program to inoculate soldiers with an anthrax 
vaccine is imperative because several nations are developing the 
biological weapon for use in battle. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense Secretary William Cohen last year ordered all 2.4  
million active duty and reserve troops to get the anthrax vaccine 
as protection against biological warfare. Some 340,000 service 
members have been immunized so far. 
</P>
<P>
	About 220 troops have refused to take it because of questions  
about its safety and efficacy. Symptoms reported after the shots 
have included fever, dizziness, blackouts and joint and muscle 
pain. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are 10 countries in this world that have already taken  
the steps to put anthrax in a bomb or a missile,'' Deputy Defense 
Secretary John Hamre testified before the House Armed Services 
personnel subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamre singled out Iraq as posing a potential threat, saying in  
1997 the military received evidence that Iraq had weapons 
containing anthrax. ``We have got absolute, incontrovertible 
evidence we have this threat,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamre and Gen. Anthony Zinni, who leads U.S. forces in the  
Persian Gulf region, said troops at risk must be vaccinated or they 
would die if exposed to the biological weapon. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wouldn't send them into combat without bullets... and we're  
not going to send them into combat without protection against an 
agent we know they will use against us to kill our troops,'' Hamre 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The hearing was the second in as many days as House lawmakers  
questioned military officials about the safety and effectiveness of 
the vaccine. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense officials and the Army surgeon general repeatedly said  
the vaccine was safe. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, some National Guard and reserve troops told  
lawmakers at a separate hearing that questions about the safety of 
the inoculations could push pilots and other reservists to leave 
the military. 
</P>
<P>
	``The dread and the fear is out there on the flight line. People  
are afraid. They're angry,'' Lt. Col. Thomas Heemstra, a pilot with 
the Indiana Air National Guard, told the Government Reform national 
security subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel uncomfortable with the vaccine,'' said Maj. Cheryl  
Hansen, an Air Force Reserves nurse based in Pennsylvania. ``We're 
faced with either resigning or taking the vaccine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The House panels also released Defense Department data  
indicating that 32,681 reserve and National Guard members had 
received one or more shots of the vaccine, but almost half had not 
received follow-up shots on time. In some cases, entire units had 
missed the schedule by a month or more. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Chris Shays, R-Conn., chairman of the national security  
subcommittee, said that was troubling in light of a Defense 
Department policy document that says any deviation from the 
FDA-approved six-shot regime over 18 months meant officials were 
``less certain'' of ``the protective effect on humans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Charles Cragin, a deputy assistant defense secretary, told  
lawmakers that most reservists and National Guard members were 
listed as overdue for shots because there was a delay in entering 
the data into a central computer system. He also said the number of 
reserve and guard members receiving shots was closer to 27,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of the overdues are a result of delayed reporting rather  
than lack of timeliness for the shots,'' Cragin testified. 
</P>
<P>
	Shays responded: ``Either ... (the data system) is inaccurate or  
compliance with the FDA-prescribed shot regimen in reserve 
component units is routinely failing. In either event, the program 
has a serious problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers also tried to reconcile the assurances of military  
officials that the vaccine program was safe and successful with 
anecdotal reports from reservists who said morale was plummeting 
and colleagues would resign rather than take the vaccine. 
</P>
<P>
	Half of the total U.S. military force are National Guard and  
reserve troops. 
</P>
<P>
	Heemstra, an airline pilot who was recently asked to resign as  
an F-16 squadron commander after refusing to take his first shot, 
predicted his squadron would lose 50 percent of its pilots. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are the guinea pigs,'' Heemstra said. ``It's a serious  
safety issue. People are sick.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
