<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pistons Center Reportedly To Retire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUBURN HILLS (AP) -- Detroit center Bison Dele has reportedly  
told the Pistons he plans to retire, although his agent said the 
decision could change after Dele returns to the United States in 
about 10 days. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's going through an epiphanal moment in his life,'' agent  
Dwight Manley said. ``We'll sit down with the team when he gets 
back and we'll discuss everything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dele, 30, told the Pistons of his intentions this week and has  
resisted management's efforts to persuade him to return, The 
Detroit News and the Detroit Free Press said Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He told me that he was tired and his heart was not in it,''  
Joe Dumars, Pistons director of player of personnel, told the News. 
``He said he did not have the motivation to keep on playing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dele was in the Middle East, Manley told The Associated Press,  
and could not be reached for comment. Pistons spokesman J.J. Carter 
said he did not know of Dele's plans. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously with Bison, anything can happen, and we are very  
hopeful that he shows up,'' coach Alvin Gentry told the News. ``We 
hope he comes to camp, and we would welcome him with open arms. He 
is a very integral part of this team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pistons players are scheduled to report to training camp Monday;  
the first practices will be Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Dele, a 6-foot-11 center, was about to begin his third season in  
Detroit. He stands to walk away from about $30 million, with five 
years left on a contract that called for him to receive $45 million 
for seven seasons. He was the team's highest-paid player. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pistons now could begin training camp without a starting  
center. For now, they will use Terry Mills, Christian Laettner or 
Eric Montross. 
</P>
<P>
	Dele spent two seasons in Detroit after signing as a free agent,  
and his relationship with his teammates was known to be strained. 
Dele's name came up frequently in trade rumors over the summer, 
although Manley acknowledged that there has been little interest 
from other teams. 
</P>
<P>
	When the team signed Michael Curry as a free agent in August, he  
came to Dele's defense at a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to be the first to say that Bison Dele is not a  
scapegoat for this team,'' Curry said. ``I felt in the last couple 
of years, because of what the team accomplished before he got here 
and with his salary, I think that he has been used as a scapegoat. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bison is just like another member of this team -- we need him  
to play and play hard. He's going to have his ups and downs just 
like everybody else, but he is part of our family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Soon after joining the Pistons, Dele admitted his passion for  
basketball was not the greatest. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never really had the kind of passion for basketball that my  
dad had for music,'' said Dele, whose father was a member of the 
Platters. ``If I had the same kind of passion for basketball as my 
dad had for music, I probably would be a better player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dele came to the Pistons after playing nine regular-season games  
and in the playoffs for the Chicago Bulls during their fifth 
championship season. 
</P>
<P>
	In Detroit, Dele averaged 10.5 points and 6.2 rebounds last  
season, 16.2 points and 8.9 rebounds the year before. 
</P>
<P>
	Before last season, Dele changed his name from Brian Williams,  
saying he made the switch after studying his family's roots. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
