<HEADLINE> Consolidated Papers Avert Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WISCONSIN RAPIDS, Wis. (AP) -- Members of unions representing  
about 2,800 paperworkers at Consolidated Papers Inc. ratified a 
six-year contract Thursday, averting a strike that had been 
authorized for Friday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Union leaders said 93 percent of the membership voted, and 77  
percent of those voted to ratify the pact, which includes wage 
increases of 3 percent each year. 
</P>
<P>
	With the first raise, the average wage will be $17.29 an hour,  
said Leon Towne, vice president and Region 10 director for the 
Paper, Allied-Industrial, Chemical and Energy (PACE) Workers' 
International Union. 
</P>
<P>
	The papermakers at several Consolidated Papers plants in central  
Wisconsin rejected the company's first contract offer three weeks 
ago, leading to talks this week that involved a federal mediator. 
The old contract expired last spring. 
</P>
<P>
	The stumbling block had been the fringe benefits package, Towne  
said. The company's latest offer included some ``structural 
changes'' in the health benefits package that made it better for 
workers, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Leaders of five locals voting on the new contract had  
recommended approval of the contract, Towne said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a good wage and benefit package,'' he said. ``Within  
the industry, it is a good offer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	John Steele, a Consolidated Papers vice president who negotiated  
the deal, said the company was pleased to have resolved the issues 
that blocked earlier proposals. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have consistently believed that a strike would have been a  
`lose-lose' situation, damaging to both the company and to union 
members,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The papermakers is the largest union at the company. A strike  
would have been the first by the papermakers union since 1957 and 
first major strike at the company since 1966. 
</P>
<P>
	Consolidated Papers is North America's largest producer of  
coated printing papers and a major manufacturer of specialty papers 
for the printing and publishing industries. 
</P>
<P>
	The company employs about 6,800 workers. Labor contracts with  
four other unions also have expired, said Tim Laatsch, a 
Consolidated Papers spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	Consolidated Papers earned $102.4 million on sales of $2 billion  
in 1998. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
