<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `Save the Grizzlies' Campaign Held </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- A group of prominent  
officials led by former mayor Art Phillips unveiled a `We Love Our 
Grizzlies' campaign Thursday in response to continued speculation 
that new owner Bill Laurie was prepared to move the franchise to 
St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a basketball fan. I really felt sick (when the Grizzlies  
were sold). If the team left, I couldn't cheer for the St. Louis 
Grizzlies,'' Phillips said. ``If you're a basketball fan, you go 
out there and buy tickets. That's the only way we're going to keep 
basketball in this town.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The group wants to generate sustained interest in the team by  
inspiring more ticket sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Laurie, married to Wal-Mart fortune heir Nancy Laurie, purchased  
the Grizzlies for $200 million a week ago. He also recently bought 
the NHL St. Louis Blues and the downtown St. Louis Kiel Center 
arena. 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference announcing the purchase, Laurie repeatedly  
said he had ``no current plan to move the Grizzlies,'' but that 
left many Vancouverites skeptical. 
</P>
<P>
	Referring to the day of the sale as ``Black Thursday,'' Phillips  
said it was imperative that Grizzlies fans rally behind the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first message we want to get out to people is it's not  
inevitable (the team will move). And the second is that they can do 
something about it,'' said Phillips, a devout Grizzlies fan who 
served a four-year term as Vancouver mayor in the 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no idea what the odds are. I know that we could win, I  
know we could lose. But I sure as hell don't want to walk away from 
this and just quit because there's a chance of losing,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the Grizzlies drew an average 16,725 last season, their  
season-ticket sales have reportedly dropped dramatically. The team 
won't release how many season-ticket subscribers remain after 
surpassing the NBA-required 12,500 in its expansion year. 
</P>
<P>
	Current Vancouver mayor Phillip Owen was on hand to offer the  
city's moral support. 
</P>
<P>
	Also on hand at the news conference was former Grizzlies owner  
Arthur Griffiths, who brought the team to Vancouver in 1995 before 
eventually selling his share to John McCaw. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's an element of the business community and the fans on  
the street that are of the view that this franchise is important to 
them,'' said Griffiths. ``I'm here as a fan.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
