<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 16:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mass. Court: Student Can Sue School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- In a case that could affect disciplinary decisions  
at private colleges nationwide, Massachusetts' appeals court ruled 
Thursday that a former Brandeis University student accused of rape 
should be allowed to sue the school for suspending him. 
</P>
<P>
	David Arlen Schaer was a 20-year-old junior when a female  
student accused him of raping her in February 1996 in her dorm 
room. She complained to school officials about a month later, and 
Schaer was brought before a disciplinary board of six students and 
two faculty members. 
</P>
<P>
	He claimed they engaged in consensual sex; she claimed she was  
raped. Schaer was never charged criminally. 
</P>
<P>
	The disciplinary panel found he committed the violations  
charged, and suspended him from campus between May and August of 
that year. The suspension prohibited him from working on a 
biomedical research project at a Brandeis lab that summer. 
</P>
<P>
	When a campus appeal failed, Schaer sued the school and  
administrators for compensatory damages. A judge dismissed the 
case. 
</P>
<P>
	The appellate court, however, ruled Thursday that the case  
should not have been tossed aside. 
</P>
<P>
	The court questioned the validity of the campus disciplinary  
hearing, saying some of the testimony would never have been allowed 
in a court of law. 
</P>
<P>
	As an example, the court cited the testimony of a campus police  
officer who said when she saw the female student one month after 
the encounter: ``She looked like a rape victim.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's not apparent ``on what possible basis a police officer  
could know such a thing,'' the court wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Another witness testified that Schaer was a ``self-motivated  
egotistical bastard who had no respect for women,'' something the 
court said was ``without rudimentary foundation'' and ``unfairly 
prejudicial.'' 
</P>
<P>
	David Lipton, Schaer's attorney, said colleges need to take a  
closer look at the way they discipline students. 
</P>
<P>
	``They should understand the gravity, the really serious impact  
this kind of process has on people, and how it can ruin their 
lives,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Schaer graduated from Brandeis in 1997 and is now pursuing  
graduate work in biology. 
</P>
<P>
	Brandeis officials declined to comment on the case, but  
spokesman Dennis Nealon said the university does not take 
disciplinary cases lightly. ``Officials here go to great lengths to 
let students know from the very first day what is and what is not 
acceptable behavior,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The appeals court decision will affect private colleges  
everywhere, said Harvey Silverglate, a defense attorney and 
co-author of ``The Shadow University: The Betrayal of Liberty on 
America's Campuses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Private colleges have generally gone on the assumption that  
they can do whatever they want,'' Silverglate said. ``Courts look 
at these on a case-by-case basis and usually private colleges get 
away with all kinds of outrageous conduct.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In many instances, Silverglate said, students accused of a crime  
on campus would be better off if they were prosecuted in court. At 
least then, he said, due process would be assured. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 14:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> High Camp, Low Humor in 'Epic' Play </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                     *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Holy Nebuchadnezzar! ``Epic Proportions'' is a  
high-camp, neo-biblical sitcom, a show that would fit nicely on 
Carol Burnett's old TV program as a 15-minute sketch. 
</P>
<P>
	On Broadway, and at an hour and a half, the play falters. This  
happens despite an accomplished crew of comics, including the 
delicious Kristin Chenoweth, and some genuinely funny moments that 
make you wish the evening were better than it actually is. 
</P>
<P>
	``Epic Proportions,'' which opened Thursday at the Helen Hayes  
Theater, feels inflated and overbuilt. Co-authors David Crane and 
Larry Coen pile joke upon joke -- about the Red Sea, camels, Moses, 
Caesar, the plagues of Egypt, etc. -- whether they are funny or not. 
</P>
<P>
	The playwrights have set the comedy in the 1930s during the  
making of a big-budget biblical movie, not unlike the films churned 
out by legendary mogul Cecil B. DeMille. 
</P>
<P>
	Louise Goldman, their peppy heroine (played by Chenoweth), is  
the motion picture's ``atmosphere personnel director,'' in charge 
of the epic's 4,000 extras. Among the teeming thousands are two 
brothers, Benny and Phil. Each falls in love with the lass -- and a 
triangle develops as disasters hamper the making of this 
sword-and-sandal drama. 
</P>
<P>
	Sounds promising. There are even hints of sweetness that should  
have found its way into the show. They never quite surface in this 
relentless production that Jerry Zaks has directed with whip in 
hand. It moves at a furious pace, afraid to stop and let the 
characters and the plot breathe. 
</P>
<P>
	This puts a strain on the actors, but they handle it admirably.  
Chenoweth excels at playing comic determination as anyone knows who 
saw her Tony-winning performance as Sally in last season's revival 
of ``You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown.'' She is in full command 
here. 
</P>
<P>
	Alan Tudyk (the blond) and Jeremy Davidson (the one with the  
brown hair) make an appealing pair of battling brothers. Ruth 
Williamson, a queen of deadpan comedy, delivers in a variety of 
roles, most hilariously as a cigarette-smoking Cleopatra who has 
trouble dealing with that darn asp. And Richard B. Shull, who has a 
great craggy, comic face, gets giggles as the DeMille-like 
director. 
</P>
<P>
	David Gallo has designed a bright, colorful setting, vaguely  
suggesting a desert that owes more to a Hollywood back lot than to 
the Sinai Peninsula. Much of it is filled by a wide staircase 
eerily reminiscent of the set for the disastrous musical version of 
``Carrie.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Epic Proportions'' is too slight an evening for Broadway,  
especially at a $65 top ticket price. As the evening grinds away, 
this ``Epic'' looks smaller and smaller. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
