<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 08:30:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Falcons' Buchanan Having Tough Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SUWANEE, Ga. (AP) -- A silver-studded, black-leather dog collar  
hangs in Ray Buchanan's locker, a reminder of better times for the 
Atlanta Falcons. 
</P>
<P>
	These days, ``Big Play Ray'' keeps winding up on the wrong side  
of his nickname. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFC champions are winless after three games, and Buchanan, a  
Pro Bowler who led the team with seven interceptions in 1998, has 
been burned on three touchdown passes. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the bad stuff comes, some guys fold real quick,'' said  
Buchanan, who also has been penalized twice for pass interference 
and once for illegal contact. ``I've been beaten by some of the 
best. But I have the mentality to go out there and win my share of 
the battles.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just eight months ago, Buchanan was a major attraction during  
Super Bowl week. He adorned himself with the aforementioned dog 
collar, symbolizing the Falcons' underdog status against Denver, 
and engaged in an entertaining war of words with Shannon Sharpe. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, there are two sides to life as an NFL cornerback.  
When you line up one-on-one with a 6-foot-2 receiver who runs the 
40 in just a shade over four seconds, there's a fine line between 
glory and humiliation 
</P>
<P>
	``You're going to get beat. It's how you come back that  
matters,'' Buchanan said. ``I haven't changed. I'm still the same, 
competitive cornerback I've been throughout my career.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, there was a hint of frustration in Buchanan's words, like  
someone who's been left behind on a deserted island while everyone 
else hopped on the rescue boat. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to point fingers at my teammates and say, `Look  
at the pass rush' or `Look at where the safety is supposed to 
be,''' he said. ``But when you see yourself (getting beat) on ESPN 
and CNN, it's difficult.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Falcons have managed only two sacks this season, allowing  
receivers plenty of time to get open. Also, Buchanan clearly feels 
he should have gotten some help in last Sunday's humiliating 35-7 
loss at St. Louis, when the Rams went long on two touchdown passes. 
</P>
<P>
	On third-and-18, Torry Holt got behind Buchanan and hauled in a  
38-yard scoring strike from Kurt Warner. Then Isaac Bruce slipped 
open down the middle and grabbed a 46-yard pass, a futile swipe by 
Buchanan actually arriving a split-second early before he tumbled 
to the turf. 
</P>
<P>
	``It all starts up front,'' said Buchanan, who has broken up  
four passes to lead the team and also has one of the Falcons' two 
interceptions. ``You can have Deion Sanders or Darrell Green at 
cornerback, but it doesn't matter if you don't have a pass rush.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Falcons defensive line, one of the best in the NFL last  
season, has admittedly struggled this year. End Chuck Smith is 
still bothered by a sore toe, suffered early in training camp, 
while tackles Shane Dronett (calf) and Travis Hall (thumb) could 
miss Sunday's game against the Baltimore Ravens with injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's real tough right now,'' Buchanan said. ``You can't take  
any chances. You've got to play passive and try to protect 
yourself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lester Archambeau will likely move from end to tackle to help  
fill in for the injured players, with first-round pick Patrick 
Kerney taking over on the outside. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are really bad right now,'' coach Dan Reeves said. ``We  
aren't putting pressure on the quarterback. I wish I knew why. We 
have just got to keep working at it, because you don't all of a 
sudden become that bad that quick with the same people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan is willing to share the blame on both long touchdowns  
by the Rams -- ``I had a chance to make a play and I didn't'' -- but 
he felt victimized by the officials in the first two games. 
</P>
<P>
	Against Minnesota, he was called for a 52-yard pass interference  
penalty trying to defend Minnesota's Randy Moss, setting up a 
2-yard scoring pass to Cris Carter, who also beat Buchanan. The 
Falcons lost 17-14. 
</P>
<P>
	In Week 2, the Atlanta cornerback was flagged again for  
interference and also for illegal contact in a 24-7 loss to Dallas. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
