<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 15:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Approves Boeing Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- A federal judge on Thursday approved a $15  
million settlement of a racial discrimination lawsuit brought 
against The Boeing Co., saying it was the best way to encourage 
racial cooperation at the company. 
</P>
<P>
	A group of black employees at the world's leading maker of  
commercial airplanes had argued before U.S. District Judge John 
Coughenour last week that the settlement was inadequate. 
</P>
<P>
	``This settlement has a greater chance of fostering a  
cooperative relationship between Boeing and its African-American 
employees than would a series of protracted individual disputes,'' 
Coughenour wrote in his opinion. ``This last point must be a 
crucial consideration for anyone who is primarily interested in 
future race relations within the company, as both the plaintiffs 
and the objectors maintain they are here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement affecting approximately 13,000 past and present  
employees had been announced in January by Boeing's chairman, 
Philip M. Condit, and civil rights leader the Rev. Jesse Jackson. 
</P>
<P>
	It covered lawsuits filed last year on behalf of black Boeing  
workers who alleged discrimination against blacks was common at 
Boeing plants, especially in selecting people for promotion. The 
lawsuits also alleged that blacks were harassed and faced 
retaliation when they complained. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing admitted no wrongdoing but agreed to spend $15 million to  
compensate the workers, pay their legal fees and set up programs to 
fight discrimination. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people weren't happy with terms,'' Oscar Desper III, lead  
attorney for the plaintiffs in the class-action lawsuit, said 
Thursday. ``Some will benefit monetarily and some will not, but all 
will benefit from the changes we're going to make at the company.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some workers complained that the settlement failed to provide  
enough money and wouldn't do enough to prevent further bias. Some 
critics also complained that they had never been allowed to vote on 
the agreement and in some cases said they first learned of the 
settlement from news reports or superiors at Boeing rather than 
from their own lawyers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously we're disappointed. From the record we created and  
the horror stories we heard from our clients -- and their passion, 
their absolute passion -- we did not believe it would be approved,'' 
said Scott Burr, who assisted Philadelphia attorney Alan B. Epstein 
in seeking to overturn the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Burr said his firm was pursuing a class-action discrimination  
suit on behalf of Philadelphia employees of Boeing when Desper's 
Seattle firm reached the settlement with Seattle-based Boeing in 
January. Epstein had asked the judge last week to either reject the 
$15 million settlement as inadequate or rule that those employees 
bringing the Philadelphia suit should not have been included in the 
Seattle settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	Coughenour ruled Thursday that the settlement was fair and that  
it also was appropriate to include the workers in the Philadelphia 
class-action suit. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge wrote that several objectors to the settlement  
``consider the amount of damages awarded to be an insult. And even 
more view Boeing's promises of future reforms with skepticism. The 
Court finds it difficult to reconcile these compelling personal 
statements with the more positive view of the settlement expressed 
by the Reverend Jesse Jackson and other experts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coughenour wrote that it was appropriate to include all Boeing  
workers in part because ``The plaintiffs allege that the root of 
Boeing's race discrimination problems are companywide policies 
which encourage favoritism among groups of white workers, and which 
tend to exclude African-Americans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Burr said it was not clear yet whether her his firm would appeal  
Coughenour's decision or file individual lawsuits on behalf of 
those plaintiffs who had dropped out by the judge's April 23 
deadline rather than remain parties to the suit. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are very pleased with today's court ruling,'' Condit said  
in statement released by Boeing. ``The court's approval today 
allows Boeing to continue its movement forward not only on the 
commitments outlined in the settlement but toward the company's 
vision of a culture of inclusion, where diverse groups and ideas 
flourish.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
