<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Timor Peacekeepers Can Cross Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DILI, East Timor (AP) -- Amid reports of a militia buildup in  
West Timor, Australia said today that peacekeepers in East Timor 
are authorized to cross the border into the Indonesian territory if 
engaged in a battle with militiamen. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia warned peacekeepers against entering West Timor,  
saying such action could lead to a clash between the Australian-led 
mission, known as Interfet, and Indonesian soldiers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Interfet cannot enter West Timor without permission,''  
Indonesian military spokesman Maj. Gen. Sudradjat said, according 
to the Antara news agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia has bristled over what it calls the foreign troops'  
aggressive style and lack of respect for its sovereignty. About 400 
outraged Indonesian students threw rocks and gasoline bombs at the 
Australian Embassy in Jakarta, Indonesia's capital. Three people 
were injured. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want war with Australia. If Australia enters West Timor,  
there will be war,'' protester Yakum Lindo said. 
</P>
<P>
	A smaller protest was held outside the U.S. Embassy as Defense  
Secretary William Cohen visited the capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Militiamen went on a rampage of killing and arson in East Timor  
following an Aug. 30 independence vote, forcing hundreds of 
thousands of East Timorese to flee to West Timor, the other half of 
the island that remains part of Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	Many were reportedly forced into West Timor. Access to refugee  
camps there has been severely limited, with allegations that the 
militias are conducting a campaign of intimidation. 
</P>
<P>
	Australian Defense Minister John Moore told Australian  
Broadcasting Corp. radio that the peacekeepers can cross briefly 
into West Timor if involved in a battle with the militias. So far, 
no such clashes have occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have intelligence information that says that there are  
numbers there,'' Moore said. ``We don't know what their intentions 
are, but we are prepared for any eventualities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A senior U.S. defense official said Wednesday that pro-Indonesia  
militias -- numbering between 2,000 and 4,000 -- may be preparing to 
launch guerrilla raids on the peacekeepers. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen, meeting Indonesian leaders in Jakarta, accused  
Indonesia's military of collusion in militia violence in East Timor 
and said it must change its ways before Washington will restore 
normal ties. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesian military chief Gen. Wiranto denied allegations his  
troops forcibly evicted people from East Timor. ``They 
spontaneously fled from their homes to seek a peaceful place for 
their safety,'' he told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	But some Timorese residents had a different story to tell.  
</P>
<P>
	``The military did it. They forced people out and they forced  
them onto trucks and they took them somewhere,'' said Joao da 
Conceao da Silva, whose sister and brother are among thousands who 
he claims were deported from the southern town of Aielu to West 
Timor. 
</P>
<P>
	``They said, `We will kill anyone who refuses,''' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a leader of East Timor's anti-Indonesia Falintil  
guerrillas ventured into Dili today for the first time in three 
years to discuss cooperation with the international force. 
</P>
<P>
	Cornelio Goma, the guerrillas' second-in-command for the capital  
area, said his 500 fighters would keep their 100 weapons -- ``all 
sorts of weapons, semiautomatics, old guns, new guns.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Falintil will not hand over weapons ... we are the national  
liberation force of East Timor,'' he told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Falintil, which fought a decades-long struggle for East Timor's  
independence, will likely form the core of an independent East 
Timor government and its army. On Wednesday, Falintil rebels manned 
roadblocks and guarding areas of East Timor where international 
peace forces have not reached. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. relief workers said Falintil will be enlisted to help  
distribute aid in the eastern part of the province. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. relief coordinator Ross Mountain said the humanitarian  
situation is gradually improving. The first mass food distribution 
in the capital is scheduled for Saturday at five sites, handing out 
enough to feed 100,000 people for a month, World Food Program 
spokeswoman Annie Spring said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
