<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Immigrants Go on Hunger Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FARMVILLE, Va. (AP) -- About a dozen Immigration and  
Naturalization Service detainees say they are conducting a hunger 
strike to protest the government's ongoing efforts to deport them. 
</P>
<P>
	The protesters have been held for months and, in some cases,  
years because their countries of origin -- Cuba, Cambodia and Iran, 
among them -- refuse to take them back. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the men face deportation for criminal convictions.  
Others told The Washington Post they don't have criminal records. 
</P>
<P>
	The men said they went on the hunger strike earlier this month.  
While they said they are sustaining themselves with only water and 
occasional bites of food, Lewis Barlow, the superintendent at 
Piedmont Regional Jail, said some have been purchasing soup and 
snacks at the jail's commissary. 
</P>
<P>
	Jail officials said they are monitoring the health of detainees  
who have refused meals and only one inmate has required medical 
attention. 
</P>
<P>
	INS spokeswoman Ernestine Fobbs said Wednesday the agency  
reviews deportation cases on a regular basis and has sent two 
officers to Piedmont to hear complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	Following a similar hunger strike in Florida this spring by  
Cuban detainees, the Washington office of the INS said it was 
examining 43 cases of individuals under long-term detention to 
identify those eligible for release pending deportation. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawyers for the men at Piedmont said they have seen no sign of  
such a review. 
</P>
<P>
	``Theoretically, they're supposed to have a procedure, but in  
practice it hasn't happened,'' said Beverly Yeskolski, a lawyer who 
represents one of the detainees. ``These people are sitting in jail 
indefinitely.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fobbs said the INS is monitoring the situation.  
</P>
<P>
	``We are taking this seriously and are working toward a  
reasonable solution of the matter,'' she said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
