<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Farm Bill Nears Passage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- For two lawmakers, it took a pledge of special  
subsidies for dairy farmers. For another, it was a favor sought by 
his home-state cattle ranchers. 
</P>
<P>
	One such promise at a time, Republican congressional leaders  
were on the verge of breaking an impasse on an agricultural 
spending bill that would preserve the 40-year-old Cuban embargo. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP leaders hoped to get a House-Senate conference committee to  
approve an agreement today that would include nearly $9 billion in 
emergency farm assistance while excluding a provision sought by 
farm groups that would allow the sale of food and medicine to Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	House leaders were still negotiating today with three GOP  
members of the committee. ``Nothing is decided yet,'' said one of 
them, Rep. George Nethercutt of Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Two Wisconsin Democrats on the panel announced their support  
late Wednesday after winning a pledge that the measure also would 
include $125 million in special subsidies for dairy farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	In a joint statement, Rep. David Obey and Sen. Herb Kohl, both  
from Wisconsin, predicted that the deal would get approval. 
</P>
<P>
	Obey is the senior Democrat on the House Appropriations  
Committee, while Kohl is the senior Democrat on the Senate's 
agricultural appropriations subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	Another panel member, Sen. Conrad Burns, R-Mont., announced his  
support for the deal because of a provision requiring meatpackers 
to report the prices they pay for livestock. ``That means a lot ... 
I'm happy,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	GOP leaders came under fire from members of their own party for  
refusing to allow the Cuba provision. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be foolhardy if we addressed the emergency, but  
failed to address this structure where farmers are not able to 
market their products around the world,'' said Sen. John Ashcroft, 
R-Mo. 
</P>
<P>
	House leaders didn't want non-spending provisions in the bill,  
said John Feehery, a spokesman for House Speaker Dennis Hastert. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to get this thing done,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Some farm groups, including the huge American Farm Bureau  
Federation, wanted lawmakers to reject the proposed deal because it 
failed to include the dairy and trade provisions and may not have 
enough money to cover farmers' weather-related losses. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Chamber of Commerce also weighed in Wednesday against  
the agreement because of the Cuba issue. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to opening trade with Cuba, the Ashcroft amendment  
would bar the president from stopping sales of agricultural 
products and medical supplies to other countries without 
congressional approval. 
</P>
<P>
	Some lawmakers from dairy states in the South and East wanted to  
use the spending bill to overturn a new nationwide milk-pricing 
system that was scheduled to take effect Friday. A federal judge on 
Tuesday postponed implementation of the plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Kohl and Obey support the new system and fought to keep the  
issue it out of the bill. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
