<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Sept. 30, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Japan Contains Nuclear Reaction  
</P>
<P>
	TOKAIMURA, Japan (AP) -- Hours after a leak of radioactive gas  
seriously injured three workers, an uncontrolled nuclear reaction 
at a uranium processing plant in northeastern Japan was contained 
early Friday. Government officials said Thursday's accident -- which 
may have also contaminated 34 people -- spewed a gas containing 
alpha, beta and gamma radiation into the atmosphere. Earlier, more 
than 310,000 people within six miles of the plant were ordered to 
stay in their homes. The facility is located in Tokaimura, 70 miles 
northeast of Tokyo. 

</P>
<P>
	Congress Struggles With Spending Bills  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Shadowed by presidential veto threats,  
Congress struggled to complete action on spending bills today as 
the government closed the books on the 1999 fiscal year. President 
Clinton denounced a plan to save money by slowing income-support 
payments to millions of working poor families. Minutes earlier, he 
signed legislation keeping agencies open through Oct. 21. Just four 
of the 13 annual spending bills have been signed into law. One has 
been vetoed and five others face veto threats. The fiscal year 
begins tomorrow. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Orders Korean War Deaths Probe  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Defense Secretary William Cohen ordered a  
top-level investigation today of accounts of mass killings of 
Korean civilians by U.S. soldiers at No Gun Ri in 1950. Accounts by 
American veterans and South Korean villagers who said they 
witnessed killings at the No Gun Ri railroad bridge early in the 
Korean War -- including six ex-GIs who said they shot civilians -- 
were reported by The Associated Press yesterday. President Clinton 
gave assurances that the Pentagon ``wants to get to the bottom of 
it,'' and South Korea promised its own investigation. 

</P>
<P>
	Infant, Maternal Death Rates Drop  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Touting what they called one of the century's  
most significant advances in public health, federal officials said 
today that infant and maternal mortality rates have dropped by more 
than 90 percent since 1900. The rate of infants who die before age 
1 went from 100 per 1,000 live births in 1915 to less than 7.2 per 
1,000 in 1997, the CDC said. At the turn of the 20th century, six 
to nine out of every 1,000 women died of pregnancy-related 
complications. The rate was less than .1 per 1,000 in 1997. 

</P>
<P>
	Bradley Upbeat After Financial Reports  
</P>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Democratic presidential hopeful Bill  
Bradley was clearly upbeat today as new campaign finance reports 
showed that he had more money in the bank than Vice President Al 
Gore. Buoyed by the fresh spending figures, Bradley said at a news 
conference, ``I don't think we have momentum, I think we have a 
little traction.'' Bradley raised an estimated $6.7 million between 
July and September, spokeswoman Anita Dunn said. Gore raised around 
$6.5 million during the same period. 

</P>
<P>
	At Least 10 Dead in Mexico Quake  
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A strong earthquake along the Pacific coast  
rattled much of Mexico today, killing at least 10 people and 
damaging hundreds of buildings. The U.S. Geological Survey in 
Golden, Colo., said the magnitude-7.5 quake was centered between in 
Oaxaca state, 280 miles south of Mexico City. The force of the 
quake was felt hundreds of miles away, as far south as Guatemala 
and very strongly in Mexico City to the north. 

</P>
<P>
	Academics, Retailers Honor Bar Code  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Academics from some of the nation's top Ivy  
League schools joined executives from Wal-Mart and other retailers 
today to praise the bar code -- that ubiquitous collection of lines 
and numbers that made its debut 25 years ago. At a daylong 
conference at the Smithsonian Institution, the executives and 
researchers recalled the earliest days of the humble technology. 
Retail and grocery industries describe universal price codes -- 
scanned an estimated 5 billion times each day -- as among the most 
significant advances ever. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Rises 123.47 to 10,336.95  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rallied sharply today for the first time  
in nearly two weeks. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 123.47 
to end at 10,336.95. On the NYSE, gainers led losers 1,907-1,193. 
The Nasdaq rose 16.26 to 2,746.53. 

</P>
<P>
	Giants Close Candlestick With a Loss  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- After 40 years of tormenting players and  
fans with swirling winds, frigid temperatures and blankets of fog, 
Candlestick Park closed its baseball career today as the Los 
Angeles Dodgers beat the San Francisco Giants 9-4. The game was 
attended by 61,389 fans, the largest regular-season crowd in 
Candlestick history. The Giants move to $319 million Pacific Bell 
Park in downtown San Francisco next season, leaving Candlestick -- 
which opened on April 12, 1960 -- to the NFL's 49ers. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
