<DOCNO> APW19990930.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 12:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Athens Chooses Logo for 2004 Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- A white wreath-shaped olive branch  
floating in a sky and sea blue field was presented Thursday as the 
new logo for the Athens 2004 Summer Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The logo was unveiled at a special ceremony at the Zappeion  
Palace, across the street from the all-marble Panatheniac Stadium 
that hosted the first modern Olympics in 1896. 
</P>
<P>
	It replaced a logo that looked like a flaming A, for Athens,  
hovering over a blue shape resembling a boat or cauldron. 
</P>
<P>
	In ancient times, the olive tree was considered sacred in Athens  
and was considered a sign of peace. The symbol was chosen to 
represent peace, democracy and civilization. It also harks back to 
the ancient Olympic truce, when ancient Greek city states declared 
peace during the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	The logo unveiling was attended by Juan Antonio Samaranch,  
president of the International Olympic Committee, Greek President 
Costis Stephanopoulos and Premier Costas Simitis and other 
officials. 
</P>
<P>
	``This emblem will be capture the attention of the world for  
many years,'' Samaranch said. ``Athens and Greece have a greater 
responsibility than others because the history of the Olympics 
belongs to you.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
