<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Underwood Released From Hospital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- Miami Dolphins player Dimitrius Underwood  
was released Thursday from Sparrow Hospital, where he was being 
treated after a suicide attempt. 
</P>
<P>
	A hospital operator who would not give her name said Underwood  
was released but would not say when, or where he went. Lansing 
television station WSYM said he was released at 10:38 a.m. 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	As recently as Thursday morning, Underwood was listed in fair  
condition at the hospital, four days after police found him 
bleeding on a city street from a self-inflicted knife wound. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said the ex-Michigan State defensive standout slashed his  
neck Sunday at the Lansing home of his twin 17-month-old children 
and their mother. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood's college coach, Nick Saban, said he was saddened by  
what his ex-player is going through. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm really disappointed that as his coach, there wasn't  
something that I could do to help this guy accomplish what he wants 
to accomplish,'' Saban said on Detroit television station WJBK. 
</P>
<P>
	A day before trying to kill himself, Underwood was arrested on a  
warrant accusing him of nonpayment of child support. 
</P>
<P>
	Police found him with the knife wound 13 hours after a woman  
posted his bond and Underwood left the jail. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood was a first-round draft pick by the Minnesota Vikings.  
But he left the team in August without explanation a day after 
signing a five-year, $5.3 million contract. 
</P>
<P>
	A reporter later found him in a Philadelphia hotel, and  
Underwood said he had been torn between his faith in God and his 
football career. 
</P>
<P>
	Underwood later decided to return to football to support his  
family, and the Miami Dolphins picked him up on waivers. He played 
one exhibition game on Sept. 2, then injured his shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson said Tuesday that the team was  
placing Underwood on the reserved-nonfootball injury list. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
