<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fannie Mae Relaxing Credit Demands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Mortgage-market giant Fannie Mae, seeking to  
help more low-income consumers become homeowners, is relaxing its 
credit requirements for loans to people with ``slightly impaired'' 
credit. 
</P>
<P>
	Many consumers with damaged credit histories don't qualify for  
lower-cost conventional mortgages. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new program announced Thursday, qualified borrowers  
will be able to get mortgages at interest rates as much as 2 
percentage points below what they would normally pay for so-called 
``subprime'' loans from finance companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Those approved for the mortgages will be granted an additional  
reduction of 1 percentage point in the third year of the loan if 
they make the first 24 monthly payments on time. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, a $100,000 mortgage from a ``subprime'' lender  
would typically come with a 30-year fixed rate of 11.5 percent and 
a monthly payment of $990. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new Fannie Mae program, the mortgage would come with  
an initial rate of 9.5 percent and a monthly payment of $841. After 
24 months without delinquent payments, the rate would be reduced to 
8.5 percent with a monthly payment of $769. 
</P>
<P>
	The program will begin on a pilot basis in 15 states and the  
District of Columbia and is expected to be available nationwide by 
next spring. 
</P>
<P>
	``There remain too many borrowers whose credit is just a notch  
below what our underwriting has required who have been relegated to 
paying significantly higher mortgage rates,'' said Franklin Raines, 
Fannie Mae's chairman and chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	Fannie Mae didn't specify how it defines ``slightly impaired''  
credit, since the definition could vary from one consumer to 
another based on their specific circumstances, company officials 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The officials said the new mortgages will be available to all  
qualified borrowers, although they should mostly help low-income 
and minority consumers, who tend to have worse credit records than 
higher-income and white consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	In a related move, the Fannie Mae Foundation announced an  
educational campaign to provide consumers with information about 
their credit and the role it plays in the home-buying process. 
</P>
<P>
	A survey released in July by Fannie Mae found that only two in  
five Americans understand that if they chronically fail to pay 
bills on time, they will have major problems getting lenders' 
approval for a mortgage. 
</P>
<P>
	For some people, that lack of awareness could stand in the way  
of home ownership even as other obstacles such as racial 
discrimination or the inability to save for a down payment have 
crumbled. 
</P>
<P>
	In January, Fannie Mae and the NAACP formed a partnership to  
provide as much as $110 million in financing for families that 
can't afford big down payments. 
</P>
<P>
	Fannie Mae, a congressionally chartered, publicly traded  
company, is the largest of several U.S. corporations that buy 
mortgages from original lenders such as banks and finance 
companies. Washington-based Fannie Mae retains some of the 
mortgages in its portfolio and packages others into securities for 
resale to investors. 
</P>
<P>
	The program initially will be available in Arizona, California,  
Colorado, District of Columbia, Florida, Georgia, Illinois, 
Indiana, Massachusetts, Minnesota, New York, North Carolina, 
Pennsylvania, South Carolina, Texas and Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Consumers seeking more information on the  
program, called Timely Payment Rewards, can call Fannie Mae's 
Consumer Resource Center at 1-800-7FANNIE from 9:00 a.m. to 5:00 
p.m. EDT Monday through Friday. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
