<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Sept. 30, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Radiation Levels Normal at Japan Plant  
</P>
<P>
	TOKAIMURA, Japan (AP) -- The radiation levels outside a uranium  
processing plant in northeastern Japan had returned to normal 
Friday morning and experts said that they did not believe there was 
a serious threat to local residents. Still, officials described 
Thursday's uncontrolled nuclear reaction as the most serious 
accident ever at a nuclear facility in Japan. A leak of radioactive 
gas seriously injured three workers and possibly contaminated 34 
others. An order for more than 310,000 residents to stay in doors 
remained in effect. 

</P>
<P>
	Party Loyalists Applaud Gore Move  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- From President Clinton on down, Democratic  
Party loyalists today applauded Vice President Al Gore's latest 
campaign shakeup. Gore said he will personally open his new 
Tennessee headquarters next Wednesday. Clinton told reporters at 
the White House that he and the vice president had long talked 
about Gore relocating and loosening up his personal campaign style. 
The president suggested that he had pressed the changes because the 
same strategy worked for his Little Rock, Ark.-based campaign in 
1992. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Urges Korea War Deaths Probe  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton said today that the Pentagon  
``wants to get to the bottom'' of allegations of mass killings of 
Korean civilians by U.S. soldiers at No Gun Ri in 1950. Defense 
Secretary William Cohen ordered a top-level investigation today. 
Accounts by American veterans and South Korean villagers who said 
they witnessed killings at the No Gun Ri railroad bridge early in 
the Korean War -- including six ex-GIs who said they shot civilians 
-- were reported by The Associated Press yesterday. 

</P>
<P>
	House Votes on Violence to Fetuses  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House voted today to make it a crime to  
harm a fetus during a violent act against a pregnant woman. It is a 
key bill this year for opponents of legalized abortion, and the 
administration threatened a veto. The bill, said leading abortion 
foe Rep. Christopher Smith, R-N.J., ``recognizes in law the 
self-evident truth that an assault on a pregnant woman is an attack 
on two victims.'' The legislation, which passed 254-172, makes it a 
separate offense to injure or kill a fetus in the commission of a 
federal crime of violence against a pregnant woman. 

</P>
<P>
	Many Seniors Face High Drug Costs  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Half of elderly Americans who have private  
health insurance covering drugs still spend $500 to $999 a year 
out-of-pocket on prescriptions, according to a new report from the 
AARP. The nation's largest organization for older adults released 
the study today to back up its support for adding drug coverage to 
Medicare, the national health insurance program for the elderly and 
disabled. Although a majority of the elderly has some type of 
insurance covering drugs, the study concluded that is no guarantee 
they will be spared high out-of-pocket costs. 

</P>
<P>
	UN To Investigate E. Timor Violence  
</P>
<P>
	DILI, East Timor (AP) -- U.N. Human Rights chief Mary Robinson  
said Thursday that she was sending officials to East Timor next 
week to prepare for an inquiry into alleged atrocities committed by 
militias in the former Indonesian province. Indonesia has rejected 
the U.N. inquiry. Meanwhile, Indonesia and Australia were embroiled 
in a dispute on whether the peacekeepers had the right to cross 
into Indonesian territory to pursue militias. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Opens Education Summit  
</P>
<P>
	PALISADES, N.Y. (AP) -- President Clinton urged the  
Republican-led Congress today to approve his budget to hire new 
teachers, modernize schools and set standards in failing 
classrooms. Clinton spoke before governors and business executives 
gathered for the National Education Summit, the third in a series 
of high-level meetings going back to 1989. As Congress struggles to 
enact spending bills, education remains a divisive issue. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Fall in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks fell moderately early Friday. The  
Nikkei Stock Average fell 38.79 points to 17,566.67 in early 
trading. In New York Thursday, the Dow Jones industrial average 
rose 123.47 to end at 10,336.95. 

</P>
<P>
	Sosa Homerless As Cubs Lose  
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Mike Lieberthal hit his 31st homer and  
Robert Person held Sammy Sosa homerless tonight as the Philadelphia 
Phillies beat the Chicago Cubs 2-1. Sosa was 0-for-3 with a walk, 
leaving him with 62 homers. He trails Mark McGwire by one homer 
going into a season-ending, three-game series beginning tomorrow in 
St. Louis. Sosa, who has only one homer since Sept. 19, missed his 
first grand slam of the season by a few feet in the third. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
