<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Seminoles Return to Scene of Defeat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Top-ranked Florida State hopes history  
doesn't repeat itself Saturday when the Seminoles meet winless Duke 
in Jacksonville. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida State's last visit to the old Gator Bowl ended in  
defeat. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten years and one month ago, Florida State was upset 30-26 by  
Southern Mississippi and quarterback Brett Favre. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida State coach Bobby Bowden has reminded his players of  
that game over and over. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must guard against overconfidence,'' said Bowden, who well  
remembers each of his team's rare defeats over the past dozen 
seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just look ... Memphis almost beats Tennessee, Louisiana Tech  
beats Alabama and Central Florida almost beats Georgia,'' Bowden 
said. ``You can see that Duke can very well beat Florida State.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But history also would indicate Duke (0-3) is in big trouble  
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	For starters, Duke has never defeated the Seminoles (4-0, 3-0  
Atlantic Coast Conference). For that matter, they've never come 
close. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, in a game played in Orlando, the Seminoles scored 54  
points -- in the first half! 
</P>
<P>
	Since joining the ACC, Florida State has averaged 54 points a  
game in seven previous meetings, winning last year's outing 62-13. 
</P>
<P>
	And the Seminoles appear to be rounding into mid-season form.  
Last week at North Carolina, it took them less than seven minutes 
to score four touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	``The perplexing thing is why we shut it off,'' Bowden said,  
noting liberal substitutions and a dropoff in intensity probably 
accounted for Florida State's offensive slowdown in the game's 
final three periods. 
</P>
<P>
	First-year Duke coach Carl Franks is still trying to get his  
first win while Bowden, only weeks away from his 70th birthday, is 
aiming to pin down his 297th overall and 224th at Florida State. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blue Devils just don't seem to have the horsepower -- or a  
Favre for that matter -- to be much of a threat. They are averaging 
11.7 points and 281 yards a game -- against Vanderbilt, Northwestern 
and East Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	But the day shouldn't be a complete waste for the Devils.  
</P>
<P>
	Duke will collect $800,000 for selling its home date to  
Jacksonville sponsors and Franks, a former assistant to Steve 
Spurrier at Florida, is counting on the exposure to help him 
recruit in the football-rich Sunshine State. 
</P>
<P>
	Franks has already appealed to his 1999 club to do its best in  
what appears to be a massive mismatch. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're the only team in the country that gets to play the  
number one team Saturday,'' he said. ``I think you enjoy, as an 
athlete, playing against the very best.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
