<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Approves Boeing Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- A $15 million settlement of a racial  
discrimination lawsuit against the Boeing Co. is adequate, despite 
the strident objections of a number of employees in the dispute, a 
judge has ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Court has heard a series of powerful arguments ... from  
objectors in this case,'' U.S. District Judge John Coughenour wrote 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Several consider the amount of damages awarded to be an  
insult. And even more view Boeing's promises of future reforms with 
skepticism. The Court finds it difficult to reconcile these 
compelling personal statements with the more positive view of the 
settlement expressed by the Rev. Jesse Jackson and other experts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement affecting approximately 13,000 past and present  
employees had been announced in January by Boeing's chairman, 
Philip M. Condit, and civil rights leader Jackson. 
</P>
<P>
	It covered two class-action lawsuits filed last year on behalf  
of black Boeing workers who alleged that discrimination against 
blacks was common at Boeing plants, especially in selecting people 
for promotion. The lawsuits also alleged that blacks were harassed 
and faced retaliation when they complained. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing admitted no wrongdoing but agreed to spend $15 million to  
compensate the workers and set up programs to fight discrimination. 
</P>
<P>
	A group of black employees at the world's leading maker of  
commercial airplanes had argued before Coughenour last week that 
the settlement was inadequate. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people weren't happy with terms,'' Oscar Desper III, lead  
attorney for some plaintiffs, said Thursday. ``Some will benefit 
monetarily and some will not, but all will benefit from the changes 
we're going to make at the company.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some workers complained that the settlement failed to provide  
enough money and wouldn't do enough to prevent further bias. Some 
critics also complained that they had never been allowed to vote on 
the agreement and in some cases said they first learned of the 
settlement from news reports or superiors at Boeing rather than 
from their own lawyers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously we're disappointed. From the record we created and  
the horror stories we heard from our clients -- and their passion, 
their absolute passion -- we did not believe it would be approved,'' 
said Scott Burr, who assisted Philadelphia lawyer Alan B. Epstein 
in seeking to block the settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	Burr said his firm was pursuing a class-action discrimination  
lawsuit on behalf of Philadelphia employees of Boeing when Desper's 
Seattle firm reached the settlement with Seattle-based Boeing in 
January. Epstein had asked the judge last week to either reject the 
$15 million settlement as inadequate or rule that those employees 
bringing the Philadelphia suit should not have been included in the 
Seattle settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	Coughenour ruled Thursday that the settlement was fair and that  
it also was appropriate to include the workers in the Philadelphia 
class-action suit. 
</P>
<P>
	It was fair to include all Boeing workers in part because ``The  
plaintiffs allege that the root of Boeing's race discrimination 
problems are companywide policies which encourage favoritism among 
groups of white workers, and which tend to exclude 
African-Americans,'' Coughenour wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Epstein said Thursday it was not yet clear whether his firm  
would appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing was pleased with the ruling, Condit said in a statement.  
</P>
<P>
	``The court's approval today allows Boeing to continue its  
movement forward not only on the commitments outlined in the 
settlement but toward the company's vision of a culture of 
inclusion, where diverse groups and ideas flourish,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the $15 million, more than $3.25 million will be paid to 70  
named plaintiffs and 194 other class members whose claims surfaced 
during litigation, Boeing said. Another $3.4 million will be 
distributed among some 3,400 members of the settlement class who 
filed claims. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement reserves $3.64 million for improvements,  
including revising Boeing's selection process for managers, 
improving the promotions process for hourly employees and putting 
in place a new system to investigate equal-opportunity complaints 
from employees, Boeing said. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
