<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Hopes To Reclaim Home Turf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- Republican presidential candidate John  
McCain returned to Arizona on Thursday with plans to reclaim the 
home turf advantage from George W. Bush, the GOP front-runner who 
was endorsed by that state's governor. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's wonderful to be home,'' McCain told about 450 supporters  
gathered at the Hayden Square Amphitheater. ``Let me tell you my 
friends, I have no doubt and you have no doubt, we will win the 
state of Arizona. We will win easily.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The trip home ended a four-day announcement tour by the U.S.  
senator. 
</P>
<P>
	During stops in Annapolis, Md., where he graduated from the  
Naval Academy, and the early primary states of New Hampshire, South 
Carolina, Michigan, Washington and California, McCain stressed his 
campaign's core issues -- decreasing the influence of money in 
politics, strengthening the military and restoring pride in public 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must stop the corruption in Washington, D.C.,'' he said.  
``I am committed to it and until I draw my last breath, I will 
fight for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCain also hoped the rally, held across the street from his  
first congressional office in Tempe, would showcase his support in 
Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, the governor of Texas, made his first campaign visit to  
the state Tuesday and left with endorsements from Gov. Jane Hull 
and former Rep. John Rhodes. 
</P>
<P>
	One political analyst said Hull's decision was bad, but not  
fatal, for McCain. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a blow, but it's not a knock-out blow,'' said Jeanne  
Clarke, political science professor at the University of Arizona in 
Tucson. ``Being the maverick that he is, his strength is with the 
regular people.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
