<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 15:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mazda To Pay $5.25 Million Fine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Mazda will pay $5.25 million to settle charges  
it violated government agreements requiring that the automaker 
clearly disclose important car leasing terms in its advertising, 
federal regulators said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The civil penalties include a $4.05 million fine, the largest  
obtained by the Federal Trade Commission's bureau of consumer 
protection, for what the FTC said was a failure to abide by a 
February 1997 agency order about Mazda's advertising. 
</P>
<P>
	Mazda also agreed to pay a total of $1.2 million in fines and  
costs to 24 states. 
</P>
<P>
	The complaint and consent decree were filed Thursday in U.S.  
District Court in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, Mazda Motor of America Inc. agreed Thursday to pay a  
$900,000 penalty and to modify its reporting of emission control 
defects in order to settle allegations it violated the Clean Air 
Act, the Justice Department said. 
</P>
<P>
	The department and the Environmental Protection Agency filed the  
settlement in U.S. District Court here to resolve civil claims that 
Mazda failed to promptly report defective emission control devices 
in its MPV minivans. 
</P>
<P>
	Mazda, based in Irvine, Calif., said it has sought to comply  
with lease disclosure requirements and has put into practice new 
procedures to ensure full compliance. 
</P>
<P>
	The earlier FTC order prohibited Mazda's television ads from  
misrepresenting the total due at lease inception and from 
highlighting only the most attractive terms of the lease -- such as 
low monthly payments. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement also required Mazda to make a number of  
disclosures before it could state the amount of any payment. They 
included a clear and conspicuous disclosure that the transaction 
advertised is a lease, the total amount due at lease inception and 
whether a security deposit is required. 
</P>
<P>
	The FTC said Mazda continued to run ads in violation of the  
order until early 1998. For example, the disclosures were in small 
and unreadable print, offset by distracting images or sounds, or 
appeared on the screen for too short a time, the agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This substantial penalty should not only deter future  
violations of the commission's order by Mazda, but send a strong 
signal to everyone in the automobile industry -- manufacturers, 
dealers and advertising agencies -- that important leasing 
information cannot be buried in fine print,'' said Jodie Bernstein, 
director of the bureau of consumer protection. 
</P>
<P>
	Mazda said in a statement that consumers who leased cars between  
February 1997 and early 1998 were informed of the complete terms 
and conditions before signing any deal. 
</P>
<P>
	As part of the settlement, the Mazda will distribute a consumer  
education brochure on vehicle leasing through its 750 U.S. dealers. 
</P>
<P>
	Mazda Motor of America Inc., doing business as Mazda North  
American Operations, is a subsidiary of Mazda Motor Corp. of 
Hiroshima, Japan. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 23:40:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Variety of Winners on NASCAR Tracks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MARTINSVILLE, Va. (AP) -- Elliott Sadler would like to see the  
recent run of first-time winners continue Sunday at Martinsville 
Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	That would give the Winston Cup rookie at least a shot at his  
first checkered flag in NASCAR's top series. 
</P>
<P>
	``The team's probably good enough to do it, but probably not me  
yet,'' said Sadler, who drives for the Wood Brothers, whose race 
shop is just a few miles up the road in Stuart, Va. ``I'm going to 
try to force the issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Considering that the last 11 short track races in Winston Cup  
have produced 11 different winners, it appears that anything is 
possible going into the NAPA AutoCare 500, the last of eight events 
this season on tracks shorter than one mile. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just want to make the show and run 500 laps on Sunday.  
That's our goal,'' said Sadler, whose season had been overshadowed 
by fellow rookie Tony Stewart, who picked up a win last month in 
Richmond, Va., and is fourth in the points. 
</P>
<P>
	Sadler is 24th in the standings and has managed only one top-10  
finish so far. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we can finish in the lead lap, we're going to be happy,''  
Sadler said. ``But, anything can happen at this place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The list of short track winners since the 1998 spring race in  
Bristol, Tenn., includes Ricky Rudd, the defending winner in the 
fall race in Martinsville, as well as Jeff Gordon, Bobby Hamilton, 
Terry Labonte, Mark Martin, Jeff Burton, Rusty Wallace, John 
Andretti, Dale Jarrett, Dale Earnhardt and rookie Tony Stewart. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that it's just that the competition is that good  
now,'' said Jarrett, who went into today's opening of practice and 
qualifying holding a 257-point lead over Martin in the season 
standings. 
</P>
<P>
	The second-generation NASCAR star says there are so many drivers  
so close in competition these days that when ``somebody hits on 
something for a particular race and gets good track position at the 
end of the race'' he can get an advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	Jarrett says that isn't true just on the short tracks, either.  
He points out there have been 11 different winners in the first 27 
races this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``You talk about parity in other sports,'' he said. ``I think we  
have that much here that when you get on short tracks where 
handling is the total key, that you don't have too many other 
things. (Aerodynamics) don't matter that much. The engine 
combination or having a lot of horsepower doesn't come into play 
that much, so you bring more people into the mix.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rudd, who hasn't won since taking the race here last year, needs  
to win in the final seven events of this season to extend his 
string of 16 straight years with at least one victory. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-time winner on Martinsville's .533-mile oval runs his  
own team and says that having a one-car operation is a handicap at 
most tracks in this day of rich, multi-car teams. But not at the 
short ovals. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of these teams are putting millions of dollars a year in  
an aerodynamic program, and those millions spent make a big 
difference at tracks like Dover or a Charlotte or an Atlanta or 
Michigan,'' Rudd said. ``But that does absolutely no good for a 
Martinsville or a Bristol. At those type of tracks, that money is 
not money wisely spent because you can just about rule out 
aerodynamics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Martin has what he thinks is a simple explanation for the  
procession of winners here. 
</P>
<P>
	``Martinsville is really, really, really tough. When you put 43  
cars on that track, that's about 10 cars more than what you'd 
really like to see out there.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 14:20:17 </DATE_TIME>
