<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marriott To Buy Back 10.6M Shares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BETHESDA, Md. (AP) -- Marriott International Inc. on Thursday  
announced it was buying back 10.6 million shares worth more than 
$320 million and reported third-quarter earnings up 12 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The hotel and real estate firm credited cost control for the  
increased earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	In a press release, the company said it has bought back 5.6  
million shares this year and will buy 10.6 million more shares from 
time to time in the open market. 
</P>
<P>
	Marriott had about 246 million shares outstanding as of Sept.  
10. Shares opened Thursday at $32.12 1/2 on the New York Stock 
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The hotel and lodging real estate company reported net income of  
$96 million for the quarter ending Sept. 10, compared to $86 
million in the same period a year ago. Per share earnings were 36 
cents, compared to 32 cents in the corresponding quarter a year 
ago, the company said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales were $2 billion, up 11 percent from $1.8 billion in same  
period last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Chairman and CEO J.W. Marriott Jr. said the company's flagship  
brand -- Marriott Hotels, Resorts and Suites -- achieved higher 
profit margins through tight cost controls. 
</P>
<P>
	Ritz-Carlton, the company's luxury brand hotel, had a strong  
summer, he said. Occupancy at the 35 Ritz-Carlton hotels was 79.7 
percent, up 5.9 percentage points from the same quarter a year ago. 
The chain's 11,600 rooms rented for an average of $196.79. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
