<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Floyd Victims Get Tax Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Taxpayers along the East Coast affected by  
Hurricane Floyd will have more time to file returns or make 
payments, the Internal Revenue Service announced Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In all counties declared disaster or emergency areas, taxpayers  
will now have until Oct. 15 to file returns or make payments if 
they were due on or after Sept. 14. In addition, penalties for late 
employment or excise tax deposits will be waived if those deposits 
are made by Oct. 15. 
</P>
<P>
	In six hard-hit states -- Delaware, Maryland, New Jersey, North  
Carolina, Pennsylvania and Virginia -- the new deadline is even 
later, on Jan. 31, 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRS previously suspended audits, seizures and levies in  
places affected by the storm and provided help for taxpayers who 
want to claim uninsured losses on either 1998 amended returns or on 
their 1999 returns. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0278 </DOCNO>
