<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Expanding Economy Benefits Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The percentage of children living in poverty  
sank to a near 20-year low and the overall poverty rate in the 
South was at a record low as American household incomes rose in 
1998 for the fourth straight year. 
</P>
<P>
	The median income -- meaning half of households earned more and  
half less -- rose by about $1,300 last year to $38,900, the Census 
Bureau said Thursday in its annual income and poverty report. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's a 3.5 percent increase in a year, tied for the largest  
since 1978, allowing American families more money for things that 
matter -- sending their children to college, buying a home, 
purchasing a car, saving for retirement,'' President Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The jump finally pushed household income above where it was in  
1989, the year before the nation slid into its most recent 
recession. 
</P>
<P>
	The current economic upswing, which began in 1991, took until  
1997 to raise incomes back to 1989 levels. Last year -- the eighth 
year of what has become the nation's longest peacetime economic 
expansion -- incomes finally surpassed 1989, by 2.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	More than a million fewer Americans had incomes below the  
federal poverty level in 1998 -- 34.5 million compared with 35.6 
million in 1997. That pulled the poverty rate down from 13.3 
percent to 12.7 percent -- about the same, statistically speaking, 
as the 13.1 percent rate of pre-recession 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, the poverty level was $16,700 for a family of four and  
$8,300 for an individual. 
</P>
<P>
	More than half of the Americans climbing out of poverty in 1998  
-- nearly 650,000 -- were children under 18 years old. 
</P>
<P>
	The poverty rate among children sunk to 18.9 percent last year  
from 19.9 percent in 1997, the first time it has been below 20 
percent by a statistically significant margin since 1980. However, 
children still have the highest poverty rate of any age group. 
</P>
<P>
	``It certainly is very good that child poverty is down, but  
there remain 13.5 million children living in poverty in this 
country,'' said Deborah Weinstein, director of the Children's 
Defense Fund's family income division. 
</P>
<P>
	Weinstein said 3 million of those poor children live in  
households headed by an adult that works full time, according to 
calculations based on the new Census figures. 
</P>
<P>
	``Families are struggling with low wages and the message is if  
we want families who are doing their part to work -- if we want them 
to get out of poverty -- we have to do our part. That means help 
with child care, transportation, food stamps,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	By region, the South -- historically the poorest part of the  
country -- is now leading the nation's decline in poverty. In 1998, 
the poverty rate in the South fell to a record low of 13.7 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Southerners, even more those living in other regions, are seeing  
a shift to industries requiring more skilled workers and increased 
emphasis on training to fill those higher paying jobs, said Steven 
Cochrane, an economist with Regional Financial Associates in West 
Chester, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
	``You see it from the high tech industries in Raleigh-Durham, to  
banking in Charlotte, to the auto industry moving into Alabama,'' 
said Cochrane. 
</P>
<P>
	Poverty rates in the West have almost matched the South since  
1994, holding at 14 percent in 1998. There also was little change 
in poverty rates in the Northeast and Midwest last year -- 12.3 
percent and 10.3 percent, respectively. 
</P>
<P>
	Nationally, the poverty rate among Hispanic Americans in 1998  
fell to 25.6 percent from 27.1 percent; for whites, it declined to 
8.2 percent from 8.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The poverty rate for blacks stayed about the same, holding at a  
record low of 26.1 percent reached last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Census Bureau said the gap between the wealthiest and  
poorest Americans remained essentially the same between 1997 and 
1998, as it has since 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	The difference between men's and women's earnings did not change  
much either, with women earning 73 cents for every dollar earned by 
men, compared with 74 cents in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Median income rose in all four regions of the country, with the  
biggest increase in the Midwest: 4.4 percent to $40,600. Incomes in 
the West increased 3 percent to $41,000; by 2.8 percent to $40,600 
in the Northeast and by 2.6 percent to $35,800 in the South. 
</P>
<P>
	Sixteen states showed significant increases in median income  
when two-year averages, for 1996-97 and 1997-98, were compared: 
Alabama, Arizona, Colorado, Florida, Georgia, Indiana, Minnesota, 
Missouri, New Mexico, Ohio, Oklahoma, Pennsylvania, Utah, Vermont, 
Washington and Wyoming. 
</P>
<P>
	By the same measure, the median income decreased only in Alaska,  
although incomes in that state remain among the highest in the 
country, at close to $50,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The poverty rate dropped significantly in two states, New Mexico  
and Virginia, while one state, North Dakota, showed an increase. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
