<HEADLINE> Nieman Foundation Curator Leaving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- Bill Kovach, curator of the Nieman  
Foundation at Harvard University since 1989, will step down from 
the post in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Kovach, 67, cited ``personal and practical'' reasons in a letter  
sent to the foundation's advisory board this week, including a wish 
to spend more time with his family. He also said he wanted to step 
aside for a curator with broader knowledge of communications 
technology. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have struggled to keep abreast of this change and what it  
means to the fellows who come to the Nieman experience,'' Kovach 
said. ``But I grow distant from direct experience. The university 
and future fellows are, as we say these days, ready for an 
upgrade.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kovach said his plans include writing books, including a memoir.  
</P>
<P>
	Working journalists in the United States and abroad are selected  
for Nieman fellowships for an academic year of study at Harvard. 
The fellowships were established in 1938 through a bequest of Agnes 
Wahl Nieman in memory of her husband, Lucius, founder and publisher 
of The Milwaukee Journal. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-four journalists are participating this year.  
</P>
<P>
	Kovach came to Harvard as a Nieman fellow himself in 1988 after  
resigning as editor of the Atlanta Journal and Constitution. 
</P>
<P>
	He was named curator in August 1989.  
</P>
<P>
	``Bill Kovach has been the very model of a curator for the  
Nieman Foundation,'' Harvard President Neil L. Rudenstine said. 
``He commands instant respect in this country and abroad and has 
constantly enhanced the quality and the reach of the Nieman Fellows 
program.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before he became editor in Atlanta in 1986, he was a reporter at  
the Johnson City (Tenn.) Press-Chronicle and The Tennessean in 
Nashville and a reporter, editor and Washington bureau chief of The 
New York Times. 
</P>
<P>
	Rudenstine will select a successor.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
