<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Status of 13 Spending Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Status of the 13 spending bills for fiscal 2000, which began  
Friday: 
</P>
<P>
	--Agriculture: $70 billion. House-Senate leaders agreed to  
package that includes $8.7 billion in emergency aid for farmers 
hurt by low market prices and bad weather. Omits provisions lifting 
some trade sanctions with Cuba and blocking new federal milk 
pricing rules. 
</P>
<P>
	--Commerce, Justice, State: $38 billion. House-Senate negotiators  
seeking compromise. Faces a veto threat because it would cut 
President Clinton's proposals for hiring new police officers, civil 
rights enforcement, other programs. 
</P>
<P>
	--Defense: Nearly $270 billion. House-Senate bargainers near  
agreement on letting Air Force buy up to six test versions of the 
F-22 stealth fighter, but not begin production of final, 
combat-ready aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	--District of Columbia: $429 million in federal funds. Clinton  
vetoed Tuesday because of ban on allowing medical use of marijuana, 
providing hypodermic needles for drug addicts, other restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	--Energy and Water: $21 billion. Signed into law Thursday.  
Removal of language helping developers trying to build on wetlands 
ended earlier veto threat. 
</P>
<P>
	--Foreign aid: $13 billion. House-Senate bargainers agreed to  
compromise Monday night. Clinton threatened veto because it cuts 
his request by $2 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	--Interior: $14 billion. House-Senate bargainers haven't  
completed compromise. Veto threat because of cuts in Clinton 
proposals for land purchases, plus provisions helping oil and 
mining companies using federal lands. 
</P>
<P>
	--Labor, health, education: About $320 billion. Approved by House  
and Senate Appropriations committees. Veto threat because of cuts 
in Clinton plans for hiring teachers, workplace safety, other 
programs. House version would slow income-support payments to 
working poor. 
</P>
<P>
	--Legislative branch: $2.5 billion. Clinton signed Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	--Military construction: $8.4 billion. Clinton signed Aug. 17.  
</P>
<P>
	--Transportation: $51 billion. House-Senate agreement reached  
boosting spending for highways, mass transit and aviation; blocking 
higher fuel efficiency standards for cars; and forbidding states 
from selling information about drivers, though there would be no 
penalty. 
</P>
<P>
	--Treasury: $28 billion. Clinton signed Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	--Veterans, housing, environment: $97 billion. House-Senate  
bargainers seeking agreement. Veto threat because of cuts in 
Clinton proposals for public housing, environment, NASA. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
