<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trump Criticizes Political Parties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Donald Trump says he is considering a run for  
the White House not out of vanity but because ``I am convinced the 
major parties have lost their way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In an opinion column published in Thursday's editions of The  
Wall Street Journal, Trump cited two reasons for a possible 
presidential candidacy, mostly likely as a Reform Party candidate. 
</P>
<P>
	``First,'' he said, ``Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura has strongly  
encouraged me to seek the nomination, and I highly respect Jesse as 
the embodiment of the political qualities America needs and voters 
reward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reason No. 2 was Pat Buchanan, who is considering bolting the  
Republican presidential race to seek the Reform Party nomination. 
``He has the virtue of plain speaking, but he often says stupid 
things,'' Trump said. 
</P>
<P>
	He took issue with the current crop of presidential candidates  
for being slow to react to Buchanan's controversial comments about 
World War II. ``They are so concerned with winning votes that they 
cannot even find it in themselves to immediately denounce a man who 
winks at barbarism,'' Trump said. 
</P>
<P>
	Trump was not available Thursday for interviews, said his  
spokeswoman, Norma Foerderer. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Republicans are captives of their right wing. The  
Democrats are captives of their left wing,'' he wrote in the 
newspaper. ``I don't hear anyone speaking for the working men and 
women in the center.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he would run the country like a business based upon  
three principles: one term, two-fisted policies, and no excuses. 
</P>
<P>
	Touting his years of business experience, he said he has the  
acumen needed to handle the economic downturn some experts are 
predicting for the near future. 
</P>
<P>
	He also made assurances the government would not invest Social  
Security retirement funds in the stock market, calling the notion 
the ``craziest idea'' in American politics since the five 
presidential bids by the late comedian, Pat Paulsen. 
</P>
<P>
	Trump said he would cut better trade deals with foreign partners  
and rid the United States of its ``habit of mistaking the easy 
availability of cheap, sweatshop-produced products for solid and 
sustainable economic stability.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If President Trump does the negotiating, we'll get a better  
deal for American workers and their families, and our economy will 
not be as vulnerable to global pressures as it is today. Watch our 
trade deficit dwindle,'' he promised. 
</P>
<P>
	And don't expect Trump to play Mr. Nice Guy to foreign  
adversaries. North Korea would learn ``its worthless promises of 
civilized behavior would cut no ice.'' And Cuba would see a 
reversal in its recent improved relations with the U.S. 
</P>
<P>
	``Normalization is pure lunacy,'' Trump said, particularly with  
``the most abnormal political figure in our hemisphere: Fidel 
Castro.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trump said he will run only if he becomes convinced that he can  
win, ``a decision I will make later this year.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
