<HEADLINE> Japan's Jobless Rate Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's jobless rate improved in August, falling to  
4.7 percent from the previous month's record high 4.9 percent, the 
government announced Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The rate fell largely on a shift of unemployed men into the  
jobholders' bracket, the Management and Coordination Agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	The jobless rate for men stood at 4.7 percent in August, down  
from July's record 5.1 percent. The rate for women was unchanged at 
4.6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	While the total number of jobholders fell by 350,000 to 65.11  
million in August from the year-earlier month, that figure rose 
from July's 64.97 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The unemployment rate had worsened in recent months, increasing  
pessimism about the nation's economy, which is struggling to emerge 
from its worst downturn in 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists surveyed by Dow Jones Newswires in Tokyo had forecast  
the overall jobless rate would stay at 4.9 percent in August. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
