<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bucs' Sapp Wins Defensive Honors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Tampa Bay's Warren Sapp was honored Thursday  
as the NFC defensive player of the month for September. 
</P>
<P>
	The fifth-year pro, who anchors the NFL's top-ranked defense,  
had 16 tackles in three games and shares the league lead in sacks 
with four. 
</P>
<P>
	``It says that this defense is playing great, and they picked  
the loud mouth out of the group,'' said Sapp, who broke two bones 
in his left hand last week and is listed as questionable for 
Sunday's game against the Minnesota Vikings. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll take it. It's just a tribute to all the work that we do  
out here every day, and my teammates around me. I always give them 
credit because without them, I'm just one person out there trying 
to do a job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sapp tied a team record with three sacks in Tampa Bay's 14-point  
victory over Philadelphia in Week 2 and is one of the reasons the 
Bucs have limited opponents to 143.3 yards per game. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Tony Dungy has held the two-time Pro Bowl selection out of  
contact work in practice this week, but is hopeful that Sapp will 
be able to play at Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	The lineman's hand and wrist remain in a hard cast that would be  
replaced by a softer version for the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to see if I can dupe them into cutting it off  
(Friday) at the X-ray,'' Sapp said. ``But I don't think I can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dungy said a decision on whether Sapp plays may not be made  
until Sunday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to say, but my thought is he'll play,'' the coach  
said, adding that the defensive tackle's performance in helping the 
Bucs to a 2-1 start has been worthy of the recognition Sapp 
received. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's had a good month. He got off to a good start. He's played  
three very good games for us,'' Dungy said. ``We kind of expect 
those kinds of performances, but I think the accolades are 
well-deserved.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
