<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Abbott, Feds Disagree on Test Kits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Abbott Laboratories and the federal government  
are locked in a dispute over how the pharmaceutical company 
manufactures its medical test kits. 
</P>
<P>
	The kits are placed into hospital and laboratory diagnostic  
machines and used to measure patient drug and disease levels. 
</P>
<P>
	If North Chicago-based Abbott doesn't change its practices, the  
Food and Drug Administration could order the company to halt 
production of the kits. 
</P>
<P>
	``If those discussions are not successful, the government has  
advised the company it will file a complaint for injunctive relief 
which would include cessation of manufacturing and sale for a 
period of time of a number of diagnostic products,'' says a 
statement issued by the company.''The company would resist that 
lawsuit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The FDA has refused to comment about its investigation of  
Abbott. But letters on the agency's Web site say quality controls 
involving kits used for several Abbott diagnostic machines are 
suspect. The agency noted the company failed to send a letter to 
customers about a machine's software defect, which had been causing 
incorrect test results to be reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The kits under suspicion are manufactured at Abbott's North  
Chicago plant. The FDA has not expressed concern about diagnostic 
operations at other Abbott plants. 
</P>
<P>
	The company is still able to make and ship the kits. But Abbott  
contends the dispute could delay production at the plant. 
</P>
<P>
	If the FDA orders a production halt, it would not be the first  
time it has taken such action against the company. Abbott last year 
was forced to suspend shipments of its clot-busting drug Abbokinase 
as the result of an FDA investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Abbott is working to meet federal standards for Abbokinase  
production before the product, which had earned the company $250 
million a year, can be shipped again. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
