<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yankees Extend Disabled Fans Access </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Disabled baseball fans will receive fair access  
to Yankee Stadium for postseason games under an interim agreement 
reached between the federal government, the New York Yankees and 
city officials, U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal requires the Yankees to substantially change ticketing  
and pricing policies, as they had during the regular season. 
</P>
<P>
	The government had joined a private lawsuit that alleged the  
Yankees and the city discriminated against the disabled by failing 
to make the Bronx stadium accessible to those who need special 
accommodations. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the club had offered six price levels for the general  
public for regular-season games, including $8 seats, it had 
required those who needed wheelchair seats to pay $26 or $50. The 
$50 seats were the only unobstructed views. 
</P>
<P>
	With the changes, the unobstructed view seats in the postseason  
will be reduced 68 percent for the division series, from $125 to 
$40, 65 percent for the American League championship series, from 
$200 to $70, and 50 percent for the World Series from, $300 to 
$150. 
</P>
<P>
	The remaining wheelchair seats and an accompanying seat for a  
guest will be priced at the lowest price levels in the stadium, $12 
for the division series, $30 for the AL championship series and $40 
for the World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, those buying wheelchair seats will be able to purchase  
tickets for the postseason through Ticketmaster or through a 
designated operator by calling (718) 537-4432 from noon to 5 p.m. 
on Saturday or between 9 a.m. and 5 p.m. on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	A trial in the case has been set for Dec. 6.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
