<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NY Philharmonic Dir. Moving to LA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Deborah Borda, one of the two women managing a  
major U.S. orchestra, is leaving after nine years as executive 
director of the New York Philharmonic to take a top job at the Los 
Angeles Philharmonic. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Borda, 50, will become executive vice president and managing  
director of the Los Angeles orchestra. She replaces Willem 
Wijnbergen, who was abruptly relieved of his duties in July. 
</P>
<P>
	Her new duties include overseeing management of the Hollywood  
Bowl and construction of the new Disney Hall designed by Frank O. 
Gehry. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's sort of like running the New York Philharmonic, Carnegie  
Hall and Tanglewood,'' Ms. Borda said Wednesday in an interview 
with The New York Times after informing the New York Philarmonic 
board of directors of her decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel like I have another great burst of energy coming here,  
and this is where I want to put it,'' Ms. Borda said in today's Los 
Angeles Times. 
</P>
<P>
	She is being paid about $400,000 per year in New York, but  
declined to discuss her new salary. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Borda reconfigured the New York Philharmonic's  
administration and finances, stepping up fund raising, while music 
director Kurt Masur introduced audience-building strategies. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Borda, a native of New York, is a violist and trained at  
London's Royal College of Music and Boston's New England 
Conservatory of Music. 
</P>
<P>
	The other female leader of a major orchestra is Deborah Card of  
the Seattle Symphony. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
