<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tenn. AD Takes Findings To SEC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) -- Tennessee athletic director Doug  
Dickey on Thursday hand-delivered to the Southeastern Conference 
the school's preliminary findings in an alleged academic fraud 
case. 
</P>
<P>
	Four players have been suspended as a result of the internal  
investigation, and Dickey has said that he would like to establish 
the eligibility of the players before Saturday's game against 
Auburn. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee president J. Wade Gilley told the Chattanooga  
Times-Chattanooga Free-Press on Thursday that he hadn't read the 
preliminary report which Dickey took to Birmingham, Ala., to 
present to SEC commissioner Roy Kramer, but said there are 
``basically two issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``One is with the individual players. Did they break the  
rules?'' Gilley said. ``And the other is with institutional 
control. An institution can't depend on the head of the tutoring 
department'' to watch the program. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee was investigating allegations that athletic department  
tutors did schoolwork for athletes, a possible violation of school 
honor codes and NCAA rules. 
</P>
<P>
	ESPN reported earlier this week that internal memos show  
high-level administrators in Tennessee's athletic department were 
told four tutors might have done schoolwork for at least five 
unidentified football players, a baseball player and a female 
athlete. Three of the football players have transferred. 
</P>
<P>
	None of this information was passed on to campus authorities  
charged with investigating possible rules infractions, university 
officials say. 
</P>
<P>
	If that was the case, punishment could be forthcoming.  
</P>
<P>
	``Now you would involve institutional control and if that is  
found, then you'd be talking about major violations,'' said Jim 
McCullough, the SEC's associate commissioner for eligibility, 
financial aid and NCAA rules interpretations. 
</P>
<P>
	McCullough said how quickly Tennessee gets a response depends on  
what's in the report. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the investigation shows, and we agree, that there's no  
violation, then we wouldn't send the report on (to the NCAA),'' he 
said. ``If we find, in our best estimation, that there is a 
violation, we would support an athletic department's investigation 
and forward it to the NCAA.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
