<DOCNO> APW19990930.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 13:40:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> ABC Tackles Falling NHL Ratings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	It's no secret the NHL has struggled to lure TV viewers. After  
Fox tried for five seasons, now it's ABC's turn, and their strategy 
is cross-promotion. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC, along with fellow Disney-owned ESPN, will try to halt  
plummeting NHL ratings that have dropped 33 percent since 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are an awful lot of markets where they don't seem to  
care about hockey,'' said ABC Sports president Howard Katz. ``And 
we've got to change that. There are plenty of places on the network 
to promote the sport.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Katz has vowed to develop player personalities, have players  
make cameo appearances on ABC prime-time shows, and promote the 
sport on both ABC and ESPN. 
</P>
<P>
	For Fox, it's a case of ``Been there. Done that.''  
</P>
<P>
	They did profile vignettes for the first two seasons, had NHL  
stars on shows such as ``Beverly Hills 90210'' and promoted their 
national coverage on local NHL games shown on Fox Sports Net. 
</P>
<P>
	``We tried all that and our promotional campaigns even won  
international awards,'' said Fox executive producer Ed Goren. 
``Hockey got more exposure in the last five years than it got in 
the 20 years before. It's just not that simple to say more 
promotion will raise the ratings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although Disney shelled out $600 million for the next five  
seasons, ABC will only show four regional telecasts in the regular 
season, along with the All-Star game and numerous playoff contests. 
</P>
<P>
	The season begins on ESPN Friday at 7:30 p.m. EDT with a tribute  
and jersey retirement for Wayne Gretzky in Edmonton. The cable 
network will switch to the banner-raising ceremony in Dallas, 
followed by the Stars-Penguins game. 
</P>
<P>
	``We knew when we made the deal, ABC had contractual  
commitments, but we know over the years that they'll do more,'' NHL 
commissioner Gary Bettman said of ABC's lack of games. 
</P>
<P>
	While both the NHL and ABC expect Disney to make a profit on the  
big-money deal, Fox was unable to do it paying more than half the 
money. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every loser says the winner overpaid and every winner says  
they'll make money,'' Goren said. ``If they are going to make money 
off this package, it'll take some creative accounting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although ABC-ESPN won't have the benefit of Gretzky or Mario  
Lemieux, new rule changes should make the game more appealing on 
television. 
</P>
<P>
	A four-on-four overtime where the loser receives one point will  
add scoring chances and aggressive play. And players can now be in 
the crease as long as they don't interfere with the goaltender. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a lot of new things,'' said John Davidson, the  
former Fox lead analyst who switch to the studio show with ABC. 
``The four-on-four in overtime and the crease change -- I like it so 
far. From what it seems to me, it looks like the players are going 
for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *FINALE?:* Could Chris Berman have broadcast his last regular  
season major league baseball game on ESPN? 
</P>
<P>
	He doesn't think so.  
</P>
<P>
	With the two entities in a dispute now in court because ESPN has  
televised late-season baseball games on ESPN2 for the second 
straight season and put NFL games on ESPN, the future of the 
baseball's regular season package are up in the air. 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball terminated the deal earlier this year, and a trial is  
scheduled for November. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've thought about it, but not very much,'' Berman said. ``I  
have thought that tonight's (Wednesday's) game could be my last, 
but hopefully we can work it out. The higher-ups at baseball know 
deep down that ESPN is best for baseball and baseball is best for 
ESPN.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *REPLACEMENT PROGRAMMING:* After losing pro football two years  
ago, NBC has had to scramble for replacement sports programming 
during the NFL season. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest certainly won't grab the ratings of a pro football  
game -- not even an exhibition. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC's inaugural ``Gravity Games,'' which comes along five years  
after ESPN's X Games debuted, airs for five consecutive Sunday's 
beginning this week at 4 p.m. EDT. It was taped in September. 
</P>
<P>
	``We saw what they had done and realized we weren't reaching the  
young audience we needed,'' said John Miller, NBC senior vice 
president of programming. ``We've got a multiyear commitment to the 
event.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	TUBE BITS:@ Marv Albert makes his return to NBC Saturday at 1:30  
p.m. EDT when he co-hosts the Basketball Hall of Fame enshrinement 
ceremony. ``I don't look at it as dramatic. It's been helpful to do 
it step-by-step and I'm very thankful that it's all moved back into 
place so nicely,'' Albert said. ... Chris Myers had reconstructive 
knee surgery after being injured in a touch football game, but 
still worked as host of Fox Sports Net's Sunday ``NFL This 
Morning.'' ... Fox Sports Net has passed on televising the 
Outrigger Hotels Rainbow Classic holiday college basketball 
tournament, which had been broadcast on ESPN for the past four 
years. ... CNBC's weekly edition of ``The Olympic Show'' will 
feature NBC Olympic host Bob Costas Saturday at 7:30 p.m. EDT. 
  	   	
</P>
