<DOCNO> APW19990930.0326 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 17:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Caps' GM McPhee Suspended, Fined </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- For picking a fight at the other team's  
dressing room, Washington Capitals general manager George McPhee 
ended up with a cast on his right thumb, a ripped suit, a $20,000 
fine -- and a one-month suspension. 
</P>
<P>
	McPhee was fined and suspended until Nov. 1 by the NHL on  
Thursday, barring him from games and practices and any business on 
behalf of the Capitals for the first 10 games of the regular 
season. He is believed to be the first NHL general manger ever 
suspended for fighting. 
</P>
<P>
	The fight occurred when McPhee, upset that Chicago had used a  
lineup of brawlers in a fight-filled Sept. 25 game at Columbus, 
Ohio, confronted Blackhawks coach Lorne Molleken. 
</P>
<P>
	``At least two things are clear,'' NHL commissioner Gary  
Bettman, who held a hearing with McPhee on Wednesday, said in a 
statement. ``First, Mr. McPhee made a deliberate decision to 
proceed to the Chicago Blackhawks dressing room area immediately 
following the conclusion of the game with the intention of 
confronting coach Molleken. 
</P>
<P>
	``Second, after a heated verbal exchange, Mr. McPhee punched  
coach Molleken.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McPhee was then surrounded and punched by Blackhawks players.  
The arm of McPhee's suit was torn, and police had to intervene to 
stop the melee. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both the decision to confront Mr. Molleken in the Blackhawks  
dressing room area and the physical contact which resulted from 
that confrontation were clearly improper and, I find, constituted 
conduct which was prejudicial to and against the welfare of the 
league and the game of hockey,'' Bettman said. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one, especially an NHL club executive or general manager,  
is free, even in the emotion of the moment, to engage in conduct 
that is clearly inappropriate. Actions such as those engaged here 
by Mr. McPhee will not be tolerated in the NHL.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McPhee's duties over the next month will be handled by several  
Capitals officials, with director of hockey operations Shawn 
Simpson acting as the point of contact with other teams on issues 
such as trades. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe the decision is harsh, but I understand the  
commissioner's rationale,'' McPhee said. ``This kind of conduct can 
never happen again in this league. Being involved in a physical 
confrontation is unprofessional, undignified and I am sorry that it 
ever happened. I however can never regret standing up for the 
Washington Capitals for what is right in the game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Washington coach Ron Wilson was fined $5,000 and  
Chicago owner Bill Wirtz was fined $3,000 for violating a gag order 
by making comments about the fight when the league was conducting 
its investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blackhawks issued a statement saying it disagreed with  
Bettman's action. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dollars cannot be the determining factor in instances of  
vigilantism,'' the statement read. ``A more appropriate method is 
censure ... by vote of the National Hockey League Board of 
Governors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The league took no action against the Blackhawks, who had  
several fight-plagued exhibition games. McPhee telephoned Chicago 
general manager Bob Murray several days before the game, asking 
that the Blackhawks use the lineup with more skill players. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, the league suspended Chicago defenseman Dave  
Manson for one game for drawing a match penalty for attempting to 
injure Washington's Steve Konowalchuk. 
</P>
<P>
	McPhee was given full support by the Capitals organization.  
</P>
<P>
	``He's our guy,'' team president Dick Patrick said. ``He has a  
passion for hockey, and part of that passion apparently spilled 
over here.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0327 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 20:50:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Rise / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar was higher against the yen at midday  
Friday ahead of the release of a central bank survey. Tokyo stocks 
rose as Japan's jobless rate improved. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 105.75 yen, up 0.09 yen from late Thursday in  
Tokyo but below its late New York level of 106.77 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 176.80 points,  
or 1 percent, to close the morning session at 17,782.26. On 
Thursday, the average climbed 323.18 points, or 1.87 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, traders were largely focused on the Bank  
of Japan's quarterly survey of business sentiment, due out Monday. 
Lingering worries by traders over an accident at a nuclear plant 70 
miles north of Tokyo on Thursday had largely subsided. 
</P>
<P>
	An accidental nuclear reaction at a uranium processing plant was  
contained early Friday, nearly a full day after a leak of 
radioactive gas seriously injured three workers and possibly 
contaminated 34 others. 
</P>
<P>
	Regarding the Bank of Japan's upcoming Tankan survey, economists  
surveyed by Dow Jones Newswires forecast it will show confidence at 
large manufacturers will have improved from the last survey three 
months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey is a widely watched indicator of Japan's economy.  
Hopes for a recovery from Japan's worst downturn in 50 years have 
been a major factor behind the yen's rally since May. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders also watched the central bank for further signs of a  
change in the central bank's monetary policy amid the yen's recent 
strength. 
</P>
<P>
	They are focused on whether the Bank of Japan is prepared to  
boost market liquidity to help strengthen the yen. Japanese 
officials said during last weekend's Group-of-Seven meeting that 
they were prepared to do just that if yen strength continued. 
</P>
<P>
	Monetary easing could weaken the yen against the U.S. currency.  
Japan fears that a strong yen could derail its recovery from 
recession by making exports more expensive abroad. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 113.14 yen, up from  
112.24 yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices jumped following news Japan's  
unemployment rate for August improved from the previous month, 
spurring further optimism over the country's budding economic 
recovery. 
</P>
<P>
	The jobless rate fell to 4.7 percent from July's record high 4.9  
percent, the government announced. 
</P>
<P>
	The nuclear accident was having little impact on the overall  
market, helped by the yen's steadiness against the dollar and 
continued hopes for an economic recovery in Japan, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York on Thursday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose  
123.47 points, or 1.2 percent, to 10,336.95. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 5.03 points, or 0.33 percent, to 1,501.80. 
The TOPIX closed up 91 points, or 2.39 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell  
to 1.7000 percent from Thursday's finish of 1.7100 percent. Its 
price rose 0.09 point to 100.00. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
