<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Armored Car Robbery Man Sentenced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- A man has been sentenced to five months  
in prison and five months of house arrest for his role in the $17 
million Loomis, Fargo &AMP; Co. robbery. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Court Judge Graham Mullen, who sentenced Mike  
Goodman on Wednesday, said he would recommend that he be allowed to 
serve the time under work-release. Goodman also was sentenced to 
two years' probation. 
</P>
<P>
	Goodman, 28, and his wife, Kim, each pleaded guilty in March to  
one count of money laundering for their role in the 1997 robbery of 
a vault at the armored car company -- one of the biggest heists of 
its kind in U.S. history. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors say the couple received $10,000 to help Michele  
Chambers convert $200,000 in cash into a bank check at a First 
Union branch where Mrs. Goodman worked. Mrs. Chambers is the wife 
of Steven Chambers, one of the heist's ringleaders. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank check helped the Chamberses buy a $635,000 house in the  
weeks after the heist in Charlotte. 
</P>
<P>
	Chambers is serving an 11-year sentence for money laundering,  
bank larceny and conspiracy to commit murder-for-hire. His wife was 
sentenced earlier this week to more seven years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	All but one of the 21 defendants in the robbery of the Loomis,  
Fargo vault pleaded guilty. The other one went to trial and was 
convicted. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 11:10:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Thursday, Sept. 30, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Earthquake Rocks Southern Mexico  
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A strong earthquake rocked southern Mexico  
today, causing buildings to sway in the capital for several 
minutes. There were reports that at least some people were injured 
when homes collapsed in the southern state of Oaxaca. Mexican 
television quoted local seismologists as saying the quake had a 
preliminary magnitude of 7.4. The U.S. Geological Survey in Golden, 
Colo. said the magnitude was 7.5. The quake was 35 miles 
north-northwest of Puerto Angel, a Pacific coast city in Oaxaca. 
The state capital, Oaxaca City, is a popular tourist destination. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Signs Spending Resolution  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today signed a resolution to  
keep federal agencies financed for the next three weeks, ``not 
because I wanted to but because it was the only way to avoid 
another government shutdown.'' He accused the Republican Congress 
of resorting to ``gimmicks and gamesmanship'' instead of meeting 
the Oct. 1 deadline for passage of the appropriations bills that 
finance the government. The resolution extends funding until Oct. 
21. 

</P>
<P>
	Pentagon To Look at Korea Killings  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Defense Secretary William Cohen said today the  
Pentagon will look at any ``substantive information'' on the 
account of mass killings of South Korean civilians by U.S. soldiers 
early in the Korean war and President Clinton said Cohen ``wants to 
get to the bottom of it.'' Clinton said he was briefed on The 
Associated Press report today. Accounts of South Korean villagers 
and of a dozen ex-GIs who either witnessed or were involved in the 
killings were reported by the AP yesterday. Sandy Berger, Clinton's 
national security adviser, called the report ``obviously deeply 
troubling.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Workers Hurt at Japan Uranium Plant  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- A major leak at a uranium-processing plant in  
central Japan today sent radiation levels skyrocketing. Three 
workers were hospitalized -- two in critical condition -- and 11 
others were contaminated. Fears remain of a possible continued 
nuclear reaction at the plant. The government's top spokesman 
called the accident ``unprecedented.'' About 150 people were 
evacuated from the town of Tokaimura, 70 miles northeast of Tokyo. 
More than 310,000 people were ordered not to leave their homes and 
officials shut down schools and train service in the region. 

</P>
<P>
	Bradley Outraises Gore in Quarter  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Bill Bradley, his Democratic presidential  
campaign surging, raised more money than Vice President Al Gore 
over the last three months, and has more money in the bank heading 
into the final quarter of the year. On the Republican side, Texas 
Gov. George W. Bush continued to shatter fund-raising records, 
reporting raising more than $56 million through the end of 
September. He has about $37 million cash on hand. Bradley raised an 
estimated $6.7 million between July and September, a spokeswoman 
said today. Gore raised around $6.5 million during the same period, 
according to senior advisers. 

</P>
<P>
	Pinochet Judgment Scheduled  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Gen. Augusto Pinochet's extradition hearing ended  
today, and a London magistrate will rule Oct. 8 on whether the 
former Chilean dictator should be sent to Spain to face charges of 
torture. Pinochet, who remained under police guard at a rented 
mansion west of London during the four-day hearing, is supposed to 
attend Bow Street Magistrate's Court for the judgment by Deputy 
Chief Magistrate Ronald Bartle. An official Chilean government 
report said 3,197 people were killed or disappeared after Pinochet 
toppled elected Marxist President Salvador Allende in a bloody 1973 
coup. 

</P>
<P>
	IMF Head Warns Against Complacency  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Future global financial crises can be avoided  
if governments show determination to avoid complacency, Michel 
Camdessus, the head of the International Monetary Fund, said today. 
``We will be making a grave error if we let the return of relative 
calm in financial markets and the improvement in world growth 
prospects lead us to believe that further reforms are not 
necessary,'' Camdessus said. Camdessus spoke at the closing session 
of this year's IMF-World Bank meetings. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Rises 84; Nasdaq Gains 13  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 2 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 84.21 points at 10,297.69. Advancers on the New York Stock 
Exchange led decliners 1,611-1,274. The Nasdaq composite index was 
up 13.83 at 2,744.10. 

</P>
<P>
	Stockton, Hornacek Sign With Jazz  
</P>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- John Stockton and Jeff Hornacek have new  
contracts with the Utah Jazz. Kevin O'Connor, Utah's vice president 
for basketball operations, confirmed the signings and said the team 
planned a news conference for 3 p.m. EDT today. Stockton has agreed 
to a two-year deal worth $22 million, The Salt Lake Tribune 
reported. Hornacek will have a one-year, $5.2 million contract. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
