<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Vitamin Co. To Plead Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Canadian company agreed Wednesday to plead  
guilty and pay a $5 million criminal fine for its role in an 
international conspiracy to fix prices on vitamin B-4. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department said the agreement is part of its ongoing  
investigation into a global conspiracy to rig prices for certain 
vitamins. 
</P>
<P>
	Chinook Group Limited of Toronto was accused of conspiring with  
other businesses to raise and fix prices for vitamin B4 in the 
United States and other countries from January 1988 through 
September 1998. The Justice Department said Chinook also conspired 
to divide the market for the vitamin during that time. 
</P>
<P>
	Vitamin B-4 is used primarily in animal feed.  
</P>
<P>
	Joel Klein, Justice's antitrust chief, said the case shows the  
government's ``continuing resolve to thwart illegal activities that 
harm American businesses and consumers, regardless of the location 
of the culprit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The one-count criminal case was filed in U.S. District Court in  
Dallas. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0334 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 23:20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former NBA Star Out as Women's Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INGLEWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- Orlando Woolridge is leaving as coach  
of the Los Angeles Sparks of the WNBA in a parting the team said 
was ``amicable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under Woolridge in 1999, the Sparks had best record in their  
three WNBA seasons, 20-12, and lost to eventual league champion 
Houston two games to one in the Western Conference finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Woolridge was third in the WNBA's Coach of the Year voting,  
behind Van Chancellor of Houston and Sonny Allen of Sacramento -- a 
team the Sparks ousted in the playoffs' first round. 
</P>
<P>
	Woolridge was an assistant coach for his first 1 1/2 seasons with  
the Sparks and interim coach at the tail end of a 12-18 1998 
season. He declined to comment on the reasons for his departure. 
Team president and interim general manager Johnny Buss was not 
available to comment, a team spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Sparks are confident in the new direction in which the  
team is headed and would like to thank Woolridge for his efforts 
over the past 2 1/2 seasons,'' the Sparks' statement said. ``The 
search for a new coach will begin immediately.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first former NBA player to become a WNBA coach, Woolridge  
played 13 NBA seasons with Chicago, Detroit, Philadelphia and the 
Los Angeles Lakers. 
</P>
<P>
	He entered coaching as an assistant to the girls' coach at a Los  
Angeles private school in 1996-97, and joined the Sparks as an 
assistant in mid-1997. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0335 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 18:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Signs Spending Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Beset by internal disputes and veto threats,  
Congress left most of its spending work unfinished Thursday as the 
government closed the books on the 1999 fiscal year. President 
Clinton denounced a plan to save money by slowing income-support 
payments to millions of working poor families. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let me be clear: I will not sign a bill that turns its back on  
these hardworking families,'' Clinton said at the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Minutes earlier, he signed legislation keeping agencies open  
through Oct. 21, giving the two sides more time to battle over 
issues ranging from schools to foreign aid. Just four of the 13 
annual spending bills were signed into law before the fiscal year 
began Friday. One has been vetoed and five others face veto 
threats. 
</P>
<P>
	One legislative deadlock was broken when House and Senate  
conferees finally agreed on a $8.7 billion farm relief package 
after dropping a provision that would have eased the embargo on 
trade with Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of the action in the Capitol centered on legislation  
financing labor, health and education programs, the biggest 
spending measure of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate spent a second, desultory day debating its $324  
billion measure. Though Democrats successfully won extra spending 
for social services and child care, the bill still faced a veto 
threat because of cuts in Clinton's proposals for hiring teachers 
and other efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	The most controversial action was in the House Appropriations  
Committee, which used a near party-line 33-26 vote to approve its 
$316 billion version of the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	But first, Republicans used a party-line 32-27 tally to approve  
a plan aimed at letting them redeem their pledge of passing 
spending bills without dipping into Social Security. 
</P>
<P>
	The GOP proposal would spread out over 12 months what has  
historically been a lump sum payment to most low-income working 
poor under a program known as the earned income tax credit. 
</P>
<P>
	Campaigning in California for the GOP presidential nomination,  
Texas Governor George Bush said, ``I don't think they ought to 
balance their budget on the backs of the poor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Amid Bush's remark and opposition from some Republicans in the  
House and Senate, one GOP official, speaking on condition of 
anonymity, said they might seek other savings options to avoid 
political damage. But others said they would stick with the delayed 
payments. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., read Bush's comments aloud to the  
Appropriations Committee, drawing hoots from Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., while not taking direct  
issue with Bush's comments, said, ``We don't use it (the money), we 
just spread it out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That budgetary sleight-of-hand would produce $8.7 billion in  
savings in fiscal 2000. That is because with monthly payments, much 
of next year's funds would instead be paid out after Oct. 1, 2000 -- 
the start of fiscal 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	The 24-year-old tax credit program is designed to help 20  
million low-income people avoid becoming welfare recipients. The 
credit averages $1,890 annually for families with children, and 
should cost nearly $32 billion next year, the Treasury Department 
estimates. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the three-week truce that became effective with  
Clinton's signature on the continuing resolution, the tone was 
combative on both sides as each sensed a brewing spending battle 
that could reverberate through next year's elections. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. and Mrs. America, President Clinton is using your Social  
Security card as his personal credit card for more government 
spending,'' House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, told a news 
conference, continuing the GOP drive to position itself as the 
defender of the pension program. 
</P>
<P>
	Firing back, House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., said  
the GOP plan to delay support payments for the poor ``is probably 
the most cynical and cruel of the suggestions or gimmicks that 
they've made.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two sides warred all day over Social Security.  
</P>
<P>
	Democrats trumpeted a letter from the Congressional Budget  
Office, Congress' nonpartisan budget scorekeeper, saying $18 
billion in Social Security surpluses would be spent under current 
GOP plans. Republicans waved a hurriedly produced CBO letter of 
their own stating that those surpluses would not be touched if 
Congress sticks to a spending target GOP leaders have set for final 
versions of their bills. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans also pushed nearly $350 million in other savings  
through the House Appropriations panel from raising fees for direct 
student loans and eliminating a rebate the Federal Housing 
Administration gives some of its low-income borrowers. 
</P>
<P>
	They also abandoned an earlier proposal to reclaim $3 billion in  
unspent federal welfare funds from the states, a plan criticized by 
both GOP and Democratic governors. 
</P>
<P>
	By voice vote, the committee also added $515 million in aid  
proposed by Rep. David Price, D-N.C., for farmers hurt by the 
recent hurricanes Floyd and Dennis. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton signed the fourth spending bill Thursday, a $21 billion  
measure financing energy and water projects. He has also signed 
measures financing the Treasury Department, Congress' own 
operations and military construction projects. 
</P>
<P>
	The nine unfinished bills cover 12 Cabinet departments including  
Defense, Health and Human Services, Interior and Justice, plus 
dozens of smaller agencies. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0336 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 01:50:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                            *W.B. Gavin    	
</P>
<P>
	WENATCHEE, Wash. (AP) -- W.B. ``Babe'' Gavin, longtime owner and  
publisher of the Lake Chelan Mirror weekly newspaper, died 
Wednesday. He was 88. 
</P>
<P>
	Even after losing his right arm to cancer in 1970, Gavin  
continued to paste up news stories, develop pictures and set type. 
He also kept on driving a tractor in his apple orchard. 
</P>
<P>
	Gavin drove a laundry truck in Cashmere until the publisher of  
the Cashmere Valley Record hired him in 1932 to sell ads, write 
news and lay out the paper. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper business stuck. When the Lake Chelan Mirror in the  
town of Chelan was put up for sale in 1937, Gavin's boss helped him 
buy it. 
</P>
<P>
	Gavin married Margaret Laschinger in 1939, and the two operated  
the Mirror for more than 30 years before their son Rick Gavin 
became publisher in 1973. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include two sons, six grandchildren and one  
great-grandchild. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Ralph Hudson    	
</P>
<P>
	HARRISON, Ark. (AP) -- Former state Sen. Ralph Hudson, who  
entered politics after owning a grocery store and serving as a 
postmaster, died Tuesday. He was 96. 
</P>
<P>
	Hudson was elected a Boone County judge in 1955. He served four  
terms before being elected state senator, a position he held from 
1963 through 1972. 
</P>
<P>
	He also was chief executive and chairman of the board of  
Guaranty Savings &AMP; Loan before he retired in 1981. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Melvin Jones    	
</P>
<P>
	LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) -- Melvin Jones, vice chancellor for business  
at University of Nebraska-Lincoln, died Tuesday of a heart attack. 
He was 48. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones had oversight of all university services that support  
academic programs, including human resources, facilities, 
landscaping, custodial work, parking, police and mail. 
</P>
<P>
	Prior to coming to Lincoln, he was vice president for financial  
affairs and treasurer at Marquette University and director of the 
department of finance for the Government of the District of 
Columbia. 
</P>
<P>
	He also had oversight of the District of Columbia for the U.S.  
Senate and was vice president of Howard University, budget 
administrator for Iowa City, Iowa and an agent for the Internal 
Revenue Service. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Anneli Cahn Lax    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Anneli Cahn Lax, the editor of a series of  
textbooks aimed at making mathematics more accessible to the 
general reader, died Friday. She was 77. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Lax retired from New York University in 1992, where she  
taught for 31 years. In her dissertation at NYU, she made 
significant contributions to the theory of hyperbolic equations, 
which deals with the behavior of waves. 
</P>
<P>
	But she may be best known for her work toward improving the  
understanding of mathematics by both students and lay people as 
editor of the Mathematical Association of America's New 
Mathematical Library Series, which began in 1961. 
</P>
<P>
	Lax was a longtime active member of the New York Academy of  
Sciences and was instrumental in shaping its program for science 
education for children. Among the honors she won was an award for 
distinguished service to mathematics from the mathematical 
association. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Gustavo Leigh Guzman    	
</P>
<P>
	SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Air Force Gen. Gustavo Leigh Guzman, a  
key figure in the 1973 coup led by Gen. Augusto Pinochet, died 
Wednesday. He was 79. 
</P>
<P>
	Leigh was commander of the air force on Sept. 11, 1973, the day  
of the Pinochet-led coup that toppled Marxist President Salvador 
Allende. 
</P>
<P>
	Leigh quickly emerged as the toughest member in the four-man  
military junta. Just hours after the coup, Leigh vowed the military 
would ``eradicate the Marxist cancer from our fatherland, until the 
last consequences.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was on his personal orders, he disclosed later, that the air  
force bombarded and heavily damaged the presidential palace to put 
down the resistance by Allende and a small group of his followers. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1978, Leigh was the first junta member to urge the  
restoration of civilian rule. That cost him his position with both 
the junta and the air force. 
</P>
<P>
	Also that year, when Pinochet called a vote to request that  
Chileans reject the United Nation's condemnation of the regime's 
human rights record, Leigh called the move ``typical of governments 
in which power is in the hands of a single dictator.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two other members of the junta -- Adm. Jose Toribio Merino and  
police Gen. Cesar Mendoza -- have died. Pinochet remains under house 
arrest in Britain fighting extradition to Spain, where a judge 
wants to try him for the human rights abuses during his 17-year 
regime. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Jane Mosley    	
</P>
<P>
	CARY, N.C. (AP) -- Three-term state Rep. Jane Mosley, an advocate  
for transportation safety and health issues, died Tuesday night at 
the age of 54 after a nearly three-year battle with breast cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	During her illness, Mosley, a Democrat, became an advocate for  
breast cancer research and urged women in their 40s to have 
mammograms. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Edward W. O'Rourke    	
</P>
<P>
	PEORIA, Ill. (AP) -- Bishop Edward W. O'Rourke, retired leader of  
the Roman Catholic Diocese of Peoria, died Wednesday. He was 81. 
</P>
<P>
	He had a long history of health problems, including heart  
ailments and a stroke. 
</P>
<P>
	During his 55 years as a priest and bishop, he lectured on  
theological and socioeconomic issues and wrote six books. He was 
bishop of the local diocese from 1971 to 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	He also taught for 15 years at the University of Illinois and  
later became executive secretary of the National Catholic Rural 
Life Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	He suffered a stroke in 1985 and had heart and other ailments  
since then, but he remained active in church-related work. He 
founded Renaissance Stand, which helps the unemployed find jobs, 
soon after retiring. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Chester G. Starr    	
</P>
<P>
	ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) -- Ancient history expert Chester G. Starr,  
professor emeritus at the University of Michigan and author of more 
than 20 books, died Sept. 22. He was 84. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr was a fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences  
and wrote more than 20 scholarly books. He was founding president 
of the Association of Ancient Historians. 
</P>
<P>
	A native of Centralia, Mo., Starr earned bachelor's and master's  
degrees at the University of Missouri and a doctorate at Cornell 
University. He served as professor of history at the University of 
Illinois for 30 years before joining the Michigan faculty in 1970. 
</P>
<P>
	The regents said his ``virtuoso performances in the classroom  
and his evident delight in explaining the complexity and 
significance of ancient societies have captivated several 
generations of students.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Starr served with the U.S. Army from 1942-46. He was chief of  
the Historical Section with the Fifth Army in Italy, and attained 
the rank of lieutenant colonel. 

</P>
<P>
                         *John Richard Zieba    	
</P>
<P>
	CROWN POINT, Ind. (AP) -- John Richard Zieba, who twice escaped  
execution at the Auschwitz Nazi concentration camp, died Saturday 
after a long illness. He was 81. 
</P>
<P>
	After earning a master's degree in chemical engineering in 1939,  
Zieba was arrested by the Nazis for his involvement in the Polish 
Underground, a rebellion group that engaged in activities designed 
to disrupt the German occupation of Poland. 
</P>
<P>
	He was held at several Nazi concentration camps and was released  
in 1945 by German guards, who were ordered to kill all prisoners 
before the Allies advanced but did not. 
</P>
<P>
	After his release, Zieba moved to Germany, where he met his  
wife, Victoria Twarogowska. They were married on Aug. 7, 1946, and 
moved to the United States three years later. 
</P>
<P>
	They settled in Cleveland, where Zieba eventually went to work  
for the Robert Gair Co., which was later bought by the Continental 
Can Co. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1953, the company transferred Zieba to its Elkhart plant. He  
stayed there until 1960, when he went to work as a chemist at 
Whitehall Laboratories before retiring in 1980. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
