<HEADLINE> Bob Marley To Be Honored on Album </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) -- Lauryn Hill, Erykah Badu and  
Aerosmith's Steven Tyler are among the performers whose renditions 
of Bob Marley tunes will be in a new tribute album. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bob Marley: Chant Down Babylon'' will be released in November,  
Jamaica's Island Records said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The album, produced by Marley's son, Stephen, is a joint effort  
with Def Jam Records, a label better known for its hip-hop acts. 
The songs highlight the 1970s hits of Marley, known as ``The Gong'' 
in Jamaica. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hope it will make an impact in terms of the hip-hop  
world,'' Stephen Marley said. ``They need a spiritual icon like 
`The Gong' to get a different message.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hill, who will add a bluesy feel to ``Turn Your Lights Down  
Low,'' is married to another of Bob Marley's sons, Rohan. 
</P>
<P>
	Badu will sing ``No More Trouble,'' and Tyler will cover  
``Roots, Rock, Reggae'' from Marley's 1976 breakthrough album, 
``Rastaman Vibration.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
