<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-Cyberstalking Laws Mulled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Harassing someone via electronic mail could  
land a cyberstalker in jail under legislation being considered in 
the House. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, introduced by Rep. Sue Kelly, R-N.Y., would strengthen  
current federal law by broadening the definition of stalking to 
include harassment by e-mail, telephone or any other form of 
interstate communications. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, authorities could prosecute for threatening behavior even  
if no explicit threat is made. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because the current federal anti-stalking law is so narrow,  
many stalking victims have had nowhere to turn,'' Kelly said during 
a hearing of the House Judiciary Committee's crime subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	``Recent research has shown that more than 1 million women and  
more than 370,000 men are stalked every year. About 59 percent of 
women victims are stalked by spouses, former spouses, live-in 
partners or dates,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kelly said the bill was inspired by people like Jayne Hitchcock,  
a writer who has suffered more three years of harassment. 
</P>
<P>
	It began after the New York state attorney general's office  
began investigating her complaint about an apparently fraudulent 
literary agency that advertised on the Internet, Hitchcock told the 
panel. 
</P>
<P>
	Cyberstalkers ``e-mail bombed'' her, sending hundreds of e-mail  
messages and posting forged messages in Internet discussion groups 
over her name, one of which invited people to call or mail her 
their sexual fantasies to help her write a book. It included her 
real telephone number and home address in Crofton, Md. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt violated and scared for my life,'' she said. ``I began  
receiving 25 to 30 phone calls a day from as far away as Germany.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Police couldn't or wouldn't help, she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Friends familiar with e-mail traced the messages to three people  
apparently connected to the literary agency, and she filed a $10 
million civil suit against them, Hitchcock said. Then, her lawyer 
received a death threat, neighbors were phoned by people seeking 
information on her and complaints accusing Hitchcock of stalking 
were filed with federal and Maryland authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	``It got so bad I had to see a psychotherapist ... and finally  
my husband and I moved to New England,'' said Hitchcock. The suit 
is still pending, Hitchcock said. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Wednesday, advocates for abused women asked Congress to  
renew the Violence Against Women Act, a 1994 law that devoted 
federal money to fighting domestic violence. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no question that (the law) is making a difference,''  
said Bonnie Campbell, director of the Justice Department's Violence 
Against Women Office. Communities nationwide ``are setting up the 
infrastructure needed to improve our response to violence against 
women,'' she said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
