<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Paper Questioned on Taxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- The owner and publisher of one of  
South Korea's largest newspapers was questioned by prosecutors 
Thursday about allegations he evaded $23.2 million in taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Suk-hyun's questioning followed two weeks of investigation  
into the Bokwang Group, in which he is a major shareholder. Hong's 
newspaper, The JoongAng Ilbo, was not directly involved in the 
alleged tax evasion scheme. 
</P>
<P>
	The prosecution's probe was prompted by a National Tax  
Administration complaint that Hong was suspected of being 
personally involved in the tax evasion. 
</P>
<P>
	If found guilty, Hong could face at least five years in prison.  
</P>
<P>
	Hong's newspaper, with an estimated circulation of 1.8 million,  
said the investigation was retaliation for its critical stance 
against the government. 
</P>
<P>
	``We consider this investigation to have targeted a specific  
news organization. It is a political conspiracy designed to stifle 
the free expression of opinions,'' JoongAng reporters said in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The Paris-based World Association of Newspapers, which  
represents some 17,000 publications in 93 countries, sent a letter 
to President Kim Dae-jung on Thursday, protesting Hong's 
questioning. 
</P>
<P>
	Any punitive action against Hong ``will inevitably damage the  
credibility of your commitment to establish a full democracy in 
South Korea, in the eyes of the international community,'' the 
letter said. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no immediate government response.  
</P>
<P>
	The National Tax Administration's complaint said that Bokwang  
opened more than 1,100 bank accounts under false or borrowed names 
to evade business and inheritance taxes for Hong and his family, 
mostly between 1996 and 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong also was suspected of involvement in large-scale land  
speculation. 
</P>
<P>
	Bokwang Group has four subsidiaries specialized in  
convenience-store chains, TV component manufacturing, 
communications and finance. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
