<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 16:40:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> W. Virginia To Play All Road Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MORGANTOWN, W.Va. (AP) -- The Mountaineers will play every game  
of the 1999-00 basketball season on a foreign court while West 
Virginia administrators try to resolve potential problems with 
asbestos in the Coliseum. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine of West Virginia's 18 home games will be played at the  
12,000-seat Charleston Civic Center instead of the 14,000-seat 
Coliseum. Six will be held at the 7,000-seat Wheeling Civic Center 
and three at the 4,000-seat Feaster Center at Fairmont State 
College. 
</P>
<P>
	Average attendance for men's home basketball games is about  
8,000, athletic director Ed Pastilong said. 
</P>
<P>
	Women's home games will be held at the 2,000-seat Morgantown  
High School. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Gale Catlett didn't attend the news conference held to  
announce the new schedule, and Pastilong was vague about how he 
took word of the disruption. 
</P>
<P>
	``Coach Catlett realizes it'll be a little bit of a disadvantage  
playing all of your games away, but he's very competitive,'' 
Pastilong said. ``Sometimes adversity brings out the best in 
people. We're hoping that will be the case here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	West Virginia will move volleyball and wrestling matches to the  
Shell Building on campus. Athletic officials are still deciding 
where to hold gymnastics meets. 
</P>
<P>
	University officials are working with the U.S. Environmental  
Protection Agency to develop a testing plan to find out whether 
asbestos levels in the air inside the Coliseum are dangerous. 
</P>
<P>
	Asbestos was applied to the bottom of the arena's ceiling in  
1969 to limit condensation and muffle noise. The adhesive holding 
the asbestos in place is now weakening, causing chunks of it to 
fall into seats. 
</P>
<P>
	The building's outer ring, where classrooms and offices are  
located, remains open because its air system functions 
independently of the arena. 
</P>
<P>
	West Virginia plans to remove the asbestos from the Coliseum  
next spring unless the EPA forces it to do so sooner. The work 
should take about six months and cost some $15 million, according 
to Scott Kelley, vice president for administration and finance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
