<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grain Futures Plummet; Gold Lower  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Grain futures prices plummeted Thursday on the Chicago Board of  
Trade as the government released estimates of supplies that were 
higher than traders expected. 
</P>
<P>
	In other commodity markets, orange juice futures fell, and gold  
gave back some of its recent major gains. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures fell in reaction to the release Thursday of  
government estimates that stockpiles would be 1.796 billion 
bushels, about 100 million bushels more than anticipated, market 
participants said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was bigger than the trade was looking for, surprisingly  
so,'' said Don Roose, president of Iowa-based U.S. Commodities Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Also hurting corn prices were an improvement in harvest  
conditions this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures also plummeted on estimates that quarterly stocks  
were much larger than expected. Roose said the growth in corn and 
wheat stocks reflect weakening export demand and a serious decline 
in feed use. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean futures fell in sympathy with corn and wheat, but losses  
were limited by stock estimates that were down slightly. 
</P>
<P>
	In trading Thursday, wheat for December delivery fell 8 1/2 cents  
to $2.75 3/4 a bushel; December corn fell 5 1/2 cents to $2.08 1/4 a bushel; 
December oats fell 2 cents to $1.13 1/4 a bushel; and November 
soybeans fell 1/2 cent to $4.91 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, cattle futures prices were higher in trading on the  
Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while pork futures were mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle futures were up 0.97 cent to 68.27 cents a  
pound; October feeder cattle rose 1.17 cent to 81.07 cents a pound; 
October lean hogs fell 0.43 cent to 48.97 cents a pound; and 
February pork bellies fell 0.42 cent to 63.80 cents a pound. 
</P>
<P>
	Frozen concentrated orange juice futures prices fell to a  
six-week low in heavy trading Thursday on the Board of Trade of the 
City of New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The market has given back gains made last month when prices  
soared more than 20 percent on a bullish crop estimate report. 
</P>
<P>
	Orange juice is expected to trade in a tight range ahead of the  
U.S, Department of Agriculture's Oct. 8 release of its first 
Florida crop estimate. 
</P>
<P>
	November orange juice fell 3.00 cents to 87.50 cents per pound.  
</P>
<P>
	Gold futures gave back recent gains in trading Thursday on the  
New York Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold reached $300 an ounce this week, but then the nearby  
contracts fell back below that mark Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold's frenzied price rally earlier in the week stalled late  
Wednesday and the decline spilled over into Thursday. Prices had 
spiraled as high as $329 Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold was driven down by news that Russia may place 7.3 million  
ounces with Western banks, enabling it to be lent to the market. 
Market participants also believe the market was simply readjusting 
after the recent highs. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold for October delivery fell $1.10 to $299.50 per ounce.  
</P>
<P>
	Palladium followed gold lower Thursday, giving back gains it  
posted the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	Palladium for December delivery fell $22.85 to $369.00 per  
ounce. 
</P>
<P>
	Palladium is used heavily in the automotive industry in the  
manufacture of emission-control devices. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
