<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stockton, Hornacek Sign With Jazz </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- John Stockton and Jeff Hornacek will  
return to take another shot at winning an NBA title, eager to give 
the Utah Jazz as much time as their aging bodies allow. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jazz on Thursday announced that Stockton, 37, signed a  
two-year contract and Hornacek, 36, agreed to a one-year deal. 
</P>
<P>
	It remains to be seen whether the oldest backcourt in the NBA  
can lead Utah back to the NBA Finals, in which Utah lost in 1997 
and 1998. Both players made it clear they're coming back to pursue 
the title. 
</P>
<P>
	``You go for it. You're always trying to win a championship,''  
Hornacek said when asked if this season marks his last chance. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms weren't disclosed for either contract. Published reports  
say Stockton, the NBA's career leader in assists and steals, will 
be paid $22 million while Hornacek's deal is worth $5.2 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Jazz owner Larry Miller said during a news conference that he  
negotiated directly with the players, as he has done for years. 
Stockton said he was never concerned he wouldn't get a good deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was a lot of faith in each other,'' Stockton said. ``I  
really had a restful summer even though I was unemployed the whole 
time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, forward Karl Malone signed a four-year, $66.5  
million contract. With Stockton and Hornacek back, Utah is 
committed to the trio that took the team to the finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Malone turned 36 in July. Although the clock has been ticking on  
the Jazz for years, it's clear from the length of the Stockton and 
Hornacek contracts the stroke of midnight can't be too far away. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all realize this is coming to an end,'' Stockton said.  
</P>
<P>
	Miller said just as he rooted for John Elway to win the Super  
Bowl, he's hopeful that Malone, Stockton and Hornacek can win the 
NBA title before they retire. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're all important to the Jazz, to be sure, but also for  
what they mean to the game, these guys deserve to win a 
championship,'' Miller said. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem for all three, and for the Jazz, is age.  
</P>
<P>
	Stockton and Hornacek at times were defensive liabilities in  
last year's playoffs, being beaten off the dribble by quicker legs. 
The Jazz were eliminated in the second round after Malone shot 
3-of-16 from the floor in Game 6 against the younger Portland Trail 
Blazers. 
</P>
<P>
	Stockton had offseason surgery on an elbow and Hornacek  
underwent surgery to repair a chronically sore knee. Both declared 
themselves fit and said they're ready for training camp next week. 
</P>
<P>
	``As September rolls around, I can't speak for everyone, but I  
get excited to get back to work,'' Stockton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hornacek was expected to see fewer minutes than last season,  
splitting time with swingman Shandon Anderson. On Wednesday, 
Anderson signed a deal with the Houston Rockets, leaving the Jazz 
without a proven backup at shooting guard. 
</P>
<P>
	Hornacek said last weekend, when he was inducted into Iowa  
State's hall of fame, that this would be his last season. He hedged 
a little on Thursday but didn't recant. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully, we can win it this year,'' Hornacek said. ``In our  
talks, Larry said to play this season and just see what happens.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0344 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 13:40:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> LSU QB Booty Hopes To Reclaim Magic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BATON ROUGE,La. (AP) -- Five years ago, Josh Booty was the  
quarterback every college wanted, the guy Bill Walsh called the 
best high school QB he had ever seen. Now he's got the chance to 
prove he's still that player. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've waited a long time for this chance,'' Booty said. ``Now  
I'm going to make the most of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Booty, now a 24-year old sophomore, was USA Today's national  
high school football player of the year in 1993 in a class that 
included NFL passers Peyton Manning and Ryan Leaf. 
</P>
<P>
	He dazzled Walsh and others by throwing for 11,700 yards and 126  
touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	Booty also impressed baseball scouts with his ability to throw  
from home plate over an outfield fence 380 feet away. Eventually, 
the Florida Marlins impressed Booty with a $1.6 million deal to 
play baseball and he spent the next five years chasing that dream. 
</P>
<P>
	But baseball never worked out and Booty said he never stopped  
dreaming about LSU. This spring Booty repaid part of the money to 
the Marlins and walked on with LSU. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could have played for anybody when I left high school,''  
Booty said. ``I could have played with the team that won the 
national championship. But I wanted to come to LSU and help them 
win. I still do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Booty took classes in the spring and summer to qualify for  
football. He also spent hours in the weight room and learning the 
system. Still, he couldn't beat out fellow sophomores Craig Nall 
and Rohan Davey for the starting job. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I made those decisions, based on the information I had, I  
thought Craig was the right choice, Rohan was the right choice, and 
now Josh is the right choice,'' coach Gerry DiNardo said. ``For 
example, I had no way of knowing how Josh would react to having 58 
pass opportunities until he had them. When I was walking off the 
field after the last game, I had enough information to make a 
decision about all three of them and so I did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Davey crumbled against Auburn, however, Booty stepped in  
and demonstrated that his arm was still strong. Even though he 
couldn't prevent LSU's 41-7 loss, he showed some of the ability he 
had displayed in high school, setting an LSU record passing 58 
times for 29 completions and a touchdown. 
</P>
<P>
	``That did a lot for me. It was almost like playing two games  
right there, so I think it got rid of some of the rust,'' Booty 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	And if the whipping Auburn handed the Tigers did little to boost  
the confidence of a team trying to come back from a 4-7 season, it 
at least helped Booty, who's trying to shake off some bad baseball 
memories. 
</P>
<P>
	``Playing minor league baseball and struggling every day -- it  
doesn't get any worse than that,'' Booty said. ``It's tough when 
you have to go to the park every night. You might go two weeks in a 
row and go 1-for-28, get in a big time rut. I struggled in baseball 
a lot and went through some ups and downs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With an off week, Booty got extra time to work with the starters  
in preparing for Saturday's game against No. 10 Georgia. He expects 
to need every minute since Georgia's defense is the most 
complicated of any LSU opponent this season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bulldogs will probably take a page from Auburn's successful  
defense of LSU -- stop the running game and pressure an 
inexperienced quarterback. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I'm getting better as the days go on,'' Booty said.  
``I'm confident we're going to move the ball on Georgia. If we can 
establish a bit of a running game, we're going to do good.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beyond a strong arm, LSU is counting on Booty to bring maturity  
and leadership to the team. It's something Booty believes he can 
provide. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a whole different thing out on the field,'' Booty said.  
``I'm trying to lead by example. If I can move the team down the 
field and score, that's the best example I can give. 
</P>
<P>
	``The job is mine now. I'm confident that I'm going to go out  
there and play the way I always have. I going to play to win not 
just to not lose. I've waited too long for this to let it get by 
me.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0345 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 17:30:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Who's Watching Academic Fraud? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	No matter how it turns out, two useful lessons will come out of  
the growing flap at Tennessee regarding possible academic fraud: 
</P>
<P>
	1 -- The proper use of ``who'' and ``whom.'' That way, in the  
future, whenever an NCAA investigator asked, ``Who wrote this 
English paper for whom?'' a football player would know the correct 
response is, ``My tutor wrote it for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	2 -- Just how unofficial college football's ``unofficial''  
national championship is in danger of becoming. 
</P>
<P>
	The way things stand and always have, the team that wins the  
Sugar Bowl next Jan. 4 could be caught cheating red-handed on Jan. 
5 -- yet walk away with its share of $13 million intact and call 
itself the national champion until the end of time. 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe it's time to look at this.  
</P>
<P>
	The people who are supposed to be in charge of such things  
better do something and fast if the charges against Tennessee turn 
out to be true. Otherwise, the reward for cheating will continue to 
outweigh the risk of getting caught. 
</P>
<P>
	Most people assume the NCAA controls the Division I-A football  
postseason the same way it controls the postseason in every other 
sport. Never assume. The NCAA sanctions the bowls, but says it has 
no say when it comes to the hardware or cash handed over in the 
end. 
</P>
<P>
	The championship game is played on a rotating basis at one of  
four bowl sites -- Sugar, Orange, Rose, Fiesta -- and controlled by a 
handful of very powerful men who currently go by the moniker of the 
Bowl Championship Series. 
</P>
<P>
	There are polls, computer programs and printouts to be used as  
guides to determine who plays for the national championship, but 
the BCS has the last word about who plays in their other three 
bowls. 
</P>
<P>
	The BCS is headed by Roy Kramer, who happens to be the  
commissioner of the Southeastern Conference, which happens to have 
Tennessee as a member. This may sound like a conflict of interest, 
but as Kramer knows, it could happen to anybody. Especially in his 
circle. Kramer's partners in the BCS just happen to be the 
commissioners of the other five major football-playing conferences 
-- Pacific 10, Big Ten, Big 12, Big East, Atlantic Coast -- and a 
representative from Notre Dame, which is practically a conference 
unto-itself. 
</P>
<P>
	And this is where the ``unofficial'' part comes in.  
</P>
<P>
	If the charges against Tennessee, the national champion, turn  
out to be true, what's the worst that can happen? 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA has the power to do plenty -- but only after the fact.  
And because the BCS operates outside its jurisdiction, football is 
the one sport where the organization can't do anything about the 
``before'' part. 
</P>
<P>
	The University of Miami, for example, has felt the NCAA's sting.  
The Hurricanes are returning to national prominence this season, 
nearly five years after getting hit with three years' probation and 
the loss of 32 scholarships for violations committed during coach 
Dennis Erickson's watch. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami also won two of its four national titles during that span,  
but nobody took the money or the championships back. The UCLA 
women's softball team wasn't so lucky in 1997. The NCAA took back 
the national title the team won two years earlier, after finding 
multiple violations. 
</P>
<P>
	And should charges of tutor-student violations at Minnesota  
prove true, the NCAA could go after the victories and money the 
school collected in last spring's NCAA basketball tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	But football is another story.  
</P>
<P>
	NCAA spokesman Wally Renfro confirmed for the Los Angeles Times  
this week that his organization could not go after a football 
champion's purse or crown. ``As to whether the NCAA has any area of 
authority over the BCS champion, I don't believe the NCAA does.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kramer did not return a call Thursday seeking comment about  
whether the BCS would think about punishing teams caught cheating. 
</P>
<P>
	But his spokesman, Charles Bloom, who, like Kramer, is an  
employee of the SEC, told the newspaper, ``It's not one of those 
things that gets discussed: What if a previous champion has to 
forfeit games? What happens to the BCS trophy? I don't think that's 
been discussed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked when it might be, Bloom added, ``I don't know.''  
</P>
<P>
	Since it's going to be a long time before the best solution -- a  
playoff run by the NCAA -- is in place, here is something to 
consider in the interim. 
</P>
<P>
	Policing the football programs is the NCAA's job. It shouldn't  
be made any more difficult by the presence of the BCS. The two 
organizations should straighten out that jurisdictional matter. 
</P>
<P>
	Considering how lucrative the bowls have become, it's only a  
matter of time before we're stuck with a champion whose cheating 
was flagrant enough to warrant being stripped of a title. 
</P>
<P>
	It would be a shame if they got away with it because no one  
figured out who was supposed to be watching whom. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is the national sports columnist for The Associated  
Press. Write to him at jlitke@ap.org. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0346 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 12:06:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Giuliani Declares War on a Painting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- City officials have fired another round in their  
escalating fight with the Brooklyn Museum of Art, accusing the 
museum of displaying controversial work just to drive up its value. 
</P>
<P>
	The accusations made Wednesday by Deputy Mayor Joseph Lhota and  
the city's top lawyer, Michael Hess, came a day after the museum 
sued to stop Mayor Rudolph Giuliani from freezing its funding over 
the dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	Giuliani has threatened to cut city funding to the museum  
because of its decision to display an exhibit that includes a black 
Madonna decorated with elephant dung and pornographic cutouts. The 
funding amounts to $7 million, or about one-third of the museum's 
budget. 
</P>
<P>
	The pieces are from advertising executive Charles Saatchi's  
collection. Lhota and Hess say the museum's board planned the 
``Sensation'' exhibition so the works would fetch high prices at 
auction once the show closes. 
</P>
<P>
	The museum's board members are ``shilling for a British subject  
who is a multimillionaire and trying to enhance his art 
collection,'' Lhota said. 
</P>
<P>
	He cited a New York Observer article which said that after the  
show closed in London, Saatchi auctioned 128 pieces from his 
collection, many of them by artists in the show. 
</P>
<P>
	Giuliani, on a fund-raising trip in California, said he has been  
in touch with Lhota and Hess about their accusations. He said the 
project raises the question whether a publicly funded museum should 
engage in ``shock commercialization.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Andree Corroon, a spokeswoman for Christie's, which is helping  
sponsor the show, said the auction house had no plans for an 
auction. 
</P>
<P>
	``This bewildering accusation has absolutely no substance, is  
absolutely not true,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, the museum called the accusations ``preposterous  
and misleading.'' The show opens Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a federal judge has been asked to decide whether to  
restore the museum's funding. The museum sued the city on Tuesday, 
saying Giuliani's act violates the First Amendment. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, the Senate agreed unanimously Wednesday to a  
non-binding measure calling for the withholding of federal funds 
from the museum unless it cancels the exhibit. Independent Sen. Bob 
Smith of New Hampshire said the museum has received $500,000 from 
the National Endowment for the Arts in the last three years. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Wednesday, singer David Bowie -- who recorded an audio tour  
for museum visitors -- joined leaders of major New York City museums 
in support of the Brooklyn Museum. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sensation represents some of the best, worst but definitely  
most extreme of the high-profile work to have come out of Britain 
in the last 10 years or so,'' Bowie said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The leaders of two dozen cultural institutions -- including the  
Metropolitan Museum and the Museum of Modern Art -- signed a letter 
protesting the mayor's funding cut. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0347 </DOCNO>
