<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 08:30:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Under Attack, IOC Leaders Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- Under sharp attack from U.S. officials,  
leaders of the International Olympic Committee are meeting to press 
ahead with their anti-drug plans and decide how to deal with 
another vote-buying scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	As the IOC finalizes a series of reforms aimed at restoring its  
image and credibility, the issues of drugs and corruption have come 
back to the forefront and will play a major part in the IOC 
executive board meetings starting Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House and Congress have accused the IOC of failing to  
deal adequately with either issue, triggering a war of words that 
has plunged relations between the Olympic body and the United 
States to a low ebb. 
</P>
<P>
	Barry McCaffrey, the White House drug policy chief, recently  
launched a series of scathing attacks on the IOC and its plans to 
set up an international anti-drug agency. 
</P>
<P>
	McCaffrey has dismissed the IOC as a ``Byzantine'' organization,  
described president Juan Antonio Samaranch as a ``former fascist'' 
and even questioned the IOC's right to control the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC vice president Dick Pound sent a bluntly worded letter to  
McCaffrey last week telling him he was ``plainly wrong'' to 
criticize the anti-doping agency and should instead tackle the drug 
problem in American pro sports. Pound said the IOC will proceed 
with the drug agency with or without U.S. government support. 
</P>
<P>
	McCaffrey and other critics say the agency should be completely  
independent of the IOC. But the IOC, which is putting up $25 
million to start the project, says it has done more than any other 
organization to fight drugs and should continue to play a leading 
role. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC says the agency, which will coordinate drug testing  
around the world, including out-of-competition controls, has the 
backing of European governments, the United Nations and other 
bodies. It says the agency will be established by the end of the 
year and be fully operational for next year's Sydney Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what we promised the athletes of the world, and we are  
going to fulfill that promise,'' Anita DeFrantz, an American IOC 
vice president, said. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC also has been criticized by leading international sports  
officials for its proposed anti-doping code, which sets out drug 
rules and sanctions for Olympic sports. The document, scheduled to 
go into force Jan. 1, will be reviewed this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. John McCain, a vocal IOC critic who chaired hearings in  
April on Olympic corruption, has scheduled another hearing Oct. 20 
on the drug issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Six days earlier, the House will hold hearings into allegations  
that a ``culture of corruption'' surrounded Atlanta's winning bid 
for the 1996 Summer Games. 
</P>
<P>
	A report submitted to Congress this month detailed gifts, travel  
and offers of college scholarships, job assistance and other perks 
to IOC members and their families by Atlanta bid officials. U.S. 
Rep. Fred Upton, R-Mich., said the report showed ``votes were for 
sale'' and accused the IOC of creating the atmosphere which led to 
a pattern of corruption. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC board will decide how Samaranch should respond to a  
letter from Upton requesting him to testify at the hearing. The 
House commerce subcommittee has threatened to subpoena Samaranch if 
he declines to appear voluntarily. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch declined to testify at the McCain hearings in April  
prompted by the bribery scandal stemming from Salt Lake City's 
winning bid for the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC's new ethics commission said Monday it would investigate  
any misconduct by IOC members related to the Atlanta bid. 
</P>
<P>
	DeFrantz said critics like McCaffrey and members of Congress  
should take into account that the IOC has embarked on major 
reforms, expelled members who committed wrongdoing, opened its 
financial books and taken other steps to clean itself up. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've done a lot in this year,'' she said. ``That is what's  
important.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During the four days of meetings, the IOC board also will get  
progress reports from organizers of the Sydney, Salt Lake and 
Athens 2004 Summer Games. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
