<DOCNO> APW19990930.0349 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 17:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Steel Execs Urge Retention of Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Times are still tough for the steel industry  
and American manufacturers can't afford any weakening of trade 
barriers, top steel executives told Congress on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Import levels have eased from last year's record highs, but  
still haven't returned to where they were before the Asian economic 
crisis triggered a surge in arrivals of low-cost, foreign-made 
steel. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many of the forces behind the steel crisis remain,'' James  
Haeck, executive vice president of Cleveland-based LTV Corp., told 
the House and Senate steel caucuses. 
</P>
<P>
	``Foreign steel industries are more subsidized, more protected,  
and more cartelized than any other industrial sector,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	American steelmakers say the help other nations give their steel  
industries has built up more steelmaking capacity than the 
worldwide market needs. That makes it difficult for American 
companies to command the prices they desire, and led last year to 
five bankruptcies and an estimated 10,000 layoffs in the United 
States. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite Clinton administration assurances that it will oppose  
efforts to discuss anti-dumping laws during the next round of 
multination trade negotiations, the steel industry is nervous about 
what might happen during the World Trade Organization meeting in 
Seattle in November. 
</P>
<P>
	George Becker, president of the United Steelworkers of America,  
said the union intended to have a 500-person presence in Seattle 
during those talks. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, steel unions and 97 steel companies signed a joint  
letter to President Clinton underscoring their concern about 
preserving anti-dumping laws. 
</P>
<P>
	The steel industry used those laws to get punitive tariffs  
imposed against Japan for selling a common type of steel for less 
in the United States than in its home market. Japanese steelmakers 
have appealed to the U.S. Court of International Trade, and the 
Japanese government is considering a request by its labor unions to 
file a complaint against the United States with the World Trade 
Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this week, the Clinton administration announced it will  
hold a series of high-level talks with Japan about steel dumping. 
</P>
<P>
	The steel issue has been difficult for the Clinton  
administration, which was vilified by organized labor for fighting 
legislation to impose quotas on steel imports. 
</P>
<P>
	That anger could become a problem for Vice President Al Gore as  
he seeks union support for his presidential run. 
</P>
<P>
	Bethlemen Steel Chairman Curtis Barnette told reporters his  
industry is telling other segments of the U.S. economy ``It's steel 
today, it could be you tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The trade issue will be the No. 1 political issue in the 2000  
election,'' he said. ``In my view we should not underestimate the 
enormous public concern over what is happening in the trade area.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barnette spoke with reporters prior to a private meeting with  
White House Chief of Staff John Podesta. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0350 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 12:00:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jackson Lectures Media Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Concentration of media ownership in too  
few hands homogenizes the culture, the Rev. Jesse Jackson told 
broadcast news leaders from across the country Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson, who has called for Federal Communications Commission  
hearings on the effect of media mergers on minorities, said he is 
concerned the trend toward consolidation of ownership will leave 
too many stories untold. 
</P>
<P>
	``Too few people are calling too many shots,'' he said at the  
annual convention of the Radio and Television News Directors 
Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson was challenged by other members of a panel addressing  
the broadcasters. Erica Farber, publisher of the trade magazine 
Radio &AMP; Records, said consolidation in radio has had the opposite 
effect. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the industry is so much more willing to take on new  
ideas,'' she said. ``There's so much more diversity in formats than 
there was 10 years ago.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Pittman, president of America Online, and Michael  
Bloomberg, founder of the multimedia news service that bears his 
name, both noted how the Internet is allowing for many more voices 
in the media. 
</P>
<P>
	``Six months, two years from now, everyone is going to have  
their own radio and television station,'' Bloomberg said, ``and I'm 
not so sure that's a good thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson countered that the powerful media owners are much more  
able to drive the public agenda than would-be moguls. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the RTNDA teamed up with a few minority journalism  
groups to encourage radio and television stations to hire more 
minorities. The percentage of minorities in electronic newsrooms 
has slipped from a high of 21 percent three years ago to 19 percent 
now, the association said. 
</P>
<P>
	The organization steered clear of the question about minority  
ownership of the media. John Sears, RTNDA chairman, said his group 
will concentrate on what its members can control. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0351 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 07:50:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lycos Opens Web Site Aimed at Kids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- One of the Internet's most popular Web sites  
has opened a new virtual playground, one of a growing number of 
kid-friendly destinations aimed at reassuring parents anxious about 
their children roaming the Internet's seedier neighborhoods. 
</P>
<P>
	Lycos Inc. of Waltham, Mass., said it created www.lycoszone.com  
as a protected environment for children online. Except for its 
advertisements, all the links lead to other Web pages within the 
site. 
</P>
<P>
	The site, unveiled Wednesday, is among dozens of so-called green  
spaces being constructed as safe havens for children whose parents 
are worried about inadvertent exposure to pornography and other 
unsavory material found on the Internet alongside its educational 
and entertainment content. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can log in, spend all your online experience as a child in  
Lycos Zone, and as a parent you can feel pretty good,'' said Chief 
Executive Officer Robert J. Davis, who acknowledged that the 
Internet was ``a medium I'm not comfortable having my children do 
without guidance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis noted that other industries also offer ostensibly  
protected realms for children, such as the Nickelodeon cable 
television station and ``Sports Illustrated for Kids,'' the spinoff 
of the popular sports magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can predict with a pretty good degree of accuracy what  
you'll see there,'' Davis said. ``We're trying to do the same thing 
for kids online. We're recognizing there's a new and future 
audience out there. Someday the kids who are 8 and 10 and using 
this product will be 22 years old.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lycos, with $135.5 million in sales last year, is one of the  
Web's popular ``portal'' sites offering collections of news, 
entertainment, stock quotes and more. It was the fifth most popular 
site on the Internet with more than 2.4 million visitors daily, 
according to figures this month from Media Metrix Inc., an online 
ratings service. 
</P>
<P>
	Other kid-friendly sites include Yahoo!'s ``Yahooligans,'' The  
Walt Disney Co.'s ``Fun for Families,'' Netscape's ``KidZone'' and 
Headbone Interactive's ``Headbone Zone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	More Web sites with content geared toward children are listed on  
a site the online industry organized earlier this year, 
www.getnetwise.org. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a solution that's good for certain types of families  
and educators, and it can help parents understand how to let their 
kids use the Net in a safer way,'' said Ari Schwartz, a spokesman 
for the Washington-based Center for Democracy and Technology. The 
group helped organize the ``Get Net Wise'' site. 
</P>
<P>
	But Lycos' reliance on online advertising aimed at kids drew  
criticism about the site from the Center for Media Education, which 
successfully lobbied last year for a new federal law that prohibits 
Web sites from collecting information from children without 
parental permission. 
</P>
<P>
	``The idea that at the end of the day, we have to hide children  
inside gated communities to protect them is not the best way to 
ensure that online media serve the needs of children,'' said Jeff 
Chester, the group's executive director. 
</P>
<P>
	Chester suggested these new Web sites aimed at children were  
``part of a marketing strategy to urge parents to let down their 
guard while the online industry moves to begin aggressively selling 
to children.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lycos said all its advertisements on its Web site are clearly  
marked as ads, and it said no personal information -- such as names 
or e-mail addresses -- will be collected, even with parental 
permission. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990930.0352 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-30 07:40:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crashes With Older Drivers Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- While overall traffic deaths are declining,  
the number of older Americans involved in fatal crashes has jumped 
by 33 percent over the past decade, according to a new analysis of 
government data. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1998, Florida, home to many retirees, had the most drivers  
aged 70 and above who were involved in accidents with at least one 
fatality -- 474 such drivers, up 41 percent from the 1988 total of 
337. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas and California placed second last year, with 316 such  
drivers in each state. 
</P>
<P>
	Nationally, 4,934 older drivers were involved in fatal accidents  
in 1998, a 33 percent increase from the 1988 total of 3,716. 
</P>
<P>
	The Road Information Program, an advocacy group supported by  
construction and insurance groups, compiled the results from data 
released last month by the National Highway Traffic Safety 
Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	The group is asking for road improvements including better signs  
and lighting, especially with the baby boom generation heading 
toward retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	Recent federal research about older drivers indicates that the  
aging process causes reduced vision, slower reaction times, a loss 
of information-processing ability and reduced neck and upper body 
flexibility. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
