<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 5 Interviewed for Independent Counsel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Clinton supporters may be about to see the  
last of Kenneth Starr. But they may not like his replacement, 
either. 
</P>
<P>
	The judges who must appoint Starr's successor interviewed at  
least five prosecutors from his staff for the job Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the candidates were Hickman Ewing, who once drew up a  
draft indictment of Hillary Rodham Clinton, and Jay Apperson, who 
handled the recent prosecution in which longtime Clinton friend 
Webster Hubbell pleaded guilty to a felony and a misdemeanor. 
</P>
<P>
	Another of those interviewed for Starr's job, Ed Page, is  
handling the criminal investigation into possible false statements 
about Mrs. Clinton's role in the purge of the White House travel 
office. 
</P>
<P>
	But it is Ewing who is perhaps most familiar to the Clintons. He  
has questioned each of them repeatedly during the course of Starr's 
five-year criminal investigation. Testifying in the trial of Susan 
McDougal earlier this year on obstruction charges, Ewing said that 
at dinner one evening with other Starr staffers, he graded the 
president and first lady on their responses to questioning by 
Whitewater investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said the president was about a 'C' and Mrs. Clinton about an  
'F,''' Ewing testified. He said he made the statement after Mrs. 
Clinton said, ``'I don't recall' about 50 times'' during a 
deposition in July 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Ewing acknowledged that he had drawn up a draft indictment of  
Mrs. Clinton, a step he said is not unusual in prosecutors' offices 
as they try to assess the evidence for and against potential 
defendants. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's office must compile a final report on the overall  
investigation of the Clintons, dealing with Whitewater, the FBI 
files controversy and the handling of documents from the White 
House office of deputy counsel Vincent Foster after his death in 
1993, which has been ruled a suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's successor also will have to deal with the still-open  
investigation of possible obstruction in the testimony of 
presidential accuser Kathleen Willey in the Paula Jones sexual 
harassment lawsuit against the president. Mrs. Willey says 
President Clinton made an unwelcome sexual advance, an accusation 
the president denies. 
</P>
<P>
	According to courthouse employees, other candidates who were  
interviewed by the three-member panel of federal appeals court 
judges included: 
</P>
<P>
	--Mike Emmick, an assistant U.S. attorney who worked on the  
Monica Lewinsky investigation. Emmick was one of the prosecutors 
who tried to persuade Ms. Lewinsky to cooperate with Starr's office 
during a controversial daylong confrontation with the former White 
House intern in a hotel room. Starr's office was sharply criticized 
because the prosecutors discussed a possible immunity deal with Ms. 
Lewinsky without her attorney present. 
</P>
<P>
	--Paul Rosenzweig, who writes legal briefs for Starr's office and  
was the first prosecutor to receive word in January 1998 that a 
witness, who turned out to be Linda Tripp, had information for 
them. Rosenzweig got his information from a former law school 
classmate who was working behind the scene on the Paula Jones case. 
Clinton supporters seized Rosenzweig's role as support for their 
allegation that Starr's office was working in concert with Jones' 
legal team to hurt the president. 
</P>
<P>
	Page previously worked in another independent counsel's  
investigation of former Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros. Page 
handled the case against Cisneros' ex-girlfriend for lying about 
tape recordings she made of telephone conversations with former San 
Antonio mayor. 
</P>
<P>
	At Susan McDougal's trial last spring, Ewing was subpoenaed by  
Mrs. McDougal's lawyers in an effort to demonstrate that Starr's 
office wanted her to tell lies that would falsely implicate the 
Clintons in wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	Ewing as head of Starr's Little Rock office oversaw the  
examination of Mrs. Clinton's work as an Arkansas lawyer, including 
investigating the mysterious disappearance of her law firm billing 
records. 
</P>
<P>
	Those records showed up in the White House under  
still-unexplained circumstances two years after they had been 
subpoenaed by a grand jury. The records revealed that Mrs. Clinton 
had done legal work on one of her Whitewater partner's land 
development projects south of Little Rock that federal bank 
examiners found was riddled with fraudulent transactions. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's successful prosecutions of the Clintons' Whitewater  
partners and then-Arkansas Gov. Jim Guy Tucker dealt in large part 
with transactions at the land development where Mrs. Clinton had 
performed some legal work. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
