<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen: No New Info. of U.S. Killing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Defense Secretary William Cohen said today the  
Pentagon will look at any ``substantive information'' on claims of 
a mass killing of Korean civilians by U.S. soldiers during the 
Korean War, but he said he is not aware of any new information to 
support the claims. 
</P>
<P>
	Accounts of South Korean villagers and a dozen ex-GIs who either  
witnessed or were involved in the killings were reported by The 
Associated Press on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Sandy Berger, President Clinton's national security adviser,  
called the AP report ``obviously deeply troubling. I intend to 
discuss this with Defense Department officials to attempt to 
determine the truth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference in Jakarta today, Cohen said that ``to the  
degree that any substantive information is forthcoming, we 
certainly would look at it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He added, however, ``This has been examined on several occasions  
in the past and I am not aware that there is any information that 
would corroborate or support that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the Pentagon, spokesman Bryan Whitman said no further inquiry  
was immediately under way by the Defense Department as a result of 
the report. 
</P>
<P>
	The killings took place during three days in late July 1950, the  
American veterans said, when their Army battalion killed a large 
number of South Korean refugees beneath a railroad bridge at a 
hamlet called No Gun Ri. 
</P>
<P>
	With the soldiers' statements confirming much of their account,  
the Korean claimants called today for a U.S. investigation into the 
killings. 
</P>
<P>
	The Koreans have said in a series of petitions, including the  
latest one rejected in 1997 by the Korean government, that some 300 
refugees lay dead under the bridge's twin arches. About 100 others 
were killed in a preceding attack by U.S. Air Force planes, they 
say. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hope the U.S. government will meet our demands and console  
the wandering souls of those who died an unfair death,'' the 
claimants said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. military has said repeatedly it found no basis for the  
allegations. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, after the AP report was released, Pentagon  
spokesman P.J. Crowley said, ``We just have no information in 
historical files to lend any clarity to what might have happened in 
July 1950.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
