<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Election Officials Hold Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Election officials held a bipartisan  
conference from Iowa and New Hampshire on Thursday but failed to 
sort through a dispute over the lineup of caucuses and primaries 
that launch the presidential nominating season. 
</P>
<P>
	A meeting of a special commission that includes representatives  
of both parties in both states was scheduled for Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the years, those two states have developed an agreement  
where Iowa's leadoff caucuses take place eight days before New 
Hampshire holds the nation's first primary. 
</P>
<P>
	That was threatened this year when New Hampshire Secretary of  
State Bill Gardner announced that his state's primary would be Feb. 
1, the day after Iowa's caucuses, tentatively set for Jan. 31. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to try to resolve this issue,'' said Iowa  
Secretary of State Chet Culver. ``We're looking forward to having 
these discussions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republican and Democratic leaders in Iowa said they hoped to  
pressure Gardner into moving to Feb. 8, when most assumed the 
primary would be held. 
</P>
<P>
	Gardner said New Hampshire's date was not negotiable. ``We've  
got the calendar being printed,'' he said. ``It's going to be Feb. 
1.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Iowa officials said they'll continue to press, but point  
to a state law requiring that Iowa's caucuses be held eight days 
before another primary, holding out the possibility that the caucus 
date could again be changed. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are holding out hope, but we will do whatever it takes to  
remain the first caucus state,'' said Joe Shannahan, a spokesman 
for Gov. Tom Vilsack. 
</P>
<P>
	Culver said he was arranging a conference call between top  
Republicans and Democrats in Iowa and New Hampshire, hoping to sort 
through the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``Depending on what they say, we'll go to plan B,'' said Culver.  
``We have a state law, which we have to comply with, which says we 
have to go eight days before any other primary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the heart of the dispute is the heavy attention and campaign  
time given to states that launch the nominating process. Officials 
in Iowa and New Hampshire have banded together in past elections to 
ward off challenges from other states. 
</P>
<P>
	Seeking a slice of the limelight, a host of other states have  
moved their primary elections closer and closer to the beginning of 
the season, a ``frontloading'' that's reshaped presidential 
politics. 
</P>
<P>
	It's likely that both parties will have a nominee within six  
weeks of the opening of the nominating process, putting an 
extraordinary importance on money and name recognition. 
</P>
<P>
	Dee Stewart, executive director of the Iowa Republican Party,  
said continued negotiations are likely. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just think we need to continue to work,'' said Stewart.  
</P>
<P>
	Part of the reluctance to once again move the date of Iowa's  
caucuses is pure logistics. Officials in both parties must find 
sites for the caucuses in each of the state's more than 2,000 
precincts. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to convince them it's a serious problem,'' said  
Culver. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
