<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pizza Hut Buys Rocket Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- In an effort to send sales into a new orbit, Pizza  
Hut Inc. plans to put its new logo on a Russian rocket carrying a 
piece of the International Space Station. 
</P>
<P>
	The 30-foot ad will be slapped on a 200-foot Proton rocket  
scheduled for a mid-November launch from Russia's space city, 
Baikonur, Kazakhstan. The rocket will be carrying the space 
station's living quarters. 
</P>
<P>
	Pizza Hut chief executive officer Mike Rawlings said today the  
pizza chain is paying about half the price of a 30-second 
television ad during the Super Bowl -- currently up to $2.5 million 
-- for rights to put the ad on the rocket. He wouldn't be more 
precise. 
</P>
<P>
	Company officials plan to use the Proton launch as the  
centerpiece of a major space-oriented ad campaign, including 
commercials featuring the blastoff and in-store promotions. 
</P>
<P>
	Rawlings said Pizza Hut marketers first considered trying to put  
the updated logo -- the company's name beneath a red roof -- on the 
moon with lasers. 
</P>
<P>
	But, after consulting for two months with astronomers and  
physicists, they found that the image would have to be as big as 
Texas to be seen by earthlings more than 238,000 miles away. The 
project also would have cost hundreds of millions of dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	``So we found this opportunity that has so much credibility and  
so much excitement for people, and we're real excited about making 
it happen,'' Rawlings said. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not the first time an American company has paid the  
cash-starved Russian space program for an ad. PepsiCo Inc. paid $5 
million three years ago to have cosmonauts float a replica of a 
soda can outside the Mir space station. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russians have been pitchmen for other products as well and  
once gave a Japanese TV reporter a seat aboard a rocket for cash. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. law prevents advertisers from putting ads on American  
spacesuits, but the National Aeronautics and Space Administration 
is interested in working with private businesses to commercialize 
space. 
</P>
<P>
	The 41-year-old pizza chain is trying to overhaul and update its  
image by spending $500 million to modernize its restaurants with 
sleeker designs and higher ceilings. 
</P>
<P>
	Rawlings also has worked to improve the company's product with  
fresher pizza toppings. The new logo was another part of his plan. 
</P>
<P>
	``We decided that if we were going to launch this logo, to  
really launch it and find a big way to do it,'' he said. 





  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
