<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Party Loyalists Applaud Gore Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- From President Clinton on down, Democratic  
Party loyalists applauded Vice President Al Gore's latest campaign 
shakeup -- but with a relieved sigh that hinted, ``It's about 
time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some greeted with bemusement Thursday the vice president's  
almost prideful claim: ``I now am, in effect, the underdog.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Campaigning in New York, Gore said he will personally open his  
new Tennessee headquarters next Wednesday, ``and the campaign will 
arrive a few days after that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, asked about Gore's bombshell, told reporters at the  
White House that he and the vice president had long talked about 
Gore relocating and loosening up his personal campaign style. 
</P>
<P>
	The president suggested that he had pressed the changes because  
the same strategy worked for his Little Rock, Ark.-based campaign 
in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	``I suppose I think that because I had such a good experience  
when I stayed home, close to my roots. We discussed it a long time 
ago,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they were good decisions, and I think they'll get good  
results. And the most important thing is, he made them and he 
believes in them,'' the president added. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee Democratic Party Chairman Douglas A. Horne enthused  
that Gore made a ``great move'' that would relocate his operation 
to ``where the normal people are, and show the American people that 
Al Gore is now Al Gore only and not just doing President Clinton's 
business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Horne added, ``We would have liked for him to have done it even  
sooner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Begala, a veteran of the `92 Clinton-Gore campaign's Little  
Rock ``War Room,'' had also been pushing Gore for months to get out 
of Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``This shows me that Gore's on the side of bold action,'' Begala  
said. ``Al Gore has his mo-jo back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kathleen Sullivan, the state party chairwoman in New Hampshire,  
where Gore narrowly trails Bill Bradley in polls gauging the 
Democratic presidential nomination race, chuckled at Gore's newly 
adopted label. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, New Hampshire does have this reputation for going for  
the underdog,'' Sullivan said. ``I guess we have to wait and see 
who's the real underdog on Election Day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, Gore's backing by the party establishment -- 18  
senators, 19 former senators, 96 House members, 17 former House 
members, eight governors, eight former governors, 13 lieutenant 
governors and 241 mayors -- hardly jives with his claim to the 
underdog title. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, he scooped up endorsements from 750 CEOs and  
business leaders from across the country. 
</P>
<P>
	``Its kind of silly that he's calling himself the underdog,''  
said New Jersey Democratic Chairman Thomas Giblin, a Bradley 
supporter. ``He has the influence of the White House and a lot of 
the operatives of the Democratic National Committee working on his 
behalf.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said former Clinton adviser Dee Dee Myers: ``I'm not sure he  
needs to label himself an underdog. He can let other people do that 
for him'' 
</P>
<P>
	Campaign aides, meanwhile, scrambled over the logistics of  
uprooting Gore's multi-million-dollar headquarters from Washington 
-- where Gore's three floors of a downtown office building cost him 
$59,069 a month in rent -- for a more down-home Nashville operation 
at 1800 Church Street. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're moving it from K Street to the aisles of K-Mart,'' Gore  
beamed. 
</P>
<P>
	Campaign manager Craig Smith is leading the transition team, but  
he told his colleagues Thursday that he will not move to Tennessee 
because he has a young family in Washington that he does not want 
to leave behind. 
</P>
<P>
	No decision has been made on the future of the campaign manager  
spot, another Gore aide said. Others in Gore's senior staff 
remained undecided about the abrupt move South. 
</P>
<P>
	With some aides talking about a possible telecommute from their  
Washington homes, California Democratic consultant Bill Carrick 
sounded a warning: ``That will not work if they have war resisters 
staying behind the lines.'' 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
